{"title_page": "Rebecca Chin", "text_new": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Rebecca Chin\n| nickname = \n| image = Rebecca Chin rower in 2015.JPG\n| imagesize = \n| caption = Chin at the 2015 World Rowing Championships\n| nationality = \n| sport = [[Rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| event = \n| club = [[Agecroft Rowing Club]]\n| coach = Hamish Burrell<br> Robin Williams\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1991|12|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[St Asaph]]\n| residence = [[Salford Quays]], [[England]]\n| retired= 2018\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height = 178cm\n| weight = 75kg\n| pb = \n| country = {{GBR}} \n| medaltemplates =\n{{Medal|Sport|[[Rowing (sport)|Rowing]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{GBR}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[World Rowing Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|[[2015 World Rowing Championships|2015 Aiguebelette]]|Women's four}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[World University Rowing Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|2014 Gravelines|Women's four}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[World Rowing U23 Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|2013 Linz|Women's eight}}\n}}\n\n'''Rebecca Chin''' (born December 11, 1991) is a retired [[British people|British]] rower who competed in international events and a former Paralympic [[discus]] and [[shot put]] thrower in the [[F44 (classification)|F44]] classification who competed in the [[2008 Summer Paralympics]] but was shifted to the [[F38 (classification)|F38 category]] as it was deemed appropriate for her unusual leg function. However, after her shot put event, she was stripped of her shot put silver medal due to an on the spot reclassification of her disability, Chin was born with hyperlax ankle ligaments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rowing/41427949|title=World Rowing Championships: Rebecca Chin on overcoming Paralympic disappointment|last=|first=|date=29 September 2017|website=BBC Sport|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nDuring her rowing career, she competed in the women's fours events with [[Karen Bennett]], Pippa Whittaker and Michelle Vezie.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/rowing/2017/08/10/rebecca-chins-journey-parlaympic-discus-world-championship-rower/|title=Rebecca Chin's journey from the Paralympic discus to World Championship rower|last=|first=|date=10 August 2017|website=The Telegraph|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishrowing.org/athlete/rebecca-chin/|title=Rebecca Chin - Profile|last=|first=|date=11 December 2019|website=British Rowing|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nChin retired due to back injury in 2018 where she was aiming to compete at the [[2020 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypost.co.uk/sport/other-sport/north-wales-ace-rebecca-chin-14967235|title=North Wales ace Rebecca Chin calls time on an 'OAR-some' career|last=|first=|date=30 July 2018|website=North Wales Live|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from St Asaph]]\n[[Category:Welsh female rowers]]\n[[Category:Welsh female discus throwers]]\n[[Category:Welsh female shot putters]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox athlete\n| name = Rebecca Chin\n| nickname = \n| image = Rebecca Chin rower in 2015.JPG\n| imagesize = \n| caption = Chin at the 2015 World Rowing Championships\n| nationality = \n| sport = [[Rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| event = \n| club = [[Agecroft Rowing Club]]\n| coach = Hamish Burrell<br> Robin Williams\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1991|12|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[St Asaph]]\n| residence = [[Salford Quays]], [[England]]\n| retired= 2018\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height = 178cm\n| weight = 75kg\n| pb = \n| country = {{GBR}} \n| medaltemplates =\n{{Medal|Sport|[[Rowing (sport)|Rowing]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{GBR}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[World Rowing Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|[[2015 World Rowing Championships|2015 Aiguebelette]]|Women's four}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[World University Rowing Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|2014 Gravelines|Women's four}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[World Rowing U23 Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|2013 Linz|Women's eight}}\n}}\n\n'''Rebecca Chin''' (born December 11, 1991) is a retired [[British people|British]] rower who competed in international events and a former Paralympic [[discus]] and [[shot put]] thrower in the [[F44 (classification)|F44]] classification who competed in the [[2008 Summer Paralympics]] but was shifted to the [[F38 (classification)|F38 category]] as it was deemed appropriate for her unusual leg function. However, after her shot put event, she was stripped off her shot put silver medal due to an on the spot reclassification of her disability, Chin was born with hyperlax ankle ligaments<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rowing/41427949|title=World Rowing Championships: Rebecca Chin on overcoming Paralympic disappointment|last=|first=|date=29 September 2017|website=BBC Sport|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\nDuring her rowing career, she competed in the women's fours events with [[Karen Bennett]], Pippa Whittaker and Michelle Vezie.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/rowing/2017/08/10/rebecca-chins-journey-parlaympic-discus-world-championship-rower/|title=Rebecca Chin's journey from the Paralympic discus to World Championship rower|last=|first=|date=10 August 2017|website=The Telegraph|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishrowing.org/athlete/rebecca-chin/|title=Rebecca Chin - Profile|last=|first=|date=11 December 2019|website=British Rowing|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nChin retired due to back injury in 2018 where she was aiming to compete at the [[2020 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypost.co.uk/sport/other-sport/north-wales-ace-rebecca-chin-14967235|title=North Wales ace Rebecca Chin calls time on an 'OAR-some' career|last=|first=|date=30 July 2018|website=North Wales Live|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from St Asaph]]\n[[Category:Welsh female rowers]]\n[[Category:Welsh female discus throwers]]\n[[Category:Welsh female shot putters]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Typo/generalfixes, replaced: stripped off \u2192 stripped of", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rebecca_Chin"}
{"title_page": "Caprigliola bridge collapse", "text_new": "{{Short description|260 m road bridge collapsed in Italy on 08 April 2020}}\n{{Current disaster|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n| name                = \n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| image               = \n| image_upright       = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| pushpin_map         = \n| pushpin_relief      = \n| pushpin_map_size    = \n| pushpin_map_alt     = \n| pushpin_map_caption = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|44|10|26.4|N|09|55|31.7|E|display=inline}}\n| os_grid_reference   = \n| qid                 = \n| refs                = \n| carries             = \n| crosses             = \n| locale              = \n| starts              = \n| ends                = \n| official_name       = \n| other_name          = \n| named_for           = \n| owner               = [[ANAS]]\n| maint               = \n| heritage            = \n| id                  = \n| id_type             = \n| website             = \n| preceded            = \n| followed            = \n| design              = \n| material            = [[Reinforced concrete]]\n| material1           = \n| material2           = \n| length              = {{convert|260|m|abbr=on}}\n| width               = {{convert|7.2|m|abbr=on}}\n| height              = {{convert|10|m|abbr=on}}\n| depth               = \n| traversable         = \n| towpath             = \n| mainspan            = \n| number_spans        = \n| piers_in_water      = \n| load                = \n| clearance_above     = \n| clearance_below     = \n| lanes               = \n| life                = \n| first_length        = \n| first_diameter      = \n| second_length       = \n| second_diameter     = \n| third_length        = \n| third_diameter      = \n| capacity            = \n| num_track           = \n| track_gauge         = \n| structure_gauge     = \n| electrification     = \n| architect           = Attilio Muggia<ref name=\"News1\" />\n| designer            = \n| contracted_designer = \n| winner              = \n| engineering         = \n| builder             = Ing. Nino Ferrari Impresa Costruzioni Generali Srl\n| fabricator          = \n| begin               = 1906\n| complete            = 1908\n| cost                = \n| open                = October 1908\n| inaugurated         = 11 October 1908\n| rebuilt             = 1945\u20131949 after being mined by the German [[Wermacht]] in 1945\n| collapsed           = 8 April 2020\n| closed              = \n| replaces            = \n| replaced_by         = \n| traffic             = \n| toll                = \n| map_type            = \n| map_relief          = \n| map_dot_label       = \n| map_image           = Caprigliola bridge collapse Location.png\n| map_size            = \n| map_alt             = \n| mapframe            = \n| mapframe_zoom       = \n| mapframe_width      = \n| mapframe_height     = \n| mapframe_marker     = \n| mapframe_marker_color = \n| mapframe_lat        = \n| mapframe_long       = \n| map_caption         = Location of the collapsed Caprigliola bridge on the [[Magra]] river between [[Caprigliola]] and [[Albiano Magra]] in [[Tuscany]]\n| extra               = <!-- extra = module = embed = -->\n}}\n\nOn 8 April 2020 at 10:25&nbsp;am local time (8:25 UTC), a {{convert|260|m|adj=on}} long road bridge on the SS330 road near the town of [[Aulla]] between the hamlets of [[Caprigliola]] and [[Albiano Magra]] at mid-way between [[Genoa]] and [[Florence]] collapsed into the [[Magra]] river. The traffic on the bridge was unusually light due to the [[2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown|coronavirus lockdown]] then in force, and the collapse resulted in only minor injuries of two truck drivers.<ref name=\"BBC_News_April_08\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-52213898 |title=Italy bridge collapse: Two drivers survive |work=BBC News |date=8 April 2020 |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Lockdown keeps casualty figure low as Italian bridge collapses |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/08/lockdown-keeps-casualty-figure-low-as-italian-bridge-collapses |date=8 April 2020 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bridge Collapses in Italy, Newest Crumbling Infrastructure |url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/04/08/world/europe/bc-eu-italy-bridge-collapse.html |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voceapuana.com/fotogallery/crollato-il-ponte-sul-magra-disastro-ad-776_1.aspx|title=Crollato il ponte sul Magra, disastro ad Albiano|work=La Voce Apuana|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Euronews]], a gas pipeline was damaged but the gas leak was promptly isolated by [[Italgas]].<ref name=\u201dEuronews_1\u201d>[https://www.euronews.com/2020/04/08/italian-bridge-collapses-injuring-only-one-as-lockdown-conditions-reduce-traffic Euronews: Italian bridge collapses injuring only one as lockdown conditions reduce traffic] </ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe bridge is located on the river Marra at about {{convert|9|km}} south from the town of Aulla, a [[comune]] in the [[province of Massa and Carrara]], [[Tuscany]] in central Italy.\nIn November 2019, a crack on the road pavement was reported by bridge users after important rain falls.<ref name=\"BBC_News_April_08\" /> [[ANAS]] S.p.A., or ''Azienda Nazionale Autonoma delle Strade'' (English: ''National Autonomous Roads Corporation''), was in charge of the maintenance of the bridge. After the first claims reported by drivers, ANAS carried out an inspection of the bridge, finding no anomalies or defects requiring to undertake emergency measures. The crack in the road pavement was then repaired with fresh asphalt. {{As of|2020|04|09}}, the root cause of the bridge collapse is still unknown but a small event may have triggered a more important one, compromising the structural stability of the bridge. \n\n===Construction===\n\n[[Attilio Muggia]], a pioneer of [[reinforced concrete]] in Italy, built the bridge on the Magra river for connecting Albiano with Caprigliola and [[Tuscany]] with [[Liguria]].<ref name =\"News1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.news1.news/a/2020/04/collapsed-bridge-it-was-from-1908-it-was-built-by-a-pioneer-of-reinforced-concrete.html|title=Collapsed bridge: it was from 1908, it was built by a pioneer of reinforced concrete|date=9 April 2020|publisher=|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Levantenews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.levantenews.it/index.php/2020/04/09/aulla-un-crollo-deja-vu/|title=Aulla: a collapse d\u00e9j\u00e0 vu|publisher=|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref name =\"Voceapuana_1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.voceapuana.com/lunigiana-e-apuane/attualita/-il-ponte-costruito-da-mio-nonno-era-sopravvissuto-alle-mine-tedesche-27210.aspx|title=\"Il ponte costruito da mio nonno, era sopravvissuto alle mine tedesche\"|date=8 April 2020|work=La Voce Apuana|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe bridge construction began in 1906 and was achieved in October 1908. The five slender arches had a span of {{convert|51.15|m}} and the deck was supported by 400 pillars. The construction works required {{convert|3000|t|ST|abbr=on}} of cement and {{convert|220|t|ST|abbr=on}} of iron. After the bridge commissioning, the ferry service on the Magra river was abandoned.<ref name=\"News1\" /><ref name=\"Voceapuana_1\" />\n\n===Reconstruction or heavy repairs after 1945===\n\nThe bridge was repaired between 1945\u20131949 after being mined by the German [[Wehrmacht]] in 1945 at the end of World War II.<ref name=\"Voceapuana_1\" />\n\n==Controversy about safety==\n\nThe Municipality of Aulla and local inhabitants were long questioning the safety of the bridge. In a letter dated of August 2019, thus before the discovery of a crack in the asphalt of the road in November 2019, Vincenzo Marzi, then head of the ANAS department for Tuscany replied them that \"The viaduct for the moment does not present criticalities such as to compromise its static functionality\".<ref name=\u201dEuronews_2\u201d>[https://www.news1.news/a/2020/04/ponte-collapsed-who-is-the-anas-manager-who-signed-the-letter-of-tutto-a-posto.html Ponte collapsed, who is the Anas manager who signed the letter of \u201cTutto a posto\u201d] </ref>\n\n==Root causes of the disaster==\n\nAlthough the root causes of the collapse are not yet identified, some conjectures have already been put forwards by some experts. Indeed, ''Voce Apuana'' reports that the engineer Fabrizio Ferrari, nephew of Nino Ferrari who constructed the bridge together with Professor Muggia between 1906 and 1908, told CDS that: {{Quote|text=\"His impression is that there has been a break due to a cut of a section of the deck at a support. The piles, however, still seem in place. A capital has rotated, perhaps dragged by the deck that passed over it, but the bulk of the pile, the one in the riverbed is intact. The piles are very deep, I doubt that the explanations for this collapse lie in the fact that you are in the river bed. Whether it is a failure of the deck.\"<ref name=\"Voceapuana_1\" />}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ponte Morandi#Collapse|Ponte Morandi]]\u2014An Italian bridge that collapsed in 2018\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.voceapuana.com/fotogallery/crollato-il-ponte-sul-magra-disastro-ad-776_1.aspx La Voce Apuana: Collapse of the Caprigliola bridge]\n* [https://www.controradio.it/albiano-magra-anas-scrisse-fatta-ispezione-niente-anomalie/ Controradio: Albiano Magra, Anas wrote 'inspection done, no anomalies']\n* [https://www.ilfogliettone.it/crolla-ponte-sul-magra-tra-liguria-e-toscana-2-mezzi-coinvolti/ Ilfogliettone.it: Bridge collapses over the Magra river between Liguria and Tuscany, 2 vehicles involved]\n* Video: [https://tg24.sky.it/cronaca/2020/04/08/ponte-crollato-albiano-sindaco-aulla.html Bridge collapse near Aulla]\n\n[[Category:2020 in Italy]]\n[[Category:2020 road incidents]]\n[[Category:21st century in Tuscany]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:Bridge disasters in Italy]]\n[[Category:Bridge disasters of unknown cause]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures demolished in 2020]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Italy]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in Italy]]\n[[Category:Viaducts]]\n\n{{Italy-bridge-struct-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|260 m road bridge collapsed in Italy on 08 April 2020}}\n{{Current disaster|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n| name                = \n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| image               = \n| image_upright       = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| pushpin_map         = \n| pushpin_relief      = \n| pushpin_map_size    = \n| pushpin_map_alt     = \n| pushpin_map_caption = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|44|10|26.4|N|09|55|31.7|E|display=inline}}\n| os_grid_reference   = \n| qid                 = \n| refs                = \n| carries             = \n| crosses             = \n| locale              = \n| starts              = \n| ends                = \n| official_name       = \n| other_name          = \n| named_for           = \n| owner               = [[ANAS]]\n| maint               = \n| heritage            = \n| id                  = \n| id_type             = \n| website             = \n| preceded            = \n| followed            = \n| design              = \n| material            = [[Reinforced concrete]]\n| material1           = \n| material2           = \n| length              = {{convert|260|m|abbr=on}}\n| width               = {{convert|7.2|m|abbr=on}}\n| height              = {{convert|10|m|abbr=on}}\n| depth               = \n| traversable         = \n| towpath             = \n| mainspan            = \n| number_spans        = \n| piers_in_water      = \n| load                = \n| clearance_above     = \n| clearance_below     = \n| lanes               = \n| life                = \n| first_length        = \n| first_diameter      = \n| second_length       = \n| second_diameter     = \n| third_length        = \n| third_diameter      = \n| capacity            = \n| num_track           = \n| track_gauge         = \n| structure_gauge     = \n| electrification     = \n| architect           = Attilio Muggia<ref name=\"News1\" />\n| designer            = \n| contracted_designer = \n| winner              = \n| engineering         = \n| builder             = Ing. Nino Ferrari Impresa Costruzioni Generali Srl\n| fabricator          = \n| begin               = 1906\n| complete            = 1908\n| cost                = \n| open                = October 1908\n| inaugurated         = 11 October 1908\n| rebuilt             = 1945\u20131949 after being mined by the German [[Wermacht]] in 1945\n| collapsed           = 8 April 2020\n| closed              = \n| replaces            = \n| replaced_by         = \n| traffic             = \n| toll                = \n| map_type            = \n| map_relief          = \n| map_dot_label       = \n| map_image           = Caprigliola bridge collapse Location.png\n| map_size            = \n| map_alt             = \n| mapframe            = \n| mapframe_zoom       = \n| mapframe_width      = \n| mapframe_height     = \n| mapframe_marker     = \n| mapframe_marker_color = \n| mapframe_lat        = \n| mapframe_long       = \n| map_caption         = Location of the collapsed Caprigliola bridge on the [[Magra]] river between [[Caprigliola]] and [[Albiano Magra]] in [[Tuscany]]\n| extra               = <!-- extra = module = embed = -->\n}}\n\nOn 8 April 2020 at 10:25&nbsp;am local time (8:25 UTC), a {{convert|260|m|adj=on}} long road bridge on the SS330 road near the town of [[Aulla]] between the hamlets of [[Caprigliola]] and [[Albiano Magra]] at mid-way between [[Genoa]] and [[Florence]] collapsed into the [[Magra]] river. The traffic on the bridge was unusually light due to the [[2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown|coronavirus lockdown]] then in force, and the collapse resulted in only minor injuries of two truck drivers.<ref name=\"BBC_News_April_08\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-52213898 |title=Italy bridge collapse: Two drivers survive |work=BBC News |date=8 April 2020 |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Lockdown keeps casualty figure low as Italian bridge collapses |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/08/lockdown-keeps-casualty-figure-low-as-italian-bridge-collapses |date=8 April 2020 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bridge Collapses in Italy, Newest Crumbling Infrastructure |url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/04/08/world/europe/bc-eu-italy-bridge-collapse.html |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voceapuana.com/fotogallery/crollato-il-ponte-sul-magra-disastro-ad-776_1.aspx|title=Crollato il ponte sul Magra, disastro ad Albiano|work=La Voce Apuana|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Euronews]], a gas pipeline was damaged but the gas leak was promptly isolated by [[Italgas]].<ref name=\u201dEuronews_1\u201d>[https://www.euronews.com/2020/04/08/italian-bridge-collapses-injuring-only-one-as-lockdown-conditions-reduce-traffic Euronews: Italian bridge collapses injuring only one as lockdown conditions reduce traffic] </ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe bridge is located on the river Marra at about {{convert|9|km}} south from the town of Aulla, a [[comune]] in the [[province of Massa and Carrara]], [[Tuscany]] in central Italy.\nIn November 2019, a crack on the road pavement was reported by bridge users after important rain falls.<ref name=\"BBC_News_April_08\" /> [[ANAS]] S.p.A., or ''Azienda Nazionale Autonoma delle Strade'' (English: ''National Autonomous Roads Corporation''), was in charge of the maintenance of the bridge. After the first claims reported by drivers, ANAS carried out an inspection of the bridge, finding no anomalies or defects requiring to undertake emergency measures. The crack in the road pavement was then repaired with fresh asphalt. {{As of|2020|04|09}}, the root cause of the bridge collapse is still unknown but a small event may have triggered a more important one, compromising the structural stability of the bridge. \n\n===Construction===\n\n[[Attilio Muggia]], a pioneer of [[reinforced concrete]] in Italy, built the bridge on the Magra river for connecting Albiano with Caprigliola and [[Tuscany]] with [[Liguria]].<ref name =\"News1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.news1.news/a/2020/04/collapsed-bridge-it-was-from-1908-it-was-built-by-a-pioneer-of-reinforced-concrete.html|title=Collapsed bridge: it was from 1908, it was built by a pioneer of reinforced concrete|date=9 April 2020|publisher=|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Levantenews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.levantenews.it/index.php/2020/04/09/aulla-un-crollo-deja-vu/|title=Aulla: a collapse d\u00e9j\u00e0 vu|publisher=|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref name =\"Voceapuana_1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.voceapuana.com/lunigiana-e-apuane/attualita/-il-ponte-costruito-da-mio-nonno-era-sopravvissuto-alle-mine-tedesche-27210.aspx|title=\"Il ponte costruito da mio nonno, era sopravvissuto alle mine tedesche\"|date=8 April 2020|work=La Voce Apuana|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe bridge construction began in 1906 and was achieved in October 1908. The five slender arches had a span of {{convert|51.15|m}} and the deck was supported by 400 pillars. The construction works required {{convert|3000|t|ST|abbr=on}} of cement and {{convert|220|t|ST|abbr=on}} of iron. After the bridge commissioning, the ferry service on the Magra river was abandoned.<ref name=\"News1\" /><ref name=\"Voceapuana_1\" />\n\n===Reconstruction or heavy repairs after 1945===\n\nThe bridge was repaired between 1945\u20131949 after being mined by the German [[Wehrmacht]] in 1945 at the end of World War II.<ref name=\"Voceapuana_1\" />\n\n==Controversy about safety==\n\nThe Municipality of Aulla and local inhabitants were long questioning the safety of the bridge. In a letter dated of August 2019, thus before the discovery of a crack in the asphalt of the road in November 2019, Vincenzo Marzi, then head of the ANAS department for Tuscany replied them that \"The viaduct for the moment does not present criticalities such as to compromise its static functionality\". <ref name=\u201dEuronews_2\u201d>[https://www.news1.news/a/2020/04/ponte-collapsed-who-is-the-anas-manager-who-signed-the-letter-of-tutto-a-posto.html Ponte collapsed, who is the Anas manager who signed the letter of \u201cTutto a posto\u201d] </ref>\n\n==Root causes of the disaster==\n\nAlthough the root causes of the collapse are not yet identified, some conjectures have already been put forwards by some experts. Indeed, ''Voce Apuana'' reports that the engineer Fabrizio Ferrari, nephew of Nino Ferrari who constructed the bridge together with Professor Muggia between 1906 and 1908, told CDS that: {{Quote|text=\"His impression is that there has been a break due to a cut of a section of the deck at a support. The piles, however, still seem in place. A capital has rotated, perhaps dragged by the deck that passed over it, but the bulk of the pile, the one in the riverbed is intact. The piles are very deep, I doubt that the explanations for this collapse lie in the fact that you are in the river bed. Whether it is a failure of the deck.\"<ref name=\"Voceapuana_1\" />}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ponte Morandi#Collapse|Ponte Morandi]]\u2014An Italian bridge that collapsed in 2018\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.voceapuana.com/fotogallery/crollato-il-ponte-sul-magra-disastro-ad-776_1.aspx La Voce Apuana: Collapse of the Caprigliola bridge]\n* [https://www.controradio.it/albiano-magra-anas-scrisse-fatta-ispezione-niente-anomalie/ Controradio: Albiano Magra, Anas wrote 'inspection done, no anomalies']\n* [https://www.ilfogliettone.it/crolla-ponte-sul-magra-tra-liguria-e-toscana-2-mezzi-coinvolti/ Ilfogliettone.it: Bridge collapses over the Magra river between Liguria and Tuscany, 2 vehicles involved]\n* Video: [https://tg24.sky.it/cronaca/2020/04/08/ponte-crollato-albiano-sindaco-aulla.html Bridge collapse near Aulla]\n\n[[Category:2020 in Italy]]\n[[Category:2020 road incidents]]\n[[Category:21st century in Tuscany]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:Bridge disasters in Italy]]\n[[Category:Bridge disasters of unknown cause]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures demolished in 2020]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Italy]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in Italy]]\n[[Category:Viaducts]]\n\n{{Italy-bridge-struct-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Corn cheese", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eControversy about safety", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caprigliola_bridge_collapse"}
{"title_page": "Allseas", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = Allseas\n| logo             = Allseas logo grey-red.png\n| type             = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| predecessor      = \n| founder          = Edward Heerema\n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = \n| industry         = offshore pipelaying<br />undersea construction\n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| aum              = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = 4,000<ref>Allseas website: [https://allseas.com/company/ About company], visited 21 December 2019</ref>\n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n| foundation       = 1985\n| location_city    = [[Ch\u00e2tel-Saint-Denis]]\n| location_country = [[Switzerland]]\n| locations        = \n| market cap       = \n| homepage         = [http://www.allseas.com www.allseas.com]\n}}\n'''Allseas''' Group S.A. is a Swiss-based offshore contractor specialising in pipelay, heavy lift and subsea construction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://allseas.com/company/|title=Allseas company|last=|first=|date=|website=www.allseas.com|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> The company, founded in 1985 by owner and president Edward Heerema, employs 4,000 people and operates worldwide.\n\n==Overview==\nAllseas is an international offshore contractor specialising in the execution of large and complex projects, covering pipeline installation, platform installation and removal, and the installation of subsea infrastructure. The company provides support to clients already in the conceptual design stage and offer services for project management, engineering, fabrication, procurement, installation and commissioning.\n\nThe Allseas Group is headquartered in Ch\u00e2tel-Saint-Denis, Switzerland. Allseas Engineering B.V. with offices in Delft, Eindhoven and Enschede, the Netherlands, provides project management and engineering services to the group. The company also operates project and engineering offices out of Australia, Brazil and the USA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://allseas.com/company/offices-and-yards/|title=Allseas offices and yards|last=|first=|date=|website=www.allseas.com|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAllseas operates a versatile fleet of specialised heavy-lift, pipelay and subsea installation vessels designed and developed in-house. The company has installed over 20,000&nbsp;km of subsea pipeline worldwide using S-lay technology, with diameters ranging from 2\u201d to 48\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://allseas.com/activities/pipelines-and-subsea/pipeline-installation/|title=Pipeline installation|website=www.allseas.com}}</ref> Allseas\u2019 launched its first vessel ''Lorelay'', the world's first pipelay vessel to operate on full dynamic positioning, in 1986.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.offshore-mag.com/articles/print/volume-56/issue-1/news/general-interest/gulf-of-mexico-converted-dp-lorelay-to-install-deepwater-lines.html|title=Converted DP Lorelay to install deepwater lines|date= 1 January 1996|work=Offshore Magazine}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Allseas added the {{convert|300|m|adj=on}} ''[[Solitaire (ship)|Solitaire]]'' to its fleet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ogj.com/articles/print/volume-96/issue-18/in-this-issue/general-interest/major-deepwater-pipelay-vessel-starts-work-in-north-sea.html|title=Major deepwater pipelay vessel starts work in North Sea|website=www.ogj.com}}</ref> The vessel has a pipe carrying capacity of 22,000 t and has achieved pipelay speeds in excess of {{convert|9|km/d}}. In 2006, while working on the Atwater Valley and Independence Trail projects in the Gulf of Mexico, ''[https://allseas.com/equipment/solitaire/ Solitaire]'' set new depth records, laying 10-inch pipeline in 2775&nbsp;m (9100&nbsp;ft) water depth and 24-inch pipeline in 2550&nbsp;m (8370&nbsp;ft) water depth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/World's+deepest+floating+production+facility+nears+completion.-a0162833236|title=World's deepest floating production facility nears completion|website=www.ogj.com}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pioneering Spirit (ship, 2014) 010.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.5|''Pioneering Spirit'' (Aug 2016)]]\nAllseas\u2019 [[Pioneering Spirit (ship)|''Pioneering Spirit'']] is the world's largest construction vessel, designed for the single-lift installation and removal of large oil and gas platforms and the installation of record-weight pipelines.\n\nDesigned entirely in-house, the 382 m long, 124 m wide vessel can lift platform topsides up to 48,000 t and steel jackets up to 20,000 t.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-2800441/world-s-biggest-ship-big-lift-oil-rig-takes-seas-pieter-schelte-begin-moving-structures-year.html|title=World's largest ship so big it can lift an OIL RIG takes to the seas|website=www.dailymail.co.uk}}</ref>  The vessel is also equipped with state-of-the-art pipelay equipment, and can install the heaviest offshore pipelines in waters more than 4&nbsp;km deep.\n\n''[[Pioneering Spirit (ship)|Pioneering Spirit]]'' set a new offshore lift record with the single-lift removal of Shell's 24,200 t Brent Delta topsides in April 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/2017-0428-Pioneering-Spirit-sets-world-lifting-record-with-Shell-Brent-Delta-topsides-removal.pdf|title=Pioneering Spirit sets lifting record with Shell Brent Delta topsides removal|website=www.allseas.com}}</ref>  For its first commercial job, the vessel removed the 13,500 t Yme mobile offshore production unit from Norwegian waters for Repsol in August 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/2016-0822-Pioneering-Spirit-completes-maiden-heavy-lift-project_web.pdf|title=Pioneering Spirit completes maiden heavy lift project|website=www.allseas.com}}</ref> ''Pioneering Spirit''\u2019s started its first pipelay job, installation of the offshore section of the TurkStream pipeline in the Black Sea, in June 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gazprom.com/about/production/projects/pipelines/built/turk-stream/|title=TurkStream project|website=www.gazprom.com}}</ref>\n\nAllseas has committed to building an even larger version of the same design, ''Amazing Grace'', which is scheduled to be delivered in 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/2013-1111-Allseas-to-build-a-single-lift-vessel-larger-than-Pieter-Schelte.pdf|title=Allseas to build a single lift vessel larger than Pieter Schelte|website=www.allseas.com}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nAllseas was founded in January 1985 by Edward Heerema, son of the late Pieter Schelte Heerema, founder of the Dutch offshore construction and installation company [[Heerema Marine Contractors]]. Offices subsequently opened in The Hague (the Netherlands) and Ch\u00e2tel-Saint-Denis (Switzerland).\n\nThe company spent its early days developing the concept of dynamically positioned (DP) subsea pipelay. Allseas acquired the former bulk carrier \u201cNatalie Bolten\u201d in 1985 and converted it for DP pipelay at the Boele shipyard in Bolnes, the Netherlands. The vessel was christened ''[https://allseas.com/equipment/lorelay/ Lorelay]'' in Rotterdam on 26 April 1986.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/swan-revival-means-1200-jobs-1340756.html|title=Swan revival means 1,200 jobs|website=www.independent.co.uk}}</ref> ''Lorelay'' immediately entered service and successfully executed her first pipelay contract, the 8-inch, 1.8-km Helder A-B pipeline, for Unocal in the Dutch sector of the North Sea.\n\nIn 1987, the company declared its intention to build a vessel capable of lifting entire offshore platforms. The initial idea featured two rigidly connected, self-propelled supertankers, with a large slot at the bows to install platform topsides in one piece.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ogj.com/articles/print/volume-96/issue-18/in-this-issue/general-interest/major-deepwater-pipelay-vessel-starts-work-in-north-sea.html|title=Major deepwater pipelay vessel starts work in North Sea|website=www.ogj.com}}</ref>\n\nDuring the late 1980s and early 1990s, the company established itself a major player in the North Sea and Gulf of Mexico. In 1992, the company acquired the former bulkhead carrier \u201cTrenchwood\u201d for conversion to ''[https://allseas.com/equipment/solitaire/ Solitaire],'' the world's largest pipelay vessel. Allseas awarded the conversion contract to Sembawang Shipyards in Singapore on a lump sum basis; however, due to ongoing problems the contract was terminated in 1995. The ship was subsequently converted at the Swan Hunter yard on Tyneside, England.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/2006-0331-Joint-press-release-Allseas-and-SembCorp.pdf|title=SembCorp and Allseas reach full and final settlement for Solitaire arbitration|website=www.allseas.com}}</ref> ''Solitaire'' laid her first pipe on Statoil's Europipe project in 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.offshore-mag.com/articles/print/volume-65/issue-6/pipeline-transportation/solitaire-undergoes-preparatory-re-vamp-as-gom-developments-head-deeper.html|title=Solitaire undergoes preparatory re-vamp as GoM developments head deeper|website=www.offshore-mag.com}}</ref> Allseas and [[Sembcorp]] reached a settlement for the ''Solitaire'' arbitration in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.offshore-mag.com/articles/print/volume-66/issue-11/pipeline-transportation/audacia-asset-for-summer-2007-launch.html|title=Audacia asset for summer 2007 launch|website=www.offshore-mag.com}}</ref>\n\nAllseas added the shallow water pipelay and construction barge ''[https://allseas.com/equipment/tog-mor/ Tog Mor]'' to its fleet in 2002. ''Solitaire\u2019s'' S-lay capacity was increased to a holding force of 1,050 t in 2005, enabling her to lay the heaviest pipelines in unprecedented water depths.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/2015-0206-Allseas-to-change-the-name-of-the-vessel-Pieter-Schelte.pdf|title=Allseas to change the name of the vessel Pieter Schelte|website=www.allseas.com}}</ref> The same year Allseas launched the dynamically positioned support vessel ''[https://allseas.com/equipment/calamity-jane/ Calamity Jane]''. The 225 m long dynamically positioned pipelay vessel ''[https://allseas.com/equipment/audacia/ Audacia]'' became operational two years later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/world/2008-11-07-3812420165_x.htm|title=Dutch outcry over naming giant ship after Nazi|website=www.usatoday.com}}</ref>\n\n<big>'''Controversy'''</big>\n\nIn 2007 Allseas announced plans to build \u201cPieter Schelte\u201d, a twin-hulled platform installation / decommissioning and pipelay vessel, named after the offshore pioneer Pieter Schelte Heerema, father of Allseas\u2019 owner and founder Edward Heerema. At 382 m long and 124 m wide the vessel would be the largest ever built.\n\nHowever, the original name created a controversy due to Pieter Schelte Heerema's service in the Waffen-SS during World War II.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/2015-0209-New-name-for-Allseas%E2%80%99-single-lift-vessel.pdf|title=New name for Allseas' single-lift vessel|website=www.allseas.com}}</ref> After the war, Pieter Schelte Heerema was arrested and sentenced to jail for three years for his ties with the Nazi war effort, according to the Dutch National Institute for War Documentation.\n\nThe choice to name the ship after a Nazi SS member provoked an outcry from some politicians and Jewish groups around the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/world/2008-11-07-3812420165_x.htm|title=Dutch outcry over naming giant ship after Nazi|website=www.usatoday.com}}</ref> The Dutch government gave Allseas' Netherlands subsidiary a $1 million tax break for its part in designing the ship, which added to the controversy. In February 2015, Allseas stated that the name would change to \"Pioneering Spirit\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/2015-0209-New-name-for-Allseas%E2%80%99-single-lift-vessel.pdf|title=New name for Allseas' single-lift vessel|website=www.allseas.com}}</ref>\n\n<big>'''Victims of \u00a373 m fraud'''</big><br />A criminal trial in the UK in 2016 revealed that Allseas were victims of a \u00a373 m fraud. In 2011, they invested \u00a373 m with investors led by Luis Nobre claiming to have links to the Vatican and Spanish nobility.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/crime/11889777/City-trader-posed-as-a-multi-millionaire-with-links-to-the-Vatican-in-73m-fraud-court-hears.html|title=City trader posed as a multi-millionaire with links to the Vatican in \u00a373m fraud|website=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/conman-faces-jail-for-posing-as-the-pope-s-banker-in-73m-fraud-a3175221.html|title=Conman faces jail for posing as the Pope's banker in \u00a373m fraud|website=www.standard.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n=== Fellowship ===\nIn April 2016 Edward Heerema was made a Fellow Chartered Engineer by the Royal Netherlands Society of Engineers (KIVI) for his pioneering and innovative contributions to the offshore and marine industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://allseas.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-0412-Persbericht-Installatie-Edward-Heerema.pdf|title=Edward Heerema ge\u00efnstalleerd als Fellow Chartered Engineer|last=|first=|date=|website=www.allseas.com|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> It is the first time that this title has been awarded in the Netherlands.\n\n== Fleet ==\nThe company owns several vessels which are used for its offshore construction activities.\n\n==== Pioneering Spirit ====\n{{Main|Pioneering Spirit (ship)|l1=Pioneering Spirit (Ship)}}\n\nPioneering Spirit is the largest construction vessel in the world. It specializes in single lift installation or removal of offshore Oil & Gas platforms. It is also capable of installation of subsea pipelines with extremely high weight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://offshore-fleet.com/particulars/p/pioneering-spirit.htm|title=Pioneering Spirit (Crane ship, pipelay) - Ships Particulars|website=offshore-fleet.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nIt holds offshore lift record for the topside installation in Johan Sverdrup field, offshore Norway.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.projectcargojournal.com/offshore/2019/03/26/pioneering-spirit-sets-new-offshore-lift-record/|title=Pioneering Spirit sets new offshore lift record|website=Project Cargo Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==== Solitaire ====\n{{Main|Solitaire (ship)|l1 = Solitaire (Ship)}}Solitaire is one of the largest construction vessel in the world focused on subsea pipeline installation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marineinsight.com/types-of-ships/solitaire-the-largest-pipe-laying-vessel-in-the-world/|website=www.marineinsight.com|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> It's holding force of 1050 tons is catered towards medium and large diameter pipelines. In 2007, it set a record for ultra deep water installation at a depth of 2775m in Gulf of Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wermac.org/nordstream/nordstream_part7.html|title=Nord Stream Pipeline - Allseas Solitaire, the largest pipelay vessel in the world|website=www.wermac.org|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> \n\n==== Audacia ====\nAudacia is a versatile pipelay vessel designed for installation of small to large diameter subsea pipelines. It is equipped with Dynamic Positioning System. Built in 2005, it has been operational since 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/equipment/audacia/|title=Audacia {{!}} Allseas|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vesselfinder.com/vessels/AUDACIA-IMO-9305130-MMSI-249117000|title=AUDACIA, Pipe Layer - Details and current position - IMO 9305130 MMSI 249117000 - VesselFinder|website=www.vesselfinder.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nIt is registered and currently sailing under the flag of Malta. It has length overall of 225 m and gross tonnage of 56172.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vesseltracking.net/ship/audacia-9305130|title=AUDACIA (IMO 9305130, Pipe Layer) - Ship Details and Current Position {{!}} Vessel Tracking|website=www.vesseltracking.net|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> \n\n==== Lorelay ====\nLorelay is a pipelay vessel designed for installation of small to medium diameter subsea pipelines. It was the first offshore pipelay vessel to be equipped with full Dynamic Positioning System (DPS).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oilandgaspeople.com/news/common/post.asp?postId=18406|title=Allseas Sister Ships Reunited for North Sea Project - Oil and Gas News|website=www.oilandgaspeople.com|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> \n\n==== Calamity Jane ====\nCalamity Jane is a support vessel built in 1978.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vesselfinder.com/vessels/CALAMITY-JANE-IMO-7616779-MMSI-249139000|title=CALAMITY JANE, Trenching Support Vessel - Details and current position - IMO 7616779 MMSI 249139000 - VesselFinder|website=www.vesselfinder.com|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> It generally assists other pipeline installation vessels during construction. Typically the activities performed by Calamity Jane would include pre and post construction survey, crossing preparation, mattress installation etc.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/equipment/calamity-jane/|title=Calamity Jane {{!}} Allseas|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n==== Tog Mor ====\nTog Mor is a shallow water construction barge. It navigates using anchors with 10 point mooring system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/equipment/tog-mor/|title=Tog Mor {{!}} Allseas|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> \n\n==== Fortitude ====\nFortitude is a multipurpose offshore construction vessel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/equipment/fortitude/|title=Fortitude {{!}} Allseas|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> The vessel was built in 2015 at Hyundai yard in Korea for Toisa Group which had named in Toisa Patroklos. Allseas acquired it in 2018 and renamed the vessel to Fortitude. It is expected that Fortitude will primarily work as an offshore support vessel for Pioneering Spirit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heavyliftnews.com/allseas-gets-another-deepwater-construction-vessel/|title=Allseas gets another Deepwater Construction Vessel \u2013 Heavy Lift News|website=www.heavyliftnews.com|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> \n\n==== Oceanic ====\n\n==== Pipe supply vessels ====\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{refbegin}}{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:Companies established in 1985]]\n[[Category:Construction and civil engineering companies of Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies of Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Oilfield services companies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = Allseas\n| logo             = Allseas logo grey-red.png\n| type             = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| predecessor      = \n| founder          = Edward Heerema\n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = \n| industry         = offshore pipelaying<br />undersea construction\n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| aum              = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = 4,000<ref>Allseas website: [https://allseas.com/company/ About company], visited 21 December 2019</ref>\n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n| foundation       = 1985\n| location_city    = [[Ch\u00e2tel-Saint-Denis]]\n| location_country = [[Switzerland]]\n| locations        = \n| market cap       = \n| homepage         = [http://www.allseas.com www.allseas.com]\n}}\n'''Allseas''' Group S.A. is a Swiss-based offshore contractor specialising in pipelay, heavy lift and subsea construction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://allseas.com/company/|title=Allseas company|last=|first=|date=|website=www.allseas.com|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> The company, founded in 1985 by owner and president Edward Heerema, employs 4,000 people and operates worldwide.\n\n==Overview==\nAllseas is an international offshore contractor specialising in the execution of large and complex projects, covering pipeline installation, platform installation and removal, and the installation of subsea infrastructure. The company provides support to clients already in the conceptual design stage and offer services for project management, engineering, fabrication, procurement, installation and commissioning.\n\nThe Allseas Group is headquartered in Ch\u00e2tel-Saint-Denis, Switzerland. Allseas Engineering B.V. with offices in Delft, Eindhoven and Enschede, the Netherlands, provides project management and engineering services to the group. The company also operates project and engineering offices out of Australia, Brazil and the USA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://allseas.com/company/offices-and-yards/|title=Allseas offices and yards|last=|first=|date=|website=www.allseas.com|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAllseas operates a versatile fleet of specialised heavy-lift, pipelay and subsea installation vessels designed and developed in-house. The company has installed over 20,000&nbsp;km of subsea pipeline worldwide using S-lay technology, with diameters ranging from 2\u201d to 48\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://allseas.com/activities/pipelines-and-subsea/pipeline-installation/|title=Pipeline installation|website=www.allseas.com}}</ref> Allseas\u2019 launched its first vessel ''Lorelay'', the world's first pipelay vessel to operate on full dynamic positioning, in 1986.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.offshore-mag.com/articles/print/volume-56/issue-1/news/general-interest/gulf-of-mexico-converted-dp-lorelay-to-install-deepwater-lines.html|title=Converted DP Lorelay to install deepwater lines|date= 1 January 1996|work=Offshore Magazine}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Allseas added the {{convert|300|m|adj=on}} ''[[Solitaire (ship)|Solitaire]]'' to its fleet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ogj.com/articles/print/volume-96/issue-18/in-this-issue/general-interest/major-deepwater-pipelay-vessel-starts-work-in-north-sea.html|title=Major deepwater pipelay vessel starts work in North Sea|website=www.ogj.com}}</ref> The vessel has a pipe carrying capacity of 22,000 t and has achieved pipelay speeds in excess of {{convert|9|km/d}}. In 2006, while working on the Atwater Valley and Independence Trail projects in the Gulf of Mexico, ''[https://allseas.com/equipment/solitaire/ Solitaire]'' set new depth records, laying 10-inch pipeline in 2775&nbsp;m (9100&nbsp;ft) water depth and 24-inch pipeline in 2550&nbsp;m (8370&nbsp;ft) water depth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/World's+deepest+floating+production+facility+nears+completion.-a0162833236|title=World's deepest floating production facility nears completion|website=www.ogj.com}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pioneering Spirit (ship, 2014) 010.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.5|''Pioneering Spirit'' (Aug 2016)]]\nAllseas\u2019 [[Pioneering Spirit (ship)|''Pioneering Spirit'']] is the world's largest construction vessel, designed for the single-lift installation and removal of large oil and gas platforms and the installation of record-weight pipelines.\n\nDesigned entirely in-house, the 382 m long, 124 m wide vessel can lift platform topsides up to 48,000 t and steel jackets up to 20,000 t.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-2800441/world-s-biggest-ship-big-lift-oil-rig-takes-seas-pieter-schelte-begin-moving-structures-year.html|title=World's largest ship so big it can lift an OIL RIG takes to the seas|website=www.dailymail.co.uk}}</ref>  The vessel is also equipped with state-of-the-art pipelay equipment, and can install the heaviest offshore pipelines in waters more than 4&nbsp;km deep.\n\n''[[Pioneering Spirit (ship)|Pioneering Spirit]]'' set a new offshore lift record with the single-lift removal of Shell's 24,200 t Brent Delta topsides in April 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/2017-0428-Pioneering-Spirit-sets-world-lifting-record-with-Shell-Brent-Delta-topsides-removal.pdf|title=Pioneering Spirit sets lifting record with Shell Brent Delta topsides removal|website=www.allseas.com}}</ref>  For its first commercial job, the vessel removed the 13,500 t Yme mobile offshore production unit from Norwegian waters for Repsol in August 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/2016-0822-Pioneering-Spirit-completes-maiden-heavy-lift-project_web.pdf|title=Pioneering Spirit completes maiden heavy lift project|website=www.allseas.com}}</ref> ''Pioneering Spirit''\u2019s started its first pipelay job, installation of the offshore section of the TurkStream pipeline in the Black Sea, in June 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gazprom.com/about/production/projects/pipelines/built/turk-stream/|title=TurkStream project|website=www.gazprom.com}}</ref>\n\nAllseas has committed to building an even larger version of the same design, ''Amazing Grace'', which is scheduled to be delivered in 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/2013-1111-Allseas-to-build-a-single-lift-vessel-larger-than-Pieter-Schelte.pdf|title=Allseas to build a single lift vessel larger than Pieter Schelte|website=www.allseas.com}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nAllseas was founded in January 1985 by Edward Heerema, son of the late Pieter Schelte Heerema, founder of the Dutch offshore construction and installation company [[Heerema Marine Contractors]]. Offices subsequently opened in The Hague (the Netherlands) and Ch\u00e2tel-Saint-Denis (Switzerland).\n\nThe company spent its early days developing the concept of dynamically positioned (DP) subsea pipelay. Allseas acquired the former bulk carrier \u201cNatalie Bolten\u201d in 1985 and converted it for DP pipelay at the Boele shipyard in Bolnes, the Netherlands. The vessel was christened ''[https://allseas.com/equipment/lorelay/ Lorelay]'' in Rotterdam on 26 April 1986.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/swan-revival-means-1200-jobs-1340756.html|title=Swan revival means 1,200 jobs|website=www.independent.co.uk}}</ref> ''Lorelay'' immediately entered service and successfully executed her first pipelay contract, the 8-inch, 1.8-km Helder A-B pipeline, for Unocal in the Dutch sector of the North Sea.\n\nIn 1987, the company declared its intention to build a vessel capable of lifting entire offshore platforms. The initial idea featured two rigidly connected, self-propelled supertankers, with a large slot at the bows to install platform topsides in one piece.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ogj.com/articles/print/volume-96/issue-18/in-this-issue/general-interest/major-deepwater-pipelay-vessel-starts-work-in-north-sea.html|title=Major deepwater pipelay vessel starts work in North Sea|website=www.ogj.com}}</ref>\n\nDuring the late 1980s and early 1990s, the company established itself a major player in the North Sea and Gulf of Mexico. In 1992, the company acquired the former bulkhead carrier \u201cTrenchwood\u201d for conversion to ''[https://allseas.com/equipment/solitaire/ Solitaire],'' the world's largest pipelay vessel. Allseas awarded the conversion contract to Sembawang Shipyards in Singapore on a lump sum basis; however, due to ongoing problems the contract was terminated in 1995. The ship was subsequently converted at the Swan Hunter yard on Tyneside, England.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/2006-0331-Joint-press-release-Allseas-and-SembCorp.pdf|title=SembCorp and Allseas reach full and final settlement for Solitaire arbitration|website=www.allseas.com}}</ref> ''Solitaire'' laid her first pipe on Statoil's Europipe project in 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.offshore-mag.com/articles/print/volume-65/issue-6/pipeline-transportation/solitaire-undergoes-preparatory-re-vamp-as-gom-developments-head-deeper.html|title=Solitaire undergoes preparatory re-vamp as GoM developments head deeper|website=www.offshore-mag.com}}</ref> Allseas and [[Sembcorp]] reached a settlement for the ''Solitaire'' arbitration in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.offshore-mag.com/articles/print/volume-66/issue-11/pipeline-transportation/audacia-asset-for-summer-2007-launch.html|title=Audacia asset for summer 2007 launch|website=www.offshore-mag.com}}</ref>\n\nAllseas added the shallow water pipelay and construction barge ''[https://allseas.com/equipment/tog-mor/ Tog Mor]'' to its fleet in 2002. ''Solitaire\u2019s'' S-lay capacity was increased to a holding force of 1,050 t in 2005, enabling her to lay the heaviest pipelines in unprecedented water depths.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/2015-0206-Allseas-to-change-the-name-of-the-vessel-Pieter-Schelte.pdf|title=Allseas to change the name of the vessel Pieter Schelte|website=www.allseas.com}}</ref> The same year Allseas launched the dynamically positioned support vessel ''[https://allseas.com/equipment/calamity-jane/ Calamity Jane]''. The 225 m long dynamically positioned pipelay vessel ''[https://allseas.com/equipment/audacia/ Audacia]'' became operational two years later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/world/2008-11-07-3812420165_x.htm|title=Dutch outcry over naming giant ship after Nazi|website=www.usatoday.com}}</ref>\n\n<big>'''Controversy'''</big>\n\nIn 2007 Allseas announced plans to build \u201cPieter Schelte\u201d, a twin-hulled platform installation / decommissioning and pipelay vessel, named after the offshore pioneer Pieter Schelte Heerema, father of Allseas\u2019 owner and founder Edward Heerema. At 382 m long and 124 m wide the vessel would be the largest ever built.\n\nHowever, the original name created a controversy due to Pieter Schelte Heerema's service in the Waffen-SS during World War II.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/2015-0209-New-name-for-Allseas%E2%80%99-single-lift-vessel.pdf|title=New name for Allseas' single-lift vessel|website=www.allseas.com}}</ref> After the war, Pieter Schelte Heerema was arrested and sentenced to jail for three years for his ties with the Nazi war effort, according to the Dutch National Institute for War Documentation.\n\nThe choice to name the ship after a Nazi SS member provoked an outcry from some politicians and Jewish groups around the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/world/2008-11-07-3812420165_x.htm|title=Dutch outcry over naming giant ship after Nazi|website=www.usatoday.com}}</ref> The Dutch government gave Allseas' Netherlands subsidiary a $1 million tax break for its part in designing the ship, which added to the controversy. In February 2015, Allseas stated that the name would change to \"Pioneering Spirit\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/2015-0209-New-name-for-Allseas%E2%80%99-single-lift-vessel.pdf|title=New name for Allseas' single-lift vessel|website=www.allseas.com}}</ref>\n\n<big>'''Victims of \u00a373 m fraud'''</big><br />A criminal trial in the UK in 2016 revealed that Allseas were victims of a \u00a373 m fraud. In 2011, they invested \u00a373 m with investors led by Luis Nobre claiming to have links to the Vatican and Spanish nobility.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/crime/11889777/City-trader-posed-as-a-multi-millionaire-with-links-to-the-Vatican-in-73m-fraud-court-hears.html|title=City trader posed as a multi-millionaire with links to the Vatican in \u00a373m fraud|website=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/conman-faces-jail-for-posing-as-the-pope-s-banker-in-73m-fraud-a3175221.html|title=Conman faces jail for posing as the Pope's banker in \u00a373m fraud|website=www.standard.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n=== Fellowship ===\nIn April 2016 Edward Heerema was made a Fellow Chartered Engineer by the Royal Netherlands Society of Engineers (KIVI) for his pioneering and innovative contributions to the offshore and marine industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://allseas.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-0412-Persbericht-Installatie-Edward-Heerema.pdf|title=Edward Heerema ge\u00efnstalleerd als Fellow Chartered Engineer|last=|first=|date=|website=www.allseas.com|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> It is the first time that this title has been awarded in the Netherlands.\n\n== Fleet ==\nThe company owns several vessels which are used for its offshore construction activities.\n\n==== Pioneering Spirit ====\n{{Main|Pioneering Spirit (ship)|l1=Pioneering Spirit (Ship)}}\n\nPioneering Spirit is the largest construction vessel in the world. It specializes in single lift installation or removal of offshore Oil & Gas platforms. It is also capable of installation of subsea pipelines with extremely high weight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://offshore-fleet.com/particulars/p/pioneering-spirit.htm|title=Pioneering Spirit (Crane ship, pipelay) - Ships Particulars|website=offshore-fleet.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nIt holds offshore lift record for the topside installation in Johan Sverdrup field, offshore Norway.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.projectcargojournal.com/offshore/2019/03/26/pioneering-spirit-sets-new-offshore-lift-record/|title=Pioneering Spirit sets new offshore lift record|website=Project Cargo Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==== Solitaire ====\n{{Main|Solitaire (ship)|l1 = Solitaire (Ship)}}Solitaire is one of the largest construction vessel in the world focused on subsea pipeline installation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marineinsight.com/types-of-ships/solitaire-the-largest-pipe-laying-vessel-in-the-world/|website=www.marineinsight.com|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> It's holding force of 1050 tons is catered towards medium and large diameter pipelines. In 2007, it set a record for ultra deep water installation at a depth of 2775m in Gulf of Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wermac.org/nordstream/nordstream_part7.html|title=Nord Stream Pipeline - Allseas Solitaire, the largest pipelay vessel in the world|website=www.wermac.org|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> \n\n==== Audacia ====\nAudacia is a versatile pipelay vessel designed for installation of small to large diameter subsea pipelines. It is equipped with Dynamic Positioning System. Built in 2005, it has been operational since 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/equipment/audacia/|title=Audacia {{!}} Allseas|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vesselfinder.com/vessels/AUDACIA-IMO-9305130-MMSI-249117000|title=AUDACIA, Pipe Layer - Details and current position - IMO 9305130 MMSI 249117000 - VesselFinder|website=www.vesselfinder.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nIt is registered and currently sailing under the flag of Malta. It has length overall of 225 m and gross tonnage of 56172.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vesseltracking.net/ship/audacia-9305130|title=AUDACIA (IMO 9305130, Pipe Layer) - Ship Details and Current Position {{!}} Vessel Tracking|website=www.vesseltracking.net|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> \n\n==== Lorelay ====\nLorelay is a pipelay vessel designed for installation of small to medium diameter subsea pipelines. It was the first offshore pipelay vessel to be equipped with full Dynamic Positioning System (DPS).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oilandgaspeople.com/news/common/post.asp?postId=18406|title=Allseas Sister Ships Reunited for North Sea Project - Oil and Gas News|website=www.oilandgaspeople.com|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> \n\n==== Calamity Jane ====\nCalamity Jane is a support vessel built in 1978.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vesselfinder.com/vessels/CALAMITY-JANE-IMO-7616779-MMSI-249139000|title=CALAMITY JANE, Trenching Support Vessel - Details and current position - IMO 7616779 MMSI 249139000 - VesselFinder|website=www.vesselfinder.com|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> It generally assists other pipeline installation vessels during construction. Typically the activities performed by Calamity Jane would include pre and post construction survey, crossing preparation, mattress installation etc.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/equipment/calamity-jane/|title=Calamity Jane {{!}} Allseas|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n==== Tog Mor ====\nTog Mor is a shallow water construction barge. It navigates using anchors with 10 point mooring system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/equipment/tog-mor/|title=Tog Mor {{!}} Allseas|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> \n\n==== Fortitude ====\nFortitude is a multipurpose offshore construction vessel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allseas.com/equipment/fortitude/|title=Fortitude {{!}} Allseas|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> The vessel was built in 2015 at Hyundai yard in Korea for Toisa Group which had named in Toisa Patroklos. Allseas acquired it in 2018 and renamed the vessel to Fortitude. It is expected that Fortitude will primarily work as an offshore support vessel for Pioneering Spirit. \n\n==== Oceanic ====\n\n==== Pipe supply vessels ====\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{refbegin}}{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:Companies established in 1985]]\n[[Category:Construction and civil engineering companies of Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies of Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Oilfield services companies]]\n", "name_user": "Billybatson11", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFortitude:added citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allseas"}
{"title_page": "Armenian Native Faith", "text_new": "{{short description|Armenian Neopaganism}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{sidebar\n|name = Armenian Native Faith\n|title = [[Hetanism]]<br />and [[Armenian mythology]]\n|image = [[File:Left-Facing Armenian Eternity Sign UC 058E SVG.svg|150px]]\n|caption = Arevakhach, symbol of hetanism\n|captionstyle = font-style:italic\n|headingstyle = background:#B0CBAC\n|contentclass = hlist\n\n|heading1 = Practices\n|content1 =\n* [[Pantheism]]\n* Semi-[[Polytheistic]] [[Monotheism]]\n* [[Matagh]]\n* [[Knunk]]\n* [[Vardavar]]\n* [[Fire worship]]\n* [[List of water deities|Water woship]]\n* [[Veneration of the dead|Worship of ancestors]]\n\n|heading2 = Places\n|content2 =\n* [[Garni temple]]\n* [[Zorats qarer]]\n* [[Khustup mountain]]\n\n|heading3 = Deities and beings\n|content3 =\n* Ar\n* [[Hayk]] (Aramazd)\n* [[Anahit]]\n* [[Vahagn]]\n* [[Tir]]\n* [[Mihr]]\n* [[Vanatur]]\n* [[Ara the Beautiful]]\n* [[Turk' Angegh]]\n* [[Nane]]\n* [[Astghik]]\n* [[Spandaramet]]\n* [[Barshamin]]\n|heading4 = Ancient Sources\n|content4 =\n* [[Moses of Chorene]]\n* [[Anania Shirakatsi]]\n* [[Ukhtagirq]]\n}}\n'''Hetanism''' ([[Armenian language|Armenian]]: \u0540\u0565\u0569\u0561\u0576\u0578\u057d\u0578\u0582\u0569\u056b\u0582\u0576 ''Hetanosutiwn'') or '''Armenian native faith''', was the dominant<ref name=\"Romeny 2010\">{{Cite book|last=Romeny|first=R. B. ter Haar|url=https://books.google.dk/books?id=ZxDi924k4RIC&vq=|title=Religious Origins of Nations?: The Christian Communities of the Middle East|date=2010|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-17375-0|language=en}}</ref> ethnic religion of Armenia before the adoption of [[Christianity]] in 301 AD.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Armen Petrosyan|url=http://archive.org/details/2015PetrosyanProblemsOfArmenianPrehistory|title=Problems of Armenian Prehistory. Myth, Language, History|language=English}}</ref><ref name=\"Romeny 2010\"/><ref>{{Cite book|last=Petrosyan|first=Armen|url=https://www.academia.edu/3656244/The_Indo-European_and_Ancient_Near_Eastern_Sources_of_the_Armenian_Epic._Washington_D.C._2002|title=The Indo-European and Ancient Near Eastern Sources of the Armenian Epic. Washington D.C. 2002|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Antonyan|first=Yulia|date=|title=\u0412\u043e\u0441\u0441\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0440\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0433\u0438\u0438: \u041d\u0435\u043e\u044f\u0437\u044b\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0432 \u0410\u0440\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 (&quot;Re-creation&quot; of a religion: neo-paganism in Armenia)|url=https://www.academia.edu/191429/%D0%92%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%81%D0%BE%D0%B7%D0%B4%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%B5_%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%BB%D0%B8%D0%B3%D0%B8%D0%B8_%D0%9D%D0%B5%D0%BE%D1%8F%D0%B7%D1%8B%D1%87%D0%B5%D1%81%D1%82%D0%B2%D0%BE_%D0%B2_%D0%90%D1%80%D0%BC%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%B8_Re-creation_of_a_religion_neo-paganism_in_Armenia_|journal=|language=en|volume=|pages=104\u2013105|via=}}</ref>\n\nEven though the organized religion in its final form appeared in the 3rd century BC, the roots of it stretch back as [[Urartu]] and the proto-hetanist religion of [[\u1e2aaldi]]sm,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Badalyan|first=Miqayel|url=https://www.academia.edu/37332324/%D4%B2%D5%AB%D5%A1%D5%B5%D5%B6%D5%AB%D5%AC%D5%AB-%D5%88%D6%82%D6%80%D5%A1%D6%80%D5%BF%D5%B8%D6%82._%D5%A1%D5%BD%D5%BF%D5%BE%D5%A1%D5%AE%D5%B6%D5%A5%D6%80_%D5%BF%D5%A1%D5%B3%D5%A1%D6%80%D5%B6%D5%A5%D6%80_%D5%BA%D5%A1%D5%B7%D5%BF%D5%A1%D5%B4%D5%B8%D6%82%D5%B6%D6%84._Biainili-Urartu_gods_temples_cults|title=\u0532\u056b\u0561\u0575\u0576\u056b\u056c\u056b-\u0548\u0582\u0580\u0561\u0580\u057f\u0578\u0582. \u0561\u057d\u057f\u057e\u0561\u056e\u0576\u0565\u0580, \u057f\u0561\u0573\u0561\u0580\u0576\u0565\u0580, \u057a\u0561\u0577\u057f\u0561\u0574\u0578\u0582\u0576\u0584. Biainili-Urartu: gods, temples, cults|last2=Grekyan|first2=Yervand|last3=Petrosyan|first3=Armen|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aivazian|first=Suren|date=2018|title=The \"door\" to the religion of Urartu|url=http://armstudies.asj-oa.am/254/1/60.pdf|journal=Armenian Studies|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> as well as [[Religions of the ancient Near East|ancient near eastern religions]].<ref name=\"Martirosyan\">{{Cite journal|last=Martirosyan|first=Hamlet|title=\u0540\u0531\u0545\u0548\u0551 \u0546\u0531\u053d\u0546\u053b \u0531\u054d\u054f\u054e\u0531\u053e\u0538|url=https://www.academia.edu/41420558/%D5%80%D4%B1%D5%85%D5%88%D5%91_%D5%86%D4%B1%D4%BD%D5%86%D4%BB_%D4%B1%D5%8D%D5%8F%D5%8E%D4%B1%D4%BE%D4%B8|language=en}}</ref> It was greatly influenced by both Zoroastrianism and Hellenic paganism, but largely retained it's uniqueness<ref>{{Cite book|last=Petrosian|first=Armen|title=\u0531\u0580\u0561\u0574\u0561\u0566\u0564. \u0531\u0580\u0561\u0574\u0561\u0566\u0564\u056b \u0587 \u0570\u056b\u0576 \u0561\u057d\u057f\u057e\u0561\u056e\u0576\u0565\u0580\u056b \u0568\u0576\u0564\u0570\u0561\u0576\u0580\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0578\u0582\u0576\u0576\u0565\u0580\u0568.|publisher=|year=2008|isbn=|location=Yerevan|pages=80\u201381}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Russell|first=James R.|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=xhJIAAAAMAAJ&q=Tiridates+I+of+Armenia+zoroastrian+adherent&dq=Tiridates+I+of+Armenia+zoroastrian+adherent&hl=nl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjT3Oehzc3JAhULiCwKHW4OCWYQ6AEIHDAA|title=Zoroastrianism in Armenia|date=1987|publisher=Harvard University, Department of Near Eastern Languages and Civilizations|isbn=978-0-674-96850-9|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe rebirth of the religion can be traced back to the 19th century intellectualist ''Hetanosakan'' movement,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=\"Mehyan\" journal's analysis|url=http://lraber.asj-oa.am/2737/1/1980-3(14).pdf|journal=Mehyan|volume=|pages=74\u201382|via=}}</ref> most notable Hetanist being [[Daniel Varuzhan]], who advocated for the complete replacement of Christianity by Hetanism.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1982|title=Hetanism and Daniel Varuzhan|url=http://hpj.asj-oa.am/3682/1/1982-3(73).pdf|journal=Banasiragan|volume=|pages=73\u201385|via=}}</ref>\n\nIt gained major support in the early 20th century, with the doctrine of ''[[Tseghakron]]'' (\u0551\u0565\u0572\u0561\u056f\u0580\u0585\u0576, literally \"national religion\") of the philosopher and nationalist political theorist and warlord [[Garegin Nzhdeh]].{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=105}} It took an institutional form in 1991, just after the collapse of the [[Soviet Union]] in a climate of national reawakening, with the foundation of several Hetanist organizations.\n\nAccording to the 2011 Armenian census, 5139 people in the Republic of Armenia identified themselves as Hetanist, and the number is estimated to have doubled or even tripled in 10 years.<ref>https://www.armstat.am/file/article/sv_03_13a_520.pdf</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe word \u0540\u0565\u0569\u0561\u0576\u0578\u057d\u0578\u0582\u0569\u056b\u0582\u0576 (''Hetanosoutiwn'' comes from Greek ''\u1f14\u03b8\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2'', ''ethnos - \"Nation\"),'' and is formed with the root \u0540\u0565\u0569\u0561\u0576\u0578\u057d and suffix -\u0578\u0582\u0569\u056b\u0582\u0576.\n\nSince at least 11th century, the adherents of the movement have also called themselves ''Arordi'' or ''Arevordi'' ([[Armenian language|Armenian]]: ''\u0531\u0580\u0578\u0580\u0564\u056b, \u0531\u0580\u0565\u0582\u0578\u0580\u0564\u056b''), meaning sons of Sun.\n\n== History ==\n=== Origins ===\nThe Hetanist religion emerged from different religions of the region<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mkrtchyan|first=Aram|title=\u0531\u0580\u0561\u0574\u0561\u0566\u0564 \u0531\u057d\u057f\u056e\u0578 \u057a\u0561\u0577\u057f\u0561\u0574\u0578\u0582\u0576\u0584\u0568|url=https://www.academia.edu/22262274/%D4%B1%D6%80%D5%A1%D5%B4%D5%A1%D5%A6%D5%A4_%D4%B1%D5%BD%D5%BF%D5%AE%D5%B8_%D5%BA%D5%A1%D5%B7%D5%BF%D5%A1%D5%B4%D5%B8%D6%82%D5%B6%D6%84%D5%A8|language=en}}</ref> - most notably the religion of Aratta and ancient near east. The first organized proto-Hetanist religion was practiced in the Kingdom of Van (Urartu).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Melikishvili|first=|title=Religion in the Kingdom of Urartu|publisher=Publishing house of the academy of scienes and history of Georgian SSR|year=1954|isbn=|location=Tbilisi, Georgia|pages=445}}</ref> The religion of Urartu was a united pantheon of different armenian tribes and confederations, which was \"collected\" and standardized by kings [[Ishpuini of Urartu|Ishpuini]] and [[Menua]]. Although different Gods were worshiped, the central God [[\u1e2aaldi]] was the central deity of worship who had the authority over the entire universe and every being respectively. This semi-monotheism of \u1e2aaldism later developed into a more monotheistic religion of Hetanism.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hmakian|first=Sergei|title=The Religion of Urartu|publisher=History academia of the republic of Armenia|year=1990|isbn=|location=Yerevan|pages=84\u201385}}</ref> The trinitarian nature of the Urartian religion - with 3 chief Gods of [[\u1e2aaldi]], [[Teisheba]], [[Shivini]] also carried out to Hetanism, which is another argument in favor of \u1e2aaldic-Hetanist continuity theory.\n[[File:Head and left hand from a bronze cult statue of Anahita, a local goddess shown here in the guide of Aphrodite, 200-100 BC, British Museum (8167358544).jpg|thumb|302x302px|Anahit, Mother of Armenia]]\nThe first largely polytheistic form of Hetanism appeared after the collapse of Urartu and the emerging of the [[Orontid Armenia|first pan-armenian kingdom]] of [[Orontid dynasty|Orontids]] under [[Paruyr Skayordi]], who is considered the first [[king of Armenia]]. Under Orontids, the central Gods of Hetanism started to emerge - including [[Hayk]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vehi.net/istoriya/armenia/khorenaci/index.html|title=MOBCEC X\u041ePEHA\u0426\u0418, \"\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0410\u0440\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438\". \u041e \u0433 \u043b \u0430 \u0432 \u043b \u0435 \u043d \u0438 \u0435.|website=www.vehi.net|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref name=\"\u0531\u057d\u057f\u057e\u0561\u056e\u0576\u0565\u0580 \u0587 \u0570\u0565\u0580\u0578\u057d\u0576\u0565\u0580\">{{Cite web|url=http://armenianhouse.org/harutyunyan/04-gods.html|title=\u0531\u057d\u057f\u057e\u0561\u056e\u0576\u0565\u0580 \u0587 \u0570\u0565\u0580\u0578\u057d\u0576\u0565\u0580|website=armenianhouse.org|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>(later renamed Aramazd under Iranian influence), [[Ara the Handsome|Aray]](later [[Mihr]]),<ref name=\"\u0531\u057d\u057f\u057e\u0561\u056e\u0576\u0565\u0580 \u0587 \u0570\u0565\u0580\u0578\u057d\u0576\u0565\u0580\"/> [[Anahit]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Xanzadian|first=A.|title=Godess Anahita and her worship in Ancient Armenia|publisher=Yerevan State Academy|year=1985|isbn=|location=http://hpj.asj-oa.am/4209/1/1985-1(123).pdf|pages=}}</ref> and [[Vahagn]]<ref name=\"\u0531\u057d\u057f\u057e\u0561\u056e\u0576\u0565\u0580 \u0587 \u0570\u0565\u0580\u0578\u057d\u0576\u0565\u0580\"/>\n\n==== Formation ====\nThe final formation of the organized religion roughly corresponds to the reign of [[Tigranes II]], the first emperor([[king of kings]]) of Armenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://serials.flib.sci.am/Founders/H.Manandyan-Tigran%20B%20ev%20Hrom@/book/#page/1/mode/1up|title=bookreader demo|website=serials.flib.sci.am|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Around the first century BC, the complete theological and philosophical nature of Hetanism was formed, and the [[Armenian mythology|pantheon]] got it's final form.\n\nThe ''Mehians'' and priests concentrated on their hands the literature, schooling and education, regulation and domination of civil acts (birth, marriage, family), review of new laws, jurisdiction, even medicine. Thus, religion and priesthood represented a strong power inside the state. Religious institutions - ''Mehians'', had vast lands spanning from westernmost border of Armenia to [[Artsakh (historic province)|Artsakh]], as well as concentrated big amount of wealth, gold, silver and many more different luxuries, which were acquired from donations of [[Armenian nobility|princes, nobles, kings]] and even peasants.\n\nDue to the nature and teachings of their religion hetanist leaders and priests were always loyal and close to the king, thus their large influence in the affairs of the kingdom never brought up notable conflicts or destabilized the kingdom.\n\nThe image of supreme and eternal God, Ar/Ara appeared, all others God's turned merely into different manifestations of Ar, moving Hetanism into monotheistic world of religions.<ref name=\"Martirosyan\"/>\n\n=== Replacement by Christianity ===\nArmenia was one of the first regions where Christianity spread and flourished. The founders of Christian communities in Armenia were [[apostles]] [[Jude the Apostle|Thaddeus (Jude)]] and [[Bartholomew the Apostle|Bartholomew]] (dates of preaching [[AD 35|35]] AD - [[60 AD|60]] AD), who bear the titles of \"first illuminators of Armenia\".<ref name=\"akunq.net\">{{Cite web|url=https://akunq.net/am/?p=19885|title=1. \u0554\u0580\u056b\u057d\u057f\u0578\u0576\u0565\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0574\u0578\u0582\u057f\u0584\u0568 \u0540\u0561\u0575\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576 \u0587 \u057a\u0561\u057f\u0574\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0578\u0582\u0576\u0568|date=2012-04-09|website=\u0531\u0580\u0565\u0582\u0574\u057f\u0561\u0570\u0561\u0575\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576\u056b \u0565\u0582 \u0531\u0580\u0565\u0582\u0574\u057f\u0561\u0570\u0561\u0575\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0565\u0561\u0576 \u0540\u0561\u0580\u0581\u0565\u0580\u0578\u0582 \u0548\u0582\u057d\u0578\u0582\u0574\u0576\u0561\u057d\u056b\u0580\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0565\u0561\u0576 \u053f\u0565\u0564\u0580\u0578\u0576|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Before the 4th century, Christianity was not very popular amongst the Armenians and was spread only in small communities across the whole country. Nevertheless, the Christians were periodically persecuted. The persecution was especially harsh during the reign of king [[Sanatruk]].<ref name=\"akunq.net\"/>\n\nIn Armenia, the first center of Christianity is considered [[Mtsurq]], which was a city built by king Sanatruk. After the fall of the city to [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanid]] forces, the center moved to [[Ashtishat]], where it stayed until the fall of the Armenian kingdom.\n\nChristianity started growing rapidly under king [[Tiridates III of Armenia|Tiridates III the great]], under whom Christianity was declared official state religion\n\n==== Christianity as state religion ====\nAccording to a folk tradition recorded in [[Agatangeghos|Agatangeghos']] \"Armenian History\", when Tiridates III returned to [[Vagharshapat]] with the help of the Roman army in [[287 AD]] to reclaim his father's throne, on his way to the Yeriza settlement he offered a sacrifice to the goddess Anahit. [[Gregory the Illuminator|Grigor]], right hand of the king, refused attend the sacrifice because he was a Christian. The Armenian king also learns that Grigor was the son of prince Anak of Parthia who killed his father [[Khosrov IV of Armenia|Khosrov]]. Tiridates orders him to be thrown into the underground prison of [[Artaxata|Artashat]] (now known as \"[[Khor Virap]]\") as death penalty.<ref name=\"\u0531\u0563\u0561\u0569\u0561\u0576\u0563\u0565\u0572\u0578\u057d\">{{Cite book|last=\u0531\u0563\u0561\u0569\u0561\u0576\u0563\u0565\u0572\u0578\u057d|url=http://archive.org/details/agathangelos11|title=\u0531\u0563\u0561\u0569\u0561\u0576\u0563\u0565\u0572\u0578\u057d, \u054a\u0561\u057f\u0574\u0578\u0582\u0569\u056b\u0582\u0576 \u0540\u0561\u0575\u0578\u0581  (Agathange\u0142os, History of Armenia)}}</ref>[[File:Hetan priest officiating at Garni Temple, Armenia (1).png|thumb|left|alt=|A hetanist priest preaching]]In addition to Gregory, Hripsime's virgins also contributed substantially to the spread of Christianity and conversion to state religion in [[Greater Armenia]]. According to tradition, they were Roman virgins who were persecuted by [[Emperor Diocletian]] and fled eastwards. Among them were [[Hripsime|St. Hripsime]], St. Gayane, St. Shoghakat, St. Nune, and others with various saints up to 40 women. One of them, Nune, founded the Georgian Church. The virgins first worship at the Christ's sacred places (holy sites of Palestine) and then cross [[Edessa]] to Greater Armenia, settling near the capital of [[Vagharshapat]] in the tents. Tiridates, after seeing the beauty of young Christian virgin, wants to marry Hripsime, but she refuses. In response, in [[300 AD]], he ordered that all virgins be executed.<ref name=\"\u0531\u0563\u0561\u0569\u0561\u0576\u0563\u0565\u0572\u0578\u057d\"/>\n\nAfter the martyrdom of the virgins, the Armenian king suffers a severe [[fever]]. According to the folk traditions, the disease is considered to have made Tiridates into a swine. The king's sister, Khosrovidukht, repeatedly dreamed that Tirdates could only be treated by Grigor, who was a prisoner in Artashat. He is released from prison and solemnly admitted to the capital Vagharshapat. Gregory first summons the souls of the martyred virgins, then preaches the religion of Christianity for 66 days and then healed the king. Tiridates III and the whole court is baptized; Christianity proclaimed a state religion.\n\nThis tradition, albeit romantic, is considered to be a legend \u2014 Adopting Christianity was merely part of Tiridates' extensive policy of creating an Armenia independent both from Persia and Rome.<ref name=\"\u0531\u0563\u0561\u0569\u0561\u0576\u0563\u0565\u0572\u0578\u057d\"/><ref>{{Cite book|last=Richard|first=Hovannisian|url=https://books.google.am/books/about/The_Armenian_People_From_Ancient_to_Mode.html?id=p37O_KtaUKsC&redir_esc=y|title=The Armenian People From Ancient to Modern Times, Volume II: Foreign Dominion to Statehood: The Fifteenth Century to the Twentieth Century|date=1997-08-14|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-0-312-10168-8|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Hakobyan|first=Aleqsan|url=https://www.academia.edu/34569879/ARMENIA_AND_CHRISTIAN_CAUCASUS|title=ARMENIA AND CHRISTIAN CAUCASUS|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Persecution by Christians ===\nAfter the embracement of Christianity, more than half of the armenian population was still Hetanist. The government soon adopted a harsh anti-Hetanist policy.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=THOMSON|first=ROBERT W.|date=1988|title=Mission, Conversion, and Christianization: The Armenian Example|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/41036303|journal=Harvard Ukrainian Studies|volume=12/13|pages=28\u201345|issn=0363-5570}}</ref> Thousands of ancient temples were destroyed. Priests were killed and entire villages which refused to be converted were destroyed.\n\nThe last pagan leader, Arzan, was recklessly murdered at the entrance of a temple.\n\nThe only surviving temple in Armenia is Garni temple.<ref name=\"armenianweekly.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://armenianweekly.com/2019/11/27/the-remnants-of-armenias-pagan-past/|title=The Remnants of Armenia's Pagan Past|date=2019-11-27|website=The Armenian Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Today, It is considered a \"symbol of Armenia\u2019s classical past as well as its deep historical ties to the civilizations of Greece and Rome.\" In ancient and medieval times, the areas surrounding the temple were utilized as a royal garrison and military fortress.\n\nIn the city of Artashat, southeast of the capital, Yerevan, Mithraic temple ruins, built from black marble, have been unearthed as well.<ref name=\"armenianweekly.com\"/>\n\nHetanism was a prominent religion in Armenia before renaissance era. The last Hetanist community survived until the 1920s<ref>{{Cite book|last=Roald|first=Anne Sofie|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Ab0yAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA313&dq=armenians+were+zoroastrian&hl=nl&sa=X&ved=0CEYQ6AEwBWoVChMI49KPt6KSxgIVAo4sCh1evgDN#v=onepage&q=armenians%20were%20zoroastrian&f=false|title=Religious Minorities in the Middle East: Domination, Self-Empowerment, Accommodation|last2=Longva|first2=Anh Nga|date=2011-11-11|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-21684-6|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Rebirth ==\n\n=== 19th century hetanist movement ===\nAt the peak of [[armenian national awakening]], armenian intellectuals started seeing Hetanism as a viable and even desirable alternative to the religion of Christianity.<ref name=\":0\" /> The most prominent advocate of the national conversion was [[Daniel Varuzhan]],<ref name=\":0\" /> one of the most popular poets of Armenia and a martyr of the [[Armenian genocide]]. Varuzhan and his fellow intellectualists organized the first Armenian hetanist group/organization - ''Mehian,'' which printed articles about armenian nationalism and Hetanism. According to the ideology of Varuzhan and his followers, the Christian ideology of \"[[Turn the other cheek|turning the cheek]]\" has become a disaster for the Armenian nation, which before was a great nation with brave soldiers and wise rulers. According to them, the Armenian nation fell low after the acceptance of Christianity and became a slave to the west and the east.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Garegin Nzhdeh ===\n[[File:Garegin_Nzhdeh_5.jpg|thumb|Garegin Nzhdeh, the ideologue of an Armenian \"national religion\".]]\n\n[[Garegin Nzhdeh]] is considered one of the most important figures of the armenian history. He was a philosopher, statesman and ''[[Armenian fedayi|fedayi]]'' of the first half of the twentieth century, who left an enduring legacy in the history of [[Armenia]], and is still one of the driving forces of [[Armenian nationalism]].{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=105}} People praised him as the \"prophet of the Armenians\".{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=266}} Nzhdeh founded a movement named ''[[Tseghakron]]'' (\"religion of the nation\"), which was among the core doctrines of the [[Armenian Youth Federation]].{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=105}} In Nzhdeh's poetic mythology, the Armenian nation is identified as [[Atlas (mythology)|Atlas]] upholding the ordered world,{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=105}} and praised [[Hayk]], the mythical patriarch of the [[Armenians]], and [[Vahagn]], the fire and warrior god \"[[Proto-Indo-European religion#Dragon or serpent|fighter of the serpent]]\", and believed Hetanism would awaken the Armenian nation and raise its spirit. Nzhdeh's movement took place in the aftermath of the [[Armenian Genocide]] of 1915.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=105}}\n\nThe first organisation of Armenian Native Faith, the \"Order of the Children of Ari\" (or \"Ara\"; ''Arordineri Ukht'' in [[Armenian language|Armenian]]) was established in 1991 by the armenologist Slak (Eduard) Kakosyan (1936\u20132005).{{sfnm|1a1=Antonyan|1y=2010|1p=105|2a1=Siekierski|2a2=Antonyan|2y=2013|2p=266}} He belonged to a generation of Armenian dissidents and was exiled in the 1970s from [[Armenian Soviet Socialist Republic|Soviet Armenia]]; in 1979 he fled to the [[United States]] where he became familiar with the ideas of [[Garegin Nzhdeh]] (1886\u20131955).{{sfnm|1a1=Antonyan|1y=2010|1p=105|2a1=Siekierski|2a2=Antonyan|2y=2013|2p=266}}\n\nAccording to modern hetanists, Garegin Nzhdeh is [[Apotheosis|deified]] as an incarnation of Vahagn, the re-establisher of the true faith of the Armenians and of the armenian values.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=106}}\n\n=== 1990s: Establishment of the Children of Ari ===\nThe hetanists re-emerged after [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union|the collapse of the soviet union]]. They began to hold rituals on traditional Armenian holidays. The [[Temple of Garni]] became the centre of the community, a council of priests was set up in order to manage the organisation and the rites.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=106, note 7}} During the 1990s, the group reached visibility in wider Armenian society.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=107}} According to the scholar Yulia Antonyan, the emergence of the Armenian Native Faith is attributable to the same causes which led to the rise of other modern religious movements, but also [[Hinduism|Hindu]] and [[Protestantism|Protestant]] movements, in the other post-Soviet countries: The Armenian Native Faith represents the indigenous answer to the social and cultural upheavals which followed the collapse of Soviet society and of its atheist and materialist ideology.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=104}}\n\n=== Republican Party support and grassroots spread ===\n[[File:Hetan_priest_officiating_at_Garni_Temple,_Armenia_13.jpg|thumb|An Arordiner priest.]]\n[[Ashot Navasardyan]] (1950\u20131997) and [[Andranik Margaryan]] (1949\u20132007), founding fathers of the [[Republican Party of Armenia]], were hetanists like many other members of the party and took part in the very first ritual at the Temple of Garni.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=270}} The Armenian government provides financial support for the Children of Ari.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=107}} Arordiner festivals are celebrated in some regions with the support of local municipalities.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=107, note 8}} Despite this strong link with the nationalist political scene, hetanism itself does not have a political orientation, and the priests are forbidden from joining any political party.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=107}}\n\nAlthough it started among the Armenian intellectual elites as a means to reawaken Armenian identity, in most recent times the Armenian Native Faith movement has expanded its contingent of adherents among the provincial and rural populations,{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=107}} and among the [[Armenian diaspora]].{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=108}} Besides the philosophical approach of the intellectuals, the common people are driven to the Armenian Native Faith by various reasons, ranging from [[mysticism]] to a sentimental devotion to the gods. Antonyan documented the case of a thirty-five years-old woman who believed to be [[Infertility|infertile]], and who joined the Armenian Native Faith movement after she allegedly became pregnant by praying to Anahit, goddess of fertility, and to Astghik, goddess of love and beauty.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=108}} The woman gave her daughter the name \"Nana\", another name of the goddess of fertility.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=109}}\n\nLocal Arordiner communities have been organised in villages outside the capital [[Yerevan]]. The structure of the Order of the Children of Ari, and of the local communities themselves, is characterised by a clear hierarchy, with the council of priests, led by an elected chief, handling the organisation of all activities. The highest position within the hierarchy is that of the supreme priest, which has remained vacant since Slak Kakosyan's death in 2005.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|pp=267\u2013268}}\n\n== Beliefs ==\n\n=== Theology and cosmology ===\n[[File:Aramazd.jpg|left|thumb|Statue of God Ar]]\n\n==== Ar and Ara ====\nThe theology of Hetanism is a [[monism]]: According to the faith, in the beginning was the Ar, who was the creator of the reality .{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=110}} The Ar is the impersonal, without qualities, [[Transcendence (religion)|transcendent]] principle begetting the universe, the universal ideal and a conscience.{{sfnm|1a1=Antonyan|1y=2010|1p=110|2a1=Siekierski|2a2=Antonyan|2y=2013|2p=266}} According to Hetanists, ''Ar'' is the life-giving word root,{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=115}} and it is the origin of words like, for instance, ''art'' (\"arable\", \"cultivation\"; culture, art), ''aryyun'' (\"blood\"), ''argand'' (\"womb\"), ''armat'' (\"root\"), ''arka'' (\"king\"), ''ara'' (\"male\"), ''Arev'' (the Sun), ''Ara'' (manifested Ar), ''Ari'' (acting with Ar), ''Chari'' (opposing Ar).{{sfnm|1a1=Antonyan|1y=2010|1p=115|2a1=Siekierski|2a2=Antonyan|2y=2013|2p=271}} The \"essence of things\" and their \"perfection\" is represented by ''[[swastika]]'' motifs.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=269}}\n\n==== Deities ====\nThe different deities are beneath the supreme Ar. They are not separate beings, but merely different manifestations of Ar. Though monotheistic in theology, the Armenian Native Faith is mostly [[Polytheism|polytheistic]] in practice.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=116}} The gods of the Arordiners include:{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=271}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! style=\"padding:0.5em 0.5em;white-space:nowrap;\" |Name\n! style=\"padding:0.5em 0.5em;white-space:nowrap;\" |Also known as\n!Details\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |[[Hayk]]\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Aramazd, Khaldi\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |The primary God of ancient armenians, head of the pantheon, manifestation of fatherhood, the earth and the sky. He was called almighty and all-father. His temple was in Kamakh, Ani province, which also was a grave for Armenian kings of the [[Artaxiad|artaxiad dynasty of Armenia.]] Along with Anahit and Vahagn contituted the holy triad.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Anahit\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Teisheba\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Daughter of Aramazd. She was the mother god, and was pictured with a long veil coming down from her hair, she was referenced to as the great mother Anahit, the good-bringer, maifestation of motherhood and the personofication and mother-protector of Armenia. It is due to Anahit that the Armenian nation still exists and will continue to live. Armenian kings, before enacting decisions or going to wars would ask the goddess for approval and tips, to succee in what they plan. She was also the devine manifestation  and personofication of motherhood and fertility.\nTogether with Aramazd and Vahagn she constituted the holy triad.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Vahagn\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Aray, Demetr\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |The third God of the pantheon was Vahagn, who was described in ancient armenian poems as a bright and red-haired teen with fire-like hair and beard and eyes that shined like the sun. He is the dying and reborning God, who is born from the union of water and fire, soil and the sky. \nHe is the most popular Armenian God and is a notable figure in the armenian consicene even nowadays.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Astghik\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Astghik, Astlik\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Astghik was the lover of Vahagn and was considered his polar opposite. She was the goddess of love and water. According to folk tradition, Vahagn met Astghik in the field of Ararat. Their marriage was a blessing for the earth, and soon holy rain started pouring from the sky fertilizing the lands.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Nane\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Next to nothing is known about her, although her popularity was big. She was most likely a goddess of war.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Ara the Beautiful\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Ara\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |He was the manifestation of the spring, God of land fertility and the bringer of prosperity.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Mihr\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Shivini\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Mihr was the God of the sun-light. Not to be confused with the sun-god Aramazd.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Tir\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Tyur\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Tir was the manifestation of knowledge, enlightenment and writing.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Vanatur\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Amanor\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Vanatur was the manifestation of friendlyness\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Spandaramet\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Spandaramet was the manifestation of the underground world. In opposition to almost all other religions in the world, Armenians believed that the soil brings life, not death. The underground was where the root of the life starts, so Spandaramet is the manifestation of life, not death.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Tarqu\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Tork Angegh\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Legendary defender of Armenia, who threw rocks at Greek ships trying to invade Armenia. Manifestation of defence and struggle.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Grogh\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Grogh\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Bringer of death.\n|}\nAramazd, Vahagn and Anahit together constituted the holy trinity of the hetanist religion. Contrary to other religions of the world, Armenains didn't have a conception of hell or bad Gods. All bad in the world comes from humanity, and the underground is root of life.\n\nArmenians consider holy the water, lions, apricot tree and fire.\n\n=== Afterlife and eschatology ===\nHetanists have a cyclical view of reality, and they believe in the [[reincarnation]] of individual souls through the genetic lineage. That is to say, men are believed to come back to life in the following generations of their own descendants, in the kin which they begot while living.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=273}} According to hetanist doctrines, the entire world goes through similar cycles, from the smaller ones represented by the days and the years, to the greatest ones represented by eras of ten thousand years.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|pp=273\u2013274}}\n\nThe struggle between light and dark unfolds through the cycle of each era: Order and connection with the ancestors prevail during the world's summer and spring; while disorder, confusion and forsaking of the ancestral roots prevail during the world's autumn and winter. In the latter period, beings are not in harmony with Ar, they are not nourished by cosmic energy. At the darkest stage of history, though, which according to Arordiners corresponds to the current times, Vahagn is born again and brings the warrior forces back to life.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|pp=273\u2013274}}\n\n=== The ''Ukhtagirk'' ===\n''Ukhtagirk'', the holy book of the Armenian Native Faith, may be translated as \"Book of Vows\". It was the life work of Slak Kakosyan, who finished the manuscript just before his death in 2005.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=271}} Kakosyan, however, is not the \"author\" of the ''Ukhtagirk'', but rather the \"recorder\" of oral traditions,{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=115}} its \"compiler\" (''kazmogh'').{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=271}} The book was officially proclaimed the holy text of the Order of the Children of Ari in 2000, a couple of years before its completion, when the religious organisation was officially registered by the Armenian state.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=271}}\n\nThe book is divided into seven parts: \u2460 ''Astvatsashoonch'' (\"Dictionary\"), which explains the Armenian language as a mystical system of symbols related to the root ''Ar''; \u2461 ''Tsagumnaran'' (\"Genesis\"), which explains in mythical terms the origin of the world, the gods and mankind; \u2462 ''Avetaran'' (\"Book of Testaments\") and \u2463 ''Dzonaran'' (\"Book of Odes\"), which deal with philosophical and ontological categories to explain reality and values; \u2464 ''Veharan'' (\"Book of Greatness\") and \u2465 ''Patgamaran'' (\"Book of Commandments\"), which present mythologised descriptions of Garegin Nzhdeh's life and ideas, respectively; and the seventh and last chapter, \u2466 ''Hymnergaran'' (\"Book of Hymns\"), which is a collection of poems written by Kakosyan and his followers, as well as by authors of the nineteenth and early twentieth century. The mythological parts about creation rely upon Armenian medieval sources and folk knowledge.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=271\u2013272}}\n\nChanting ritual texts from the book is considered to procure mystical experiences, and the physical book itself is crucial for some ritual activities, such as wedding ceremonies, in which the rings are passed to the bride and groom on top of a copy of the ''Ukhtagirk''.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=273}} At the same time, Arordiners do not consider their book unquestionable, but the text is open to corrections as required by changing circumstances. This attitude is supported by a declaration of Slak Kakosyan himself, who conceived the book in the terms of a changeful and adaptable truth.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=273}}\n\n== Practices ==\n[[File:Hetan_priest_officiating_at_Garni_Temple,_Armenia_30.jpg|thumb|300x300px|People gathered on the occasion of a public ceremony at the Temple of Garni.]]\nArmenian Native Faith practices, rituals and representations mostly rely on the instructions given by the ''Ukhtagirk''.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=110}} For instance, it is common for the priests to make pilgrimage to [[Khustup|Mount Khustup]], where, according to the book, Garegin Nzhdeh experienced the presence of the god Vahagn.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=109}} The priests' aim is to replicate such experience.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=109}} The veneration of Nzhdeh and the pilgrimage to his burial site, which is located on the slopes of the Khustup, is also slowly developing within the larger community of Hetanists.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=110, note 14}} In general, mountains are revered as holy, so, besides Khustup, other mountains, including [[Mount Ararat]] and [[Mount Aragats]], function as pilgrimage destination for hetanists.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|pp=275, 278}}\n\n=== Rituals ===\nArmenian Native Faith rituals include the yearly ceremonies performed on Armenian traditional holidays, and three [[rites of passage]]: The ''knunk'', a complex ritual of initiation; the ''psak'', that is wedding; and death rituals.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=121}} The death rituals require the [[cremation]] of the body,{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=121}} and its return to the four elements. Fire is symbolised by the cremation itself; then the ashes are divided into three parts, of which one is buried in the earth, one is scattered in the air of the [[Garni Gorge]], and the third one is poured in the water of the Garni River.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=277}} Afterwards, the deceased is memorialised by the collective lighting of a torch.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=278}} The first Arordiner to be cremated was Kakosyan himself,when cremation is illegal in Armenia. Later, hetanists obtained by the state the right to cremate their dead.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=277}}[[File:Hetan_initiation_ritual_(0).PNG|thumb|Stage of a ''knunk'' ritual.|alt=|left]]The Armenian term ''knunk'' may be translated as \"conversion\" or \"reversion\" (to the native way of life).{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=108, note 11}} Yulia Antonyan observed that about ten to twenty people take part to each ''knunk'' ritual, which is held on the occasion of the public ceremonies at the Temple of Garni. At the same time, there are many hetanists who believe that in order to worship the native gods of Armenia it is not necessary to undergo an official conversion.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=108, note 11}}\n\n=== Temples and idols ===\nArordiner public ceremonies and rituals are held at ancient sacred places, which are often in ruins.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=119}} The re-appropriation of churches that were built on native sacred sites is also common.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=119}} The most important of these sites is the first-century Temple of Garni, a temple which was rebuilt in 1975, which has become the main ceremonial center for the Armenian Native Faith movement.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=119}}\n\nThe Arordiners have reconsecrated the temple to Vahagn, although historically it was dedicated to Mihr. They have also been given approval for the rearrangement of the compound, in order for it to match the ideal structure of ancient Armenian sanctuaries.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=119}} They have added a holy spring dedicated to Slak Kakosyan and a wood of [[apricot]] trees, the holy tree of Armenian Native Faith. The temple is now organised into three sacred spaces: The first is the sacred spring, the second one is the temple proper, and the third one is the holy wood, located on a hillock.{{sfnm|1a1=Antonyan|1y=2010|1p=119|2a1=Siekierski|2a2=Antonyan|2y=2013|2pp=275\u2013277}} The rituals at the Temple of Garni take place following a route which starts from the spring, passes through the temple, and endly reaches the holy wood.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=119}} Downhill, each newly established local Arordiner community plants a tree, symbolising the unity and well-being of the group itself. These holy trees are adorned with ribbons and handkerchiefs symbolising one's requests to the gods.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|pp=275\u2013277}}\n\nBesides the Temple of Garni, other sites considered holy by the Arordiners and used for their rituals include the [[Metsamor Castle]] (third millennium BCE), considered a site for the cult of the mother goddess, the [[Erebuni Fortress]] (eighth century BCE), [[Shengavit Settlement|Shengavit]] (fourth to second millennium BCE) and [[Zorats Karer]] (third millennium BCE), and the mountains.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|pp=275\u2013277}} Sculptures representing the gods which have been realised within the context of modern Armenian Native Faith are inspired by both historical specimens and the creativity of modern artists.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=119}}\n\n=== Holidays ===\nThe Arordiners celebrate a number of holidays:{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=116}} Terendez, Zatik, Hambardzum, [[Vardavar]] and Khaghoghorhnek. To these holy days they add a holy day for the remembrance of ancestors (20 September), the Birth of Vahagn (21 March), the Birth of Mihr (22 December) and the Navasard, the New Year celebrated in August.\n\n== Poetry and legends ==\nSeveral hetanist legends and poems have survived till our days. One of the best examples of this is ''Vahagni tsnund, t''he birth of Vahagn, recorded by Moses of Chorene\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Armenian\n!Transliteration\n!English translation\n|-\n|''\u0535\u0580\u056f\u0576\u0567\u0580 \u0565\u0580\u056f\u056b\u0576, \u0565\u0580\u056f\u0576\u0567\u0580 \u0565\u0580\u056f\u056b\u0580,''\n\n''\u0535\u0580\u056f\u0576\u0567\u0580 \u0587 \u056e\u0578\u057e\u0576 \u056e\u056b\u0580\u0561\u0576\u056b.''\n\n''\u0535\u0580\u056f\u0576 \u056b \u056e\u0578\u057e\u0578\u0582\u0576 \u0578\u0582\u0576\u0567\u0580 \u0587 \u0566\u056f\u0561\u0580\u0574\u0580\u056b\u056f\u0576 \u0565\u0572\u0565\u0563\u0576\u056b\u056f.''\n\n''\u0538\u0576\u0564 \u0565\u0572\u0565\u0563\u0561\u0576 \u0583\u0578\u0572 \u056e\u0578\u0582\u056d \u0565\u056c\u0561\u0576\u0567\u0580,''\n\n''\u0538\u0576\u0564 \u0565\u0572\u0565\u0563\u0561\u0576 \u0583\u0578\u0572 \u0562\u0578\u0581 \u0565\u056c\u0561\u0576\u0567\u0580,''\n\n''\u0535\u0582 \u056b \u0562\u0578\u0581\u0578\u0575\u0576 \u057e\u0561\u0566\u0567\u0580 \u056d\u0561\u0580\u057f\u0565\u0561\u0577 \u057a\u0561\u057f\u0561\u0576\u0565\u056f\u056b\u056f.''\n\n''\u0546\u0561 \u0570\u0578\u0582\u0580 \u0570\u0565\u0580 \u0578\u0582\u0576\u0567\u0580,''\n\n''\u0532\u0578\u0581 \u0578\u0582\u0576\u0567\u0580 \u0574\u0585\u0580\u0578\u0582\u057d,''\n\n''\u0535\u0582 \u0561\u0579\u0584\u0578\u0582\u0576\u0584\u0576 \u0567\u056b\u0576 \u0561\u0580\u0565\u0563\u0561\u056f\u0578\u0582\u0576\u0584\u0589''\n|''Yerkneer Yerkin, yerkneer yerkir''\n\n''Yerkneer yew tsovn tsirani''\n\n''Yerkn i-tsovun uner yev ezkarmrikn ellgenik''\n\n''End yellegan poll tsoux yelaner,''\n\n''End yellgedan poll bots yerlaner''\n\n''Yew i-botsoyn vazer xarteash patanekik,''\n\n''Na hur her uner''\n\n''Bots uner morus''\n\n''Yev Achqoonq ein aregaqonq''\n|\n: ''In travail were heaven and earth,''\n\n: ''In travail, too, the purple sea!''\n\n: ''The travail held in the sea the small red reed.''\n\n: ''Through the hollow of the stalk came forth smoke,''\n\n: ''Through the hollow of the stalk came forth flame,''\n\n: ''And out of the flame a youth ran!''\n\n: ''Fiery hair had he,''\n\n: ''Ay, too, he had flaming beard,''\n\n: ''And his eyes, they were as suns!''\n|}\n\n=== Hayk and Bel ===\nOne of the most ancient and famous traditions is the tradition of the battle of Hayk, founder of the armenian nation, and Bel, a Babylonian tyrant.\n\nIn Moses of Chorene's account, Hayk son of [[Togarmah|Torgom]] had a child named [[Armanak (disambiguation)|Armanak]] while he was living in [[Babylon]]. After the arrogant [[Titan (mythology)|Titanid]] [[Belus (Babylonian)|Bel]] made himself king over all, Hayk emigrated to the region near [[Mount Ararat]]. Hayk relocated near Mount Ararat with an extended household of at least 300 and settled there, founding a village he named ''Haykashen''. On the way he had left a detachment in another settlement with his grandson Kadmos. Bel sent one of his sons to entreat him to return, but was refused. Bel decided to march against him with a massive force, but Hayk was warned ahead of time by Kadmos of his pending approach. He assembled his own army along the shore of [[Lake Van]] and told them that they must defeat and kill Bel, or die trying to do so, rather than become his slaves. In his writings Moses states that:<blockquote>\u201c Hayk was a handsome, friendly man, with curly hair, sparkling eyes, and strong arms. He was a man of giant stature, a mighty archer and fearless warrior. Hayk and his people, from the time of their forefathers [[Noah]] and [[Japheth]], had migrated south toward the warmer lands near Babylon. In that land there ruled a wicked giant, Bel. Bel tried to impose his tyranny upon Hayk's people. But proud Hayk refused to submit to Bel. As soon as his son Aramaniak was born, Hayk rose up and led his people northward into the land of [[Ayrarat|Ararad]]. At the foot of the mountain he built a village and gave it his name, calling Haykashen. \u201d</blockquote>Hayk and his men soon discovered Bel's army positioned in a mountain pass (Moses of Chorene located the site as [[Dastakert]]), with the king in the [[Vanguard (military formation)|vanguard]].\n\nAt ''Dyutsaznamart'' ([[Armenian language|Armenian]]: \u0534\u0575\u0578\u0582\u0581\u0561\u0566\u0576\u0561\u0574\u0561\u0580\u057f, \"Battle of Giants\"), near [[Julamerk]] southeast of [[Lake Van]], on 11 August 2492 BC (according to the Armenian traditional chronology of the first month of the [[Armenian calendar]], Navasard or 2107 BC (according to \"The Chronological table\" of [[Mikael Chamchian]]), Hayk slew Bel with a nearly impossible shot using a long bow, sending the king's forces into disarray.\n\nThe hill where Bel with his warriors fell, Hayk named ''Gerezmank'' meaning \"tombs\". He embalmed the corpse of Bel and ordered it to be taken to Hark where it was to be buried in a high place in the view of the wives and sons of the king.\n\nSoon after, Hayk established the fortress of [[Haykaberd]] at the battle site and the town of Haykashen in the Armenian province of [[Vaspurakan]] (modern-day Turkey). He named the region of the battle ''Hayk'', and the site of the battle Hayots Dzor.\n\n=== Ara the handsome ===\nAnother ancient Armenian legend is connected with Ara the beautiful, God of spring and rebirth.\n\nAccording to the legend, Shamiram had fallen in love with the handsome Ara and asked him to marry her. When Ara refused, Semiramis, in the heat of passion, gathered the armies of [[Assyria]] and marched against Armenia. During the battle Semiramis was victorious, but Ara was slain despite her orders to capture him alive. To avoid continuous warfare with the Armenians, Shamiram, reputed to be a sorceress, took his body and prayed to the gods to raise Ara from the dead. When the Armenians advanced to avenge their leader, Shamiram disguised one of her lovers as Ara and spread the rumor that the gods had brought Ara back to life, convincing the Armenians not to continue the war. Nevertheless, Ara is reborn later and gets his revenge on the Assyrian queen.{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n\nIt was also reported that a village called Lezk, near [[Van, Turkey|Van]], traditionally held that it was Ara's place of resurrection.{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== Torq Angegh ===\nTorq was considered one of [[Hayk]]'s great-grandsons and reportedly represented as an unattractive male figure. He is mentioned by Armenian 5th Century historian [[Movses Khorenatsi]] and considered one of the significant deities of the Armenian pantheon. Taken in the context of [[Proto-Indo-Europeans|Proto-Indo-European]] religions, it is conceivable that an etymological connection with [[Norse mythology|Norse]] god [[Thor]]/Tyr is more than a simple coincidence. According to tradition, with his immense strength he threw rocks at the invading Greek navy, keeping the shores of Armenia safe.\n\n== Relations with Christianity ==\n[[File:\u054a\u0561\u0580_\u0533\u0561\u057c\u0576\u0578\u0582\u0574.jpg|thumb|A ritual dance at the Temple of Garni.]]\nThe relations between the Armenian Native Faith movement and the [[Armenian Apostolic Church]] have been good and collaborative, since both share the common interest of protecting and promoting Armenian identity, especially against what are perceived as disruptive foreign forces infiltrating the country, such as Protestants, [[Jehovah's Witnesses]] and [[Mormonism|Mormons]].{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=268}} The Armenian Apostolic Church generally sees Arordiners as allies. A high-ranking spokesman of the Armenian Apostolic Church declared:{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=268}}\n{{Quote|The Armenian Church has an unequivocal stance on sectarians (i.e. Protestants et al.), but we do not interfere into hetanos affairs.}}\nSimilarly, the head of an Armenian institution catering to the victims of destructive cults declared:{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=268}}\n{{Quote|The Armenian nation must remember its pre-Christian past, and Ara's Children help them remember. They also support the Armenian Apostolic Church in its fight against destructive sects.}}\nArmenian Native Faith believers' attitude towards Christianity oscillates between two positions: The critique of the religion's role in Armenian history, and the conditional acceptance of the Armenian Apostolic Church as a national institution.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=268}} Christianity is criticised for having destroyed the rich and highly developed ancient Armenian culture, replacing the values of courage, martial spirit and honour with those of humility, obedience and modesty, thus causing the collapse of Armenian statehood and condemning the nation to centuries of subordination to foreign powers, migrations, persecutions and massacres.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=268}} According to the strongest accusations, Christianity is responsible for the \"first genocide of the Armenians\", which coincided with its forceful introduction in the fourth century.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=269}}\n\nAt the same time, the Armenian Apostolic Church is considered an institution peculiar to the Armenian nation, and the fruit of a synthesis of Christian and indigenous elements, in which the former represent just the surface. The hetanists find proof of this in the Church's prayers devoted to the Sun and light, in Church festivals overlapping indigenous Armenian festivals, and in the practice of ''matagh'', Christian animal sacrifice. Moreover, the hetanists believe that the Armenian alphabet, which Church historiography holds to have been invented by the monk Mesrop Mahtots, is actually an elaboration of ancient Armenian symbolism based on the motif of the ''[[swastika]]''.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=269}}\n\nHetanists generally do not have problems visiting Armenian churches and treating them as holy places, since many of them were built on the site of pre-Christian temples. Furthermore, some figures of the history of the Armenian Apostolic Church are revered as Hetanists in disguise: The ''[[Catholicos|catholicoi]]'' (high-ranking bishops) Vazgen I (in charge 1954\u20131994) and Garegin I (1995\u20131999). The former was a supporter of Nzhdeh and on his tombstone, instead of a cross, he has a letter of the Armenian alphabet which is considered a variant of the ''swastika'' and symbolic of seven Armenian gods. The latter is said to have visited Garni before his death and, despite being terminally ill, to have walked alone to the temple.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=269}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n<references group=\"\" responsive=\"0\"></references>\n\n=== Sources ===\n\n* {{cite contribution|last1=Siekierski|first1=Konrad|last2=Antonyan|first2=Yulia|year=2013|contribution=A Neopagan Movement in Armenia: the Children of Ara|title=Modern Pagan and Native Faith Movements in Central and Eastern Europe|editor1=Kaarina Aitamurto|editor2=Scott Simpson|isbn=9781844656622|location=Durham|publisher=Acumen|pages=266\u2013282|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Antonyan|first=Yulia|year=2010|title='Re-creation' of a Religion: Neo-paganism in Armenia|url=https://www.academia.edu/191429|journal=Laboratorium|language=ru|location=Saint-Petersburg|pages=103\u2013128|ref=harv|number=1}}\n* {{cite contribution|last=Antonyan|language=hy|archivedate=16 April 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416201021/http://old.brusov.am/docs/cank-Identity_Articles_final.pdf|accessdate=16 April 2018|date=|ref=harv|pages=23\u201330|isbn=9789993079934|first=Yulia|location=Yerevan|publisher=Lingva|url=http://old.brusov.am/docs/cank-Identity_Articles_final.pdf|title=Identities and Changing World, Proceedings of International Conference|contribution=The Aryan Myth and the New Armenian Paganism|year=2008|author-mask={{long dash}}|url-status=dead}}\n\n; Armenian neoshamanism\n\n* {{cite contribution|last=Antonyan|first=Yulia|year=2008|contribution=Magical and Healing Practices in Contemporary Urban Environment (in Armenian Cities of Yerevan, Gyumri, and Vanadzor|title=Figuring the South Caucasus: Societies and Environment|publisher=Heinrich B\u00f6ll Foundation|location=Tbilisi|isbn=9789941900914|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Antonyan|first=Yulia|author-mask={{long dash}}|year=2006|title=On the Name and Origins of 'Chopchi' Healing Practices|journal=Bulletin of Armenian Studies|pages=61\u201366|ref=harv|number=1}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Antonyan|first=Yulia|author-mask={{long dash}}|year=2003|title=Pre-Christian Healers in a Christian Society|journal=Cultural Survival Quarterly|volume=27|ref=harv|number=2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://arordiukht.do.am/ Order of the Children of Ari] \u2014 official website\n* [http://www.hayary.org/ Armenian Aryan Congregation] \u2014 official website\n\n{{Neopaganism}}\n\n[[Category:Modern Pagan traditions]]\n[[Category:Neopaganism in Europe]]\n[[Category:Neopaganism by country]]\n[[Category:Religion in Armenia]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Hetanism}}\n{{short description|Armenian Neopaganism}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{sidebar\n|name = Armenian Native Faith\n|title = [[Hetanism]]<br />and [[Armenian mythology]]\n|image = [[File:Left-Facing Armenian Eternity Sign UC 058E SVG.svg|150px]]\n|caption = Arevakhach, symbol of hetanism\n|captionstyle = font-style:italic\n|headingstyle = background:#B0CBAC\n|contentclass = hlist\n\n|heading1 = Practices\n|content1 =\n* [[Pantheism]]\n* Semi-[[Polytheistic]] [[Monotheism]]\n* [[Matagh]]\n* [[Knunk]]\n* [[Vardavar]]\n* [[Fire worship]]\n* [[List of water deities|Water woship]]\n* [[Veneration of the dead|Worship of ancestors]]\n\n|heading2 = Places\n|content2 =\n* [[Garni temple]]\n* [[Zorats qarer]]\n* [[Khustup mountain]]\n\n|heading3 = Deities and beings\n|content3 =\n* Ar\n* [[Hayk]] (Aramazd)\n* [[Anahit]]\n* [[Vahagn]]\n* [[Tir]]\n* [[Mihr]]\n* [[Vanatur]]\n* [[Ara the Beautiful]]\n* [[Turk' Angegh]]\n* [[Nane]]\n* [[Astghik]]\n* [[Spandaramet]]\n* [[Barshamin]]\n|heading4 = Ancient Sources\n|content4 =\n* [[Moses of Chorene]]\n* [[Anania Shirakatsi]]\n* [[Ukhtagirq]]\n\n}}\n'''Hetanism''' ([[Armenian language|Armenian]]: \u0540\u0565\u0569\u0561\u0576\u0578\u057d\u0578\u0582\u0569\u056b\u0582\u0576 ''Hetanosutiwn'') or '''Armenian native faith''', was the dominant<ref name=\"Romeny 2010\">{{Cite book|last=Romeny|first=R. B. ter Haar|url=https://books.google.dk/books?id=ZxDi924k4RIC&vq=|title=Religious Origins of Nations?: The Christian Communities of the Middle East|date=2010|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-17375-0|language=en}}</ref> ethnic religion of Armenia before the adoption of [[Christianity]] in 301 AD.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Armen Petrosyan|url=http://archive.org/details/2015PetrosyanProblemsOfArmenianPrehistory|title=Problems of Armenian Prehistory. Myth, Language, History|language=English}}</ref><ref name=\"Romeny 2010\"/><ref>{{Cite book|last=Petrosyan|first=Armen|url=https://www.academia.edu/3656244/The_Indo-European_and_Ancient_Near_Eastern_Sources_of_the_Armenian_Epic._Washington_D.C._2002|title=The Indo-European and Ancient Near Eastern Sources of the Armenian Epic. Washington D.C. 2002|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Antonyan|first=Yulia|date=|title=\u0412\u043e\u0441\u0441\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0440\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0433\u0438\u0438: \u041d\u0435\u043e\u044f\u0437\u044b\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0432 \u0410\u0440\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 (&quot;Re-creation&quot; of a religion: neo-paganism in Armenia)|url=https://www.academia.edu/191429/%D0%92%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%81%D0%BE%D0%B7%D0%B4%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%B5_%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%BB%D0%B8%D0%B3%D0%B8%D0%B8_%D0%9D%D0%B5%D0%BE%D1%8F%D0%B7%D1%8B%D1%87%D0%B5%D1%81%D1%82%D0%B2%D0%BE_%D0%B2_%D0%90%D1%80%D0%BC%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%B8_Re-creation_of_a_religion_neo-paganism_in_Armenia_|journal=|language=en|volume=|pages=104\u2013105|via=}}</ref>\n\nEven though the organized religion in its final form appeared in the 3rd century BC, the roots of it stretch back as [[Urartu]] and the proto-hetanist religion of [[\u1e2aaldi]]sm,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Badalyan|first=Miqayel|url=https://www.academia.edu/37332324/%D4%B2%D5%AB%D5%A1%D5%B5%D5%B6%D5%AB%D5%AC%D5%AB-%D5%88%D6%82%D6%80%D5%A1%D6%80%D5%BF%D5%B8%D6%82._%D5%A1%D5%BD%D5%BF%D5%BE%D5%A1%D5%AE%D5%B6%D5%A5%D6%80_%D5%BF%D5%A1%D5%B3%D5%A1%D6%80%D5%B6%D5%A5%D6%80_%D5%BA%D5%A1%D5%B7%D5%BF%D5%A1%D5%B4%D5%B8%D6%82%D5%B6%D6%84._Biainili-Urartu_gods_temples_cults|title=\u0532\u056b\u0561\u0575\u0576\u056b\u056c\u056b-\u0548\u0582\u0580\u0561\u0580\u057f\u0578\u0582. \u0561\u057d\u057f\u057e\u0561\u056e\u0576\u0565\u0580, \u057f\u0561\u0573\u0561\u0580\u0576\u0565\u0580, \u057a\u0561\u0577\u057f\u0561\u0574\u0578\u0582\u0576\u0584. Biainili-Urartu: gods, temples, cults|last2=Grekyan|first2=Yervand|last3=Petrosyan|first3=Armen|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aivazian|first=Suren|date=2018|title=The \"door\" to the religion of Urartu|url=http://armstudies.asj-oa.am/254/1/60.pdf|journal=Armenian Studies|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> as well as [[Religions of the ancient Near East|ancient near eastern religions]].<ref name=\"Martirosyan\">{{Cite journal|last=Martirosyan|first=Hamlet|title=\u0540\u0531\u0545\u0548\u0551 \u0546\u0531\u053d\u0546\u053b \u0531\u054d\u054f\u054e\u0531\u053e\u0538|url=https://www.academia.edu/41420558/%D5%80%D4%B1%D5%85%D5%88%D5%91_%D5%86%D4%B1%D4%BD%D5%86%D4%BB_%D4%B1%D5%8D%D5%8F%D5%8E%D4%B1%D4%BE%D4%B8|language=en}}</ref> It was greatly influenced by both Zoroastrianism and Hellenic paganism, but largely retained it's uniqueness<ref>{{Cite book|last=Petrosian|first=Armen|title=\u0531\u0580\u0561\u0574\u0561\u0566\u0564. \u0531\u0580\u0561\u0574\u0561\u0566\u0564\u056b \u0587 \u0570\u056b\u0576 \u0561\u057d\u057f\u057e\u0561\u056e\u0576\u0565\u0580\u056b \u0568\u0576\u0564\u0570\u0561\u0576\u0580\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0578\u0582\u0576\u0576\u0565\u0580\u0568.|publisher=|year=2008|isbn=|location=Yerevan|pages=80\u201381}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Russell|first=James R.|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=xhJIAAAAMAAJ&q=Tiridates+I+of+Armenia+zoroastrian+adherent&dq=Tiridates+I+of+Armenia+zoroastrian+adherent&hl=nl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjT3Oehzc3JAhULiCwKHW4OCWYQ6AEIHDAA|title=Zoroastrianism in Armenia|date=1987|publisher=Harvard University, Department of Near Eastern Languages and Civilizations|isbn=978-0-674-96850-9|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe rebirth of the religion can be traced back to the 19th century intellectualist ''Hetanosakan'' movement,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=\"Mehyan\" journal's analysis|url=http://lraber.asj-oa.am/2737/1/1980-3(14).pdf|journal=Mehyan|volume=|pages=74\u201382|via=}}</ref> most notable Hetanist being [[Daniel Varuzhan]], who advocated for the complete replacement of Christianity by Hetanism.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1982|title=Hetanism and Daniel Varuzhan|url=http://hpj.asj-oa.am/3682/1/1982-3(73).pdf|journal=Banasiragan|volume=|pages=73\u201385|via=}}</ref>\n\nIt gained major support in the early 20th century, with the doctrine of ''[[Tseghakron]]'' (\u0551\u0565\u0572\u0561\u056f\u0580\u0585\u0576, literally \"national religion\") of the philosopher and nationalist political theorist and warlord [[Garegin Nzhdeh]].{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=105}} It took an institutional form in 1991, just after the collapse of the [[Soviet Union]] in a climate of national reawakening, with the foundation of several Hetanist organizations.\n\nAccording to the 2011 Armenian census, 5139 people in the Republic of Armenia identified themselves as Hetanist, and the number is estimated to have doubled or even tripled in 10 years.<ref>https://www.armstat.am/file/article/sv_03_13a_520.pdf</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe word \u0540\u0565\u0569\u0561\u0576\u0578\u057d\u0578\u0582\u0569\u056b\u0582\u0576 (''Hetanosoutiwn'' comes from Greek ''\u1f14\u03b8\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2'', ''ethnos - \"Nation\"),'' and is formed with the root \u0540\u0565\u0569\u0561\u0576\u0578\u057d and suffix -\u0578\u0582\u0569\u056b\u0582\u0576.\n\nSince at least 11th century, the adherents of the movement have also called themselves ''Arordi'' or ''Arevordi'' ([[Armenian language|Armenian]]: ''\u0531\u0580\u0578\u0580\u0564\u056b, \u0531\u0580\u0565\u0582\u0578\u0580\u0564\u056b''), meaning sons of Sun.\n\n== History ==\n=== Origins ===\nThe Hetanist religion emerged from different religions of the region<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mkrtchyan|first=Aram|title=\u0531\u0580\u0561\u0574\u0561\u0566\u0564 \u0531\u057d\u057f\u056e\u0578 \u057a\u0561\u0577\u057f\u0561\u0574\u0578\u0582\u0576\u0584\u0568|url=https://www.academia.edu/22262274/%D4%B1%D6%80%D5%A1%D5%B4%D5%A1%D5%A6%D5%A4_%D4%B1%D5%BD%D5%BF%D5%AE%D5%B8_%D5%BA%D5%A1%D5%B7%D5%BF%D5%A1%D5%B4%D5%B8%D6%82%D5%B6%D6%84%D5%A8|language=en}}</ref> - most notably the religion of Aratta and ancient near east. The first organized proto-Hetanist religion was practiced in the Kingdom of Van (Urartu).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Melikishvili|first=|title=Religion in the Kingdom of Urartu|publisher=Publishing house of the academy of scienes and history of Georgian SSR|year=1954|isbn=|location=Tbilisi, Georgia|pages=445}}</ref> The religion of Urartu was a united pantheon of different armenian tribes and confederations, which was \"collected\" and standardized by kings [[Ishpuini of Urartu|Ishpuini]] and [[Menua]]. Although different Gods were worshiped, the central God [[\u1e2aaldi]] was the central deity of worship who had the authority over the entire universe and every being respectively. This semi-monotheism of \u1e2aaldism later developed into a more monotheistic religion of Hetanism.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hmakian|first=Sergei|title=The Religion of Urartu|publisher=History academia of the republic of Armenia|year=1990|isbn=|location=Yerevan|pages=84\u201385}}</ref> The trinitarian nature of the Urartian religion - with 3 chief Gods of [[\u1e2aaldi]], [[Teisheba]], [[Shivini]] also carried out to Hetanism, which is another argument in favor of \u1e2aaldic-Hetanist continuity theory.\n[[File:Head and left hand from a bronze cult statue of Anahita, a local goddess shown here in the guide of Aphrodite, 200-100 BC, British Museum (8167358544).jpg|thumb|302x302px|Anahit, Mother of Armenia]]\nThe first largely polytheistic form of Hetanism appeared after the collapse of Urartu and the emerging of the [[Orontid Armenia|first pan-armenian kingdom]] of [[Orontid dynasty|Orontids]] under [[Paruyr Skayordi]], who is considered the first [[king of Armenia]]. Under Orontids, the central Gods of Hetanism started to emerge - including [[Hayk]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vehi.net/istoriya/armenia/khorenaci/index.html|title=MOBCEC X\u041ePEHA\u0426\u0418, \"\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0410\u0440\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438\". \u041e \u0433 \u043b \u0430 \u0432 \u043b \u0435 \u043d \u0438 \u0435.|website=www.vehi.net|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref name=\"\u0531\u057d\u057f\u057e\u0561\u056e\u0576\u0565\u0580 \u0587 \u0570\u0565\u0580\u0578\u057d\u0576\u0565\u0580\">{{Cite web|url=http://armenianhouse.org/harutyunyan/04-gods.html|title=\u0531\u057d\u057f\u057e\u0561\u056e\u0576\u0565\u0580 \u0587 \u0570\u0565\u0580\u0578\u057d\u0576\u0565\u0580|website=armenianhouse.org|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>(later renamed Aramazd under Iranian influence), [[Ara the Handsome|Aray]](later [[Mihr]]),<ref name=\"\u0531\u057d\u057f\u057e\u0561\u056e\u0576\u0565\u0580 \u0587 \u0570\u0565\u0580\u0578\u057d\u0576\u0565\u0580\"/> [[Anahit]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Xanzadian|first=A.|title=Godess Anahita and her worship in Ancient Armenia|publisher=Yerevan State Academy|year=1985|isbn=|location=http://hpj.asj-oa.am/4209/1/1985-1(123).pdf|pages=}}</ref> and [[Vahagn]]<ref name=\"\u0531\u057d\u057f\u057e\u0561\u056e\u0576\u0565\u0580 \u0587 \u0570\u0565\u0580\u0578\u057d\u0576\u0565\u0580\"/>\n\n==== Formation ====\nThe final formation of the organized religion roughly corresponds to the reign of [[Tigranes II]], the first emperor([[king of kings]]) of Armenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://serials.flib.sci.am/Founders/H.Manandyan-Tigran%20B%20ev%20Hrom@/book/#page/1/mode/1up|title=bookreader demo|website=serials.flib.sci.am|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Around the first century BC, the complete theological and philosophical nature of Hetanism was formed, and the [[Armenian mythology|pantheon]] got it's final form.\n\nThe ''Mehians'' and priests concentrated on their hands the literature, schooling and education, regulation and domination of civil acts (birth, marriage, family), review of new laws, jurisdiction, even medicine. Thus, religion and priesthood represented a strong power inside the state. Religious institutions - ''Mehians'', had vast lands spanning from westernmost border of Armenia to [[Artsakh (historic province)|Artsakh]], as well as concentrated big amount of wealth, gold, silver and many more different luxuries, which were acquired from donations of [[Armenian nobility|princes, nobles, kings]] and even peasants.\n\nDue to the nature and teachings of their religion hetanist leaders and priests were always loyal and close to the king, thus their large influence in the affairs of the kingdom never brought up notable conflicts or destabilized the kingdom.\n\nThe image of supreme and eternal God, Ar/Ara appeared, all others God's turned merely into different manifestations of Ar, moving Hetanism into monotheistic world of religions.<ref name=\"Martirosyan\"/>\n\n=== Replacement by Christianity ===\nArmenia was one of the first regions where Christianity spread and flourished. The founders of Christian communities in Armenia were [[apostles]] [[Jude the Apostle|Thaddeus (Jude)]] and [[Bartholomew the Apostle|Bartholomew]] (dates of preaching [[AD 35|35]] AD - [[60 AD|60]] AD), who bear the titles of \"first illuminators of Armenia\".<ref name=\"akunq.net\">{{Cite web|url=https://akunq.net/am/?p=19885|title=1. \u0554\u0580\u056b\u057d\u057f\u0578\u0576\u0565\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0574\u0578\u0582\u057f\u0584\u0568 \u0540\u0561\u0575\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576 \u0587 \u057a\u0561\u057f\u0574\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0578\u0582\u0576\u0568|date=2012-04-09|website=\u0531\u0580\u0565\u0582\u0574\u057f\u0561\u0570\u0561\u0575\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576\u056b \u0565\u0582 \u0531\u0580\u0565\u0582\u0574\u057f\u0561\u0570\u0561\u0575\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0565\u0561\u0576 \u0540\u0561\u0580\u0581\u0565\u0580\u0578\u0582 \u0548\u0582\u057d\u0578\u0582\u0574\u0576\u0561\u057d\u056b\u0580\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0565\u0561\u0576 \u053f\u0565\u0564\u0580\u0578\u0576|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Before the 4th century, Christianity was not very popular amongst the Armenians and was spread only in small communities across the whole country. Nevertheless, the Christians were periodically persecuted. The persecution was especially harsh during the reign of king [[Sanatruk]].<ref name=\"akunq.net\"/>\n\nIn Armenia, the first center of Christianity is considered [[Mtsurq]], which was a city built by king Sanatruk. After the fall of the city to [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanid]] forces, the center moved to [[Ashtishat]], where it stayed until the fall of the Armenian kingdom.\n\nChristianity started growing rapidly under king [[Tiridates III of Armenia|Tiridates III the great]], under whom Christianity was declared official state religion\n\n==== Christianity as state religion ====\nAccording to a folk tradition recorded in [[Agatangeghos|Agatangeghos']] \"Armenian History\", when Tiridates III returned to [[Vagharshapat]] with the help of the Roman army in [[287 AD]] to reclaim his father's throne, on his way to the Yeriza settlement he offered a sacrifice to the goddess Anahit. [[Gregory the Illuminator|Grigor]], right hand of the king, refused attend the sacrifice because he was a Christian. The Armenian king also learns that Grigor was the son of prince Anak of Parthia who killed his father [[Khosrov IV of Armenia|Khosrov]]. Tiridates orders him to be thrown into the underground prison of [[Artaxata|Artashat]] (now known as \"[[Khor Virap]]\") as death penalty.<ref name=\"\u0531\u0563\u0561\u0569\u0561\u0576\u0563\u0565\u0572\u0578\u057d\">{{Cite book|last=\u0531\u0563\u0561\u0569\u0561\u0576\u0563\u0565\u0572\u0578\u057d|url=http://archive.org/details/agathangelos11|title=\u0531\u0563\u0561\u0569\u0561\u0576\u0563\u0565\u0572\u0578\u057d, \u054a\u0561\u057f\u0574\u0578\u0582\u0569\u056b\u0582\u0576 \u0540\u0561\u0575\u0578\u0581  (Agathange\u0142os, History of Armenia)}}</ref>[[File:Hetan priest officiating at Garni Temple, Armenia (1).png|thumb|left|alt=|A hetanist priest preaching]]In addition to Gregory, Hripsime's virgins also contributed substantially to the spread of Christianity and conversion to state religion in [[Greater Armenia]]. According to tradition, they were Roman virgins who were persecuted by [[Emperor Diocletian]] and fled eastwards. Among them were [[Hripsime|St. Hripsime]], St. Gayane, St. Shoghakat, St. Nune, and others with various saints up to 40 women. One of them, Nune, founded the Georgian Church. The virgins first worship at the Christ's sacred places (holy sites of Palestine) and then cross [[Edessa]] to Greater Armenia, settling near the capital of [[Vagharshapat]] in the tents. Tiridates, after seeing the beauty of young Christian virgin, wants to marry Hripsime, but she refuses. In response, in [[300 AD]], he ordered that all virgins be executed.<ref name=\"\u0531\u0563\u0561\u0569\u0561\u0576\u0563\u0565\u0572\u0578\u057d\"/>\n\nAfter the martyrdom of the virgins, the Armenian king suffers a severe [[fever]]. According to the folk traditions, the disease is considered to have made Tiridates into a swine. The king's sister, Khosrovidukht, repeatedly dreamed that Tirdates could only be treated by Grigor, who was a prisoner in Artashat. He is released from prison and solemnly admitted to the capital Vagharshapat. Gregory first summons the souls of the martyred virgins, then preaches the religion of Christianity for 66 days and then healed the king. Tiridates III and the whole court is baptized; Christianity proclaimed a state religion.\n\nThis tradition, albeit romantic, is considered to be a legend \u2014 Adopting Christianity was merely part of Tiridates' extensive policy of creating an Armenia independent both from Persia and Rome.<ref name=\"\u0531\u0563\u0561\u0569\u0561\u0576\u0563\u0565\u0572\u0578\u057d\"/><ref>{{Cite book|last=Richard|first=Hovannisian|url=https://books.google.am/books/about/The_Armenian_People_From_Ancient_to_Mode.html?id=p37O_KtaUKsC&redir_esc=y|title=The Armenian People From Ancient to Modern Times, Volume II: Foreign Dominion to Statehood: The Fifteenth Century to the Twentieth Century|date=1997-08-14|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-0-312-10168-8|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Hakobyan|first=Aleqsan|url=https://www.academia.edu/34569879/ARMENIA_AND_CHRISTIAN_CAUCASUS|title=ARMENIA AND CHRISTIAN CAUCASUS|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Persecution by Christians ===\nAfter the embracement of Christianity, more than half of the armenian population was still Hetanist. The government soon adopted a harsh anti-Hetanist policy.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=THOMSON|first=ROBERT W.|date=1988|title=Mission, Conversion, and Christianization: The Armenian Example|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/41036303|journal=Harvard Ukrainian Studies|volume=12/13|pages=28\u201345|issn=0363-5570}}</ref> Thousands of ancient temples were destroyed. Priests were killed and entire villages which refused to be converted were destroyed.\n\nThe last pagan leader, Arzan, was recklessly murdered at the entrance of a temple.\n\nThe only surviving temple in Armenia is Garni temple.<ref name=\"armenianweekly.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://armenianweekly.com/2019/11/27/the-remnants-of-armenias-pagan-past/|title=The Remnants of Armenia's Pagan Past|date=2019-11-27|website=The Armenian Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Today, It is considered a \"symbol of Armenia\u2019s classical past as well as its deep historical ties to the civilizations of Greece and Rome.\" In ancient and medieval times, the areas surrounding the temple were utilized as a royal garrison and military fortress.\n\nIn the city of Artashat, southeast of the capital, Yerevan, Mithraic temple ruins, built from black marble, have been unearthed as well.<ref name=\"armenianweekly.com\"/>\n\nHetanism was a prominent religion in Armenia before renaissance era. The last Hetanist community survived until the 1920s<ref>{{Cite book|last=Roald|first=Anne Sofie|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=Ab0yAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA313&dq=armenians+were+zoroastrian&hl=nl&sa=X&ved=0CEYQ6AEwBWoVChMI49KPt6KSxgIVAo4sCh1evgDN#v=onepage&q=armenians%20were%20zoroastrian&f=false|title=Religious Minorities in the Middle East: Domination, Self-Empowerment, Accommodation|last2=Longva|first2=Anh Nga|date=2011-11-11|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-21684-6|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Rebirth ==\n\n=== 19th century hetanist movement ===\nAt the peak of [[armenian national awakening]], armenian intellectuals started seeing Hetanism as a viable and even desirable alternative to the religion of Christianity.<ref name=\":0\" /> The most prominent advocate of the national conversion was [[Daniel Varuzhan]],<ref name=\":0\" /> one of the most popular poets of Armenia and a martyr of the [[Armenian genocide]]. Varuzhan and his fellow intellectualists organized the first Armenian hetanist group/organization - ''Mehian,'' which printed articles about armenian nationalism and Hetanism. According to the ideology of Varuzhan and his followers, the Christian ideology of \"[[Turn the other cheek|turning the cheek]]\" has become a disaster for the Armenian nation, which before was a great nation with brave soldiers and wise rulers. According to them, the Armenian nation fell low after the acceptance of Christianity and became a slave to the west and the east.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Garegin Nzhdeh ===\n[[File:Garegin_Nzhdeh_5.jpg|thumb|Garegin Nzhdeh, the ideologue of an Armenian \"national religion\".]]\n\n[[Garegin Nzhdeh]] is considered one of the most important figures of the armenian history. He was a philosopher, statesman and ''[[Armenian fedayi|fedayi]]'' of the first half of the twentieth century, who left an enduring legacy in the history of [[Armenia]], and is still one of the driving forces of [[Armenian nationalism]].{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=105}} People praised him as the \"prophet of the Armenians\".{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=266}} Nzhdeh founded a movement named ''[[Tseghakron]]'' (\"religion of the nation\"), which was among the core doctrines of the [[Armenian Youth Federation]].{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=105}} In Nzhdeh's poetic mythology, the Armenian nation is identified as [[Atlas (mythology)|Atlas]] upholding the ordered world,{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=105}} and praised [[Hayk]], the mythical patriarch of the [[Armenians]], and [[Vahagn]], the fire and warrior god \"[[Proto-Indo-European religion#Dragon or serpent|fighter of the serpent]]\", and believed Hetanism would awaken the Armenian nation and raise its spirit. Nzhdeh's movement took place in the aftermath of the [[Armenian Genocide]] of 1915.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=105}}\n\nThe first organisation of Armenian Native Faith, the \"Order of the Children of Ari\" (or \"Ara\"; ''Arordineri Ukht'' in [[Armenian language|Armenian]]) was established in 1991 by the armenologist Slak (Eduard) Kakosyan (1936\u20132005).{{sfnm|1a1=Antonyan|1y=2010|1p=105|2a1=Siekierski|2a2=Antonyan|2y=2013|2p=266}} He belonged to a generation of Armenian dissidents and was exiled in the 1970s from [[Armenian Soviet Socialist Republic|Soviet Armenia]]; in 1979 he fled to the [[United States]] where he became familiar with the ideas of [[Garegin Nzhdeh]] (1886\u20131955).{{sfnm|1a1=Antonyan|1y=2010|1p=105|2a1=Siekierski|2a2=Antonyan|2y=2013|2p=266}}\n\nAccording to modern hetanists, Garegin Nzhdeh is [[Apotheosis|deified]] as an incarnation of Vahagn, the re-establisher of the true faith of the Armenians and of the armenian values.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=106}}\n\n=== 1990s: Establishment of the Children of Ari ===\nThe hetanists re-emerged after [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union|the collapse of the soviet union]]. They began to hold rituals on traditional Armenian holidays. The [[Temple of Garni]] became the centre of the community, a council of priests was set up in order to manage the organisation and the rites.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=106, note 7}} During the 1990s, the group reached visibility in wider Armenian society.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=107}} According to the scholar Yulia Antonyan, the emergence of the Armenian Native Faith is attributable to the same causes which led to the rise of other modern religious movements, but also [[Hinduism|Hindu]] and [[Protestantism|Protestant]] movements, in the other post-Soviet countries: The Armenian Native Faith represents the indigenous answer to the social and cultural upheavals which followed the collapse of Soviet society and of its atheist and materialist ideology.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=104}}\n\n=== Republican Party support and grassroots spread ===\n[[File:Hetan_priest_officiating_at_Garni_Temple,_Armenia_13.jpg|thumb|An Arordiner priest.]]\n[[Ashot Navasardyan]] (1950\u20131997) and [[Andranik Margaryan]] (1949\u20132007), founding fathers of the [[Republican Party of Armenia]], were hetanists like many other members of the party and took part in the very first ritual at the Temple of Garni.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=270}} The Armenian government provides financial support for the Children of Ari.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=107}} Arordiner festivals are celebrated in some regions with the support of local municipalities.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=107, note 8}} Despite this strong link with the nationalist political scene, hetanism itself does not have a political orientation, and the priests are forbidden from joining any political party.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=107}}\n\nAlthough it started among the Armenian intellectual elites as a means to reawaken Armenian identity, in most recent times the Armenian Native Faith movement has expanded its contingent of adherents among the provincial and rural populations,{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=107}} and among the [[Armenian diaspora]].{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=108}} Besides the philosophical approach of the intellectuals, the common people are driven to the Armenian Native Faith by various reasons, ranging from [[mysticism]] to a sentimental devotion to the gods. Antonyan documented the case of a thirty-five years-old woman who believed to be [[Infertility|infertile]], and who joined the Armenian Native Faith movement after she allegedly became pregnant by praying to Anahit, goddess of fertility, and to Astghik, goddess of love and beauty.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=108}} The woman gave her daughter the name \"Nana\", another name of the goddess of fertility.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=109}}\n\nLocal Arordiner communities have been organised in villages outside the capital [[Yerevan]]. The structure of the Order of the Children of Ari, and of the local communities themselves, is characterised by a clear hierarchy, with the council of priests, led by an elected chief, handling the organisation of all activities. The highest position within the hierarchy is that of the supreme priest, which has remained vacant since Slak Kakosyan's death in 2005.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|pp=267\u2013268}}\n\n== Beliefs ==\n\n=== Theology and cosmology ===\n[[File:Aramazd.jpg|left|thumb|Statue of God Ar]]\n\n==== Ar and Ara ====\nThe theology of Hetanism is a [[monism]]: According to the faith, in the beginning was the Ar, who was the creator of the reality .{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=110}} The Ar is the impersonal, without qualities, [[Transcendence (religion)|transcendent]] principle begetting the universe, the universal ideal and a conscience.{{sfnm|1a1=Antonyan|1y=2010|1p=110|2a1=Siekierski|2a2=Antonyan|2y=2013|2p=266}} According to Hetanists, ''Ar'' is the life-giving word root,{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=115}} and it is the origin of words like, for instance, ''art'' (\"arable\", \"cultivation\"; culture, art), ''aryyun'' (\"blood\"), ''argand'' (\"womb\"), ''armat'' (\"root\"), ''arka'' (\"king\"), ''ara'' (\"male\"), ''Arev'' (the Sun), ''Ara'' (manifested Ar), ''Ari'' (acting with Ar), ''Chari'' (opposing Ar).{{sfnm|1a1=Antonyan|1y=2010|1p=115|2a1=Siekierski|2a2=Antonyan|2y=2013|2p=271}} The \"essence of things\" and their \"perfection\" is represented by ''[[swastika]]'' motifs.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=269}}\n\n==== Deities ====\nThe different deities are beneath the supreme Ar. They are not separate beings, but merely different manifestations of Ar. Though monotheistic in theology, the Armenian Native Faith is mostly [[Polytheism|polytheistic]] in practice.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=116}} The gods of the Arordiners include:{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=271}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! style=\"padding:0.5em 0.5em;white-space:nowrap;\" |Name\n! style=\"padding:0.5em 0.5em;white-space:nowrap;\" |Also known as\n!Details\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |[[Hayk]]\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Aramazd, Khaldi\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |The primary God of ancient armenians, head of the pantheon, manifestation of fatherhood, the earth and the sky. He was called almighty and all-father. His temple was in Kamakh, Ani province, which also was a grave for Armenian kings of the [[Artaxiad|artaxiad dynasty of Armenia.]] Along with Anahit and Vahagn contituted the holy triad.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Anahit\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Teisheba\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Daughter of Aramazd. She was the mother god, and was pictured with a long veil coming down from her hair, she was referenced to as the great mother Anahit, the good-bringer, maifestation of motherhood and the personofication and mother-protector of Armenia. It is due to Anahit that the Armenian nation still exists and will continue to live. Armenian kings, before enacting decisions or going to wars would ask the goddess for approval and tips, to succee in what they plan. She was also the devine manifestation  and personofication of motherhood and fertility.\nTogether with Aramazd and Vahagn she constituted the holy triad.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Vahagn\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Aray, Demetr\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |The third God of the pantheon was Vahagn, who was described in ancient armenian poems as a bright and red-haired teen with fire-like hair and beard and eyes that shined like the sun. He is the dying and reborning God, who is born from the union of water and fire, soil and the sky. \nHe is the most popular Armenian God and is a notable figure in the armenian consicene even nowadays.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Astghik\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Astghik, Astlik\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Astghik was the lover of Vahagn and was considered his polar opposite. She was the goddess of love and water. According to folk tradition, Vahagn met Astghik in the field of Ararat. Their marriage was a blessing for the earth, and soon holy rain started pouring from the sky fertilizing the lands.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Nane\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Next to nothing is known about her, although her popularity was big. She was most likely a goddess of war.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Ara the Beautiful\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Ara\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |He was the manifestation of the spring, God of land fertility and the bringer of prosperity.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Mihr\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Shivini\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Mihr was the God of the sun-light. Not to be confused with the sun-god Aramazd.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Tir\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Tyur\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Tir was the manifestation of knowledge, enlightenment and writing.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Vanatur\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Amanor\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Vanatur was the manifestation of friendlyness\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Spandaramet\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Spandaramet was the manifestation of the underground world. In opposition to almost all other religions in the world, Armenians believed that the soil brings life, not death. The underground was where the root of the life starts, so Spandaramet is the manifestation of life, not death.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Tarqu\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Tork Angegh\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Legendary defender of Armenia, who threw rocks at Greek ships trying to invade Armenia. Manifestation of defence and struggle.\n|-\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Grogh\n| style=\"padding-left:1em;\" |Grogh\n| style=\"padding:0.5em;\" |Bringer of death.\n|}\nAramazd, Vahagn and Anahit together constituted the holy trinity of the hetanist religion. Contrary to other religions of the world, Armenains didn't have a conception of hell or bad Gods. All bad in the world comes from humanity, and the underground is root of life.\n\nArmenians consider holy the water, lions, apricot tree and fire.\n\n=== Afterlife and eschatology ===\nHetanists have a cyclical view of reality, and they believe in the [[reincarnation]] of individual souls through the genetic lineage. That is to say, men are believed to come back to life in the following generations of their own descendants, in the kin which they begot while living.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=273}} According to hetanist doctrines, the entire world goes through similar cycles, from the smaller ones represented by the days and the years, to the greatest ones represented by eras of ten thousand years.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|pp=273\u2013274}}\n\nThe struggle between light and dark unfolds through the cycle of each era: Order and connection with the ancestors prevail during the world's summer and spring; while disorder, confusion and forsaking of the ancestral roots prevail during the world's autumn and winter. In the latter period, beings are not in harmony with Ar, they are not nourished by cosmic energy. At the darkest stage of history, though, which according to Arordiners corresponds to the current times, Vahagn is born again and brings the warrior forces back to life.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|pp=273\u2013274}}\n\n=== The ''Ukhtagirk'' ===\n''Ukhtagirk'', the holy book of the Armenian Native Faith, may be translated as \"Book of Vows\". It was the life work of Slak Kakosyan, who finished the manuscript just before his death in 2005.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=271}} Kakosyan, however, is not the \"author\" of the ''Ukhtagirk'', but rather the \"recorder\" of oral traditions,{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=115}} its \"compiler\" (''kazmogh'').{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=271}} The book was officially proclaimed the holy text of the Order of the Children of Ari in 2000, a couple of years before its completion, when the religious organisation was officially registered by the Armenian state.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=271}}\n\nThe book is divided into seven parts: \u2460 ''Astvatsashoonch'' (\"Dictionary\"), which explains the Armenian language as a mystical system of symbols related to the root ''Ar''; \u2461 ''Tsagumnaran'' (\"Genesis\"), which explains in mythical terms the origin of the world, the gods and mankind; \u2462 ''Avetaran'' (\"Book of Testaments\") and \u2463 ''Dzonaran'' (\"Book of Odes\"), which deal with philosophical and ontological categories to explain reality and values; \u2464 ''Veharan'' (\"Book of Greatness\") and \u2465 ''Patgamaran'' (\"Book of Commandments\"), which present mythologised descriptions of Garegin Nzhdeh's life and ideas, respectively; and the seventh and last chapter, \u2466 ''Hymnergaran'' (\"Book of Hymns\"), which is a collection of poems written by Kakosyan and his followers, as well as by authors of the nineteenth and early twentieth century. The mythological parts about creation rely upon Armenian medieval sources and folk knowledge.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=271\u2013272}}\n\nChanting ritual texts from the book is considered to procure mystical experiences, and the physical book itself is crucial for some ritual activities, such as wedding ceremonies, in which the rings are passed to the bride and groom on top of a copy of the ''Ukhtagirk''.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=273}} At the same time, Arordiners do not consider their book unquestionable, but the text is open to corrections as required by changing circumstances. This attitude is supported by a declaration of Slak Kakosyan himself, who conceived the book in the terms of a changeful and adaptable truth.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=273}}\n\n== Practices ==\n[[File:Hetan_priest_officiating_at_Garni_Temple,_Armenia_30.jpg|thumb|300x300px|People gathered on the occasion of a public ceremony at the Temple of Garni.]]\nArmenian Native Faith practices, rituals and representations mostly rely on the instructions given by the ''Ukhtagirk''.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=110}} For instance, it is common for the priests to make pilgrimage to [[Khustup|Mount Khustup]], where, according to the book, Garegin Nzhdeh experienced the presence of the god Vahagn.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=109}} The priests' aim is to replicate such experience.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=109}} The veneration of Nzhdeh and the pilgrimage to his burial site, which is located on the slopes of the Khustup, is also slowly developing within the larger community of Hetanists.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=110, note 14}} In general, mountains are revered as holy, so, besides Khustup, other mountains, including [[Mount Ararat]] and [[Mount Aragats]], function as pilgrimage destination for hetanists.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|pp=275, 278}}\n\n=== Rituals ===\nArmenian Native Faith rituals include the yearly ceremonies performed on Armenian traditional holidays, and three [[rites of passage]]: The ''knunk'', a complex ritual of initiation; the ''psak'', that is wedding; and death rituals.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=121}} The death rituals require the [[cremation]] of the body,{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=121}} and its return to the four elements. Fire is symbolised by the cremation itself; then the ashes are divided into three parts, of which one is buried in the earth, one is scattered in the air of the [[Garni Gorge]], and the third one is poured in the water of the Garni River.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=277}} Afterwards, the deceased is memorialised by the collective lighting of a torch.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=278}} The first Arordiner to be cremated was Kakosyan himself,when cremation is illegal in Armenia. Later, hetanists obtained by the state the right to cremate their dead.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=277}}[[File:Hetan_initiation_ritual_(0).PNG|thumb|Stage of a ''knunk'' ritual.|alt=|left]]The Armenian term ''knunk'' may be translated as \"conversion\" or \"reversion\" (to the native way of life).{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=108, note 11}} Yulia Antonyan observed that about ten to twenty people take part to each ''knunk'' ritual, which is held on the occasion of the public ceremonies at the Temple of Garni. At the same time, there are many hetanists who believe that in order to worship the native gods of Armenia it is not necessary to undergo an official conversion.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=108, note 11}}\n\n=== Temples and idols ===\nArordiner public ceremonies and rituals are held at ancient sacred places, which are often in ruins.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=119}} The re-appropriation of churches that were built on native sacred sites is also common.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=119}} The most important of these sites is the first-century Temple of Garni, a temple which was rebuilt in 1975, which has become the main ceremonial center for the Armenian Native Faith movement.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=119}}\n\nThe Arordiners have reconsecrated the temple to Vahagn, although historically it was dedicated to Mihr. They have also been given approval for the rearrangement of the compound, in order for it to match the ideal structure of ancient Armenian sanctuaries.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=119}} They have added a holy spring dedicated to Slak Kakosyan and a wood of [[apricot]] trees, the holy tree of Armenian Native Faith. The temple is now organised into three sacred spaces: The first is the sacred spring, the second one is the temple proper, and the third one is the holy wood, located on a hillock.{{sfnm|1a1=Antonyan|1y=2010|1p=119|2a1=Siekierski|2a2=Antonyan|2y=2013|2pp=275\u2013277}} The rituals at the Temple of Garni take place following a route which starts from the spring, passes through the temple, and endly reaches the holy wood.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=119}} Downhill, each newly established local Arordiner community plants a tree, symbolising the unity and well-being of the group itself. These holy trees are adorned with ribbons and handkerchiefs symbolising one's requests to the gods.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|pp=275\u2013277}}\n\nBesides the Temple of Garni, other sites considered holy by the Arordiners and used for their rituals include the [[Metsamor Castle]] (third millennium BCE), considered a site for the cult of the mother goddess, the [[Erebuni Fortress]] (eighth century BCE), [[Shengavit Settlement|Shengavit]] (fourth to second millennium BCE) and [[Zorats Karer]] (third millennium BCE), and the mountains.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|pp=275\u2013277}} Sculptures representing the gods which have been realised within the context of modern Armenian Native Faith are inspired by both historical specimens and the creativity of modern artists.{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=119}}\n\n=== Holidays ===\nThe Arordiners celebrate a number of holidays:{{sfn|Antonyan|2010|p=116}} Terendez, Zatik, Hambardzum, [[Vardavar]] and Khaghoghorhnek. To these holy days they add a holy day for the remembrance of ancestors (20 September), the Birth of Vahagn (21 March), the Birth of Mihr (22 December) and the Navasard, the New Year celebrated in August.\n\n== Poetry and legends ==\nSeveral hetanist legends and poems have survived till our days. One of the best examples of this is ''Vahagni tsnund, t''he birth of Vahagn, recorded by Moses of Chorene\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Armenian\n!Transliteration\n!English translation\n|-\n|''\u0535\u0580\u056f\u0576\u0567\u0580 \u0565\u0580\u056f\u056b\u0576, \u0565\u0580\u056f\u0576\u0567\u0580 \u0565\u0580\u056f\u056b\u0580,''\n\n''\u0535\u0580\u056f\u0576\u0567\u0580 \u0587 \u056e\u0578\u057e\u0576 \u056e\u056b\u0580\u0561\u0576\u056b.''\n\n''\u0535\u0580\u056f\u0576 \u056b \u056e\u0578\u057e\u0578\u0582\u0576 \u0578\u0582\u0576\u0567\u0580 \u0587 \u0566\u056f\u0561\u0580\u0574\u0580\u056b\u056f\u0576 \u0565\u0572\u0565\u0563\u0576\u056b\u056f.''\n\n''\u0538\u0576\u0564 \u0565\u0572\u0565\u0563\u0561\u0576 \u0583\u0578\u0572 \u056e\u0578\u0582\u056d \u0565\u056c\u0561\u0576\u0567\u0580,''\n\n''\u0538\u0576\u0564 \u0565\u0572\u0565\u0563\u0561\u0576 \u0583\u0578\u0572 \u0562\u0578\u0581 \u0565\u056c\u0561\u0576\u0567\u0580,''\n\n''\u0535\u0582 \u056b \u0562\u0578\u0581\u0578\u0575\u0576 \u057e\u0561\u0566\u0567\u0580 \u056d\u0561\u0580\u057f\u0565\u0561\u0577 \u057a\u0561\u057f\u0561\u0576\u0565\u056f\u056b\u056f.''\n\n''\u0546\u0561 \u0570\u0578\u0582\u0580 \u0570\u0565\u0580 \u0578\u0582\u0576\u0567\u0580,''\n\n''\u0532\u0578\u0581 \u0578\u0582\u0576\u0567\u0580 \u0574\u0585\u0580\u0578\u0582\u057d,''\n\n''\u0535\u0582 \u0561\u0579\u0584\u0578\u0582\u0576\u0584\u0576 \u0567\u056b\u0576 \u0561\u0580\u0565\u0563\u0561\u056f\u0578\u0582\u0576\u0584\u0589''\n|''Yerkneer Yerkin, yerkneer yerkir''\n\n''Yerkneer yew tsovn tsirani''\n\n''Yerkn i-tsovun uner yev ezkarmrikn ellgenik''\n\n''End yellegan poll tsoux yelaner,''\n\n''End yellgedan poll bots yerlaner''\n\n''Yew i-botsoyn vazer xarteash patanekik,''\n\n''Na hur her uner''\n\n''Bots uner morus''\n\n''Yev Achqoonq ein aregaqonq''\n|\n: ''In travail were heaven and earth,''\n\n: ''In travail, too, the purple sea!''\n\n: ''The travail held in the sea the small red reed.''\n\n: ''Through the hollow of the stalk came forth smoke,''\n\n: ''Through the hollow of the stalk came forth flame,''\n\n: ''And out of the flame a youth ran!''\n\n: ''Fiery hair had he,''\n\n: ''Ay, too, he had flaming beard,''\n\n: ''And his eyes, they were as suns!''\n|}\n\n=== Hayk and Bel ===\nOne of the most ancient and famous traditions is the tradition of the battle of Hayk, founder of the armenian nation, and Bel, a Babylonian tyrant.\n\nIn Moses of Chorene's account, Hayk son of [[Togarmah|Torgom]] had a child named [[Armanak (disambiguation)|Armanak]] while he was living in [[Babylon]]. After the arrogant [[Titan (mythology)|Titanid]] [[Belus (Babylonian)|Bel]] made himself king over all, Hayk emigrated to the region near [[Mount Ararat]]. Hayk relocated near Mount Ararat with an extended household of at least 300 and settled there, founding a village he named ''Haykashen''. On the way he had left a detachment in another settlement with his grandson Kadmos. Bel sent one of his sons to entreat him to return, but was refused. Bel decided to march against him with a massive force, but Hayk was warned ahead of time by Kadmos of his pending approach. He assembled his own army along the shore of [[Lake Van]] and told them that they must defeat and kill Bel, or die trying to do so, rather than become his slaves. In his writings Moses states that:<blockquote>\u201c Hayk was a handsome, friendly man, with curly hair, sparkling eyes, and strong arms. He was a man of giant stature, a mighty archer and fearless warrior. Hayk and his people, from the time of their forefathers [[Noah]] and [[Japheth]], had migrated south toward the warmer lands near Babylon. In that land there ruled a wicked giant, Bel. Bel tried to impose his tyranny upon Hayk's people. But proud Hayk refused to submit to Bel. As soon as his son Aramaniak was born, Hayk rose up and led his people northward into the land of [[Ayrarat|Ararad]]. At the foot of the mountain he built a village and gave it his name, calling Haykashen. \u201d</blockquote>Hayk and his men soon discovered Bel's army positioned in a mountain pass (Moses of Chorene located the site as [[Dastakert]]), with the king in the [[Vanguard (military formation)|vanguard]].\n\nAt ''Dyutsaznamart'' ([[Armenian language|Armenian]]: \u0534\u0575\u0578\u0582\u0581\u0561\u0566\u0576\u0561\u0574\u0561\u0580\u057f, \"Battle of Giants\"), near [[Julamerk]] southeast of [[Lake Van]], on 11 August 2492 BC (according to the Armenian traditional chronology of the first month of the [[Armenian calendar]], Navasard or 2107 BC (according to \"The Chronological table\" of [[Mikael Chamchian]]), Hayk slew Bel with a nearly impossible shot using a long bow, sending the king's forces into disarray.\n\nThe hill where Bel with his warriors fell, Hayk named ''Gerezmank'' meaning \"tombs\". He embalmed the corpse of Bel and ordered it to be taken to Hark where it was to be buried in a high place in the view of the wives and sons of the king.\n\nSoon after, Hayk established the fortress of [[Haykaberd]] at the battle site and the town of Haykashen in the Armenian province of [[Vaspurakan]] (modern-day Turkey). He named the region of the battle ''Hayk'', and the site of the battle Hayots Dzor.\n\n=== Ara the handsome ===\nAnother ancient Armenian legend is connected with Ara the beautiful, God of spring and rebirth.\n\nAccording to the legend, Shamiram had fallen in love with the handsome Ara and asked him to marry her. When Ara refused, Semiramis, in the heat of passion, gathered the armies of [[Assyria]] and marched against Armenia. During the battle Semiramis was victorious, but Ara was slain despite her orders to capture him alive. To avoid continuous warfare with the Armenians, Shamiram, reputed to be a sorceress, took his body and prayed to the gods to raise Ara from the dead. When the Armenians advanced to avenge their leader, Shamiram disguised one of her lovers as Ara and spread the rumor that the gods had brought Ara back to life, convincing the Armenians not to continue the war. Nevertheless, Ara is reborn later and gets his revenge on the Assyrian queen.{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n\nIt was also reported that a village called Lezk, near [[Van, Turkey|Van]], traditionally held that it was Ara's place of resurrection.{{fact|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== Torq Angegh ===\nTorq was considered one of [[Hayk]]'s great-grandsons and reportedly represented as an unattractive male figure. He is mentioned by Armenian 5th Century historian [[Movses Khorenatsi]] and considered one of the significant deities of the Armenian pantheon. Taken in the context of [[Proto-Indo-Europeans|Proto-Indo-European]] religions, it is conceivable that an etymological connection with [[Norse mythology|Norse]] god [[Thor]]/Tyr is more than a simple coincidence. According to tradition, with his immense strength he threw rocks at the invading Greek navy, keeping the shores of Armenia safe.\n\n== Relations with Christianity ==\n[[File:\u054a\u0561\u0580_\u0533\u0561\u057c\u0576\u0578\u0582\u0574.jpg|thumb|A ritual dance at the Temple of Garni.]]\nThe relations between the Armenian Native Faith movement and the [[Armenian Apostolic Church]] have been good and collaborative, since both share the common interest of protecting and promoting Armenian identity, especially against what are perceived as disruptive foreign forces infiltrating the country, such as Protestants, [[Jehovah's Witnesses]] and [[Mormonism|Mormons]].{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=268}} The Armenian Apostolic Church generally sees Arordiners as allies. A high-ranking spokesman of the Armenian Apostolic Church declared:{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=268}}\n{{Quote|The Armenian Church has an unequivocal stance on sectarians (i.e. Protestants et al.), but we do not interfere into hetanos affairs.}}\nSimilarly, the head of an Armenian institution catering to the victims of destructive cults declared:{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=268}}\n{{Quote|The Armenian nation must remember its pre-Christian past, and Ara's Children help them remember. They also support the Armenian Apostolic Church in its fight against destructive sects.}}\nArmenian Native Faith believers' attitude towards Christianity oscillates between two positions: The critique of the religion's role in Armenian history, and the conditional acceptance of the Armenian Apostolic Church as a national institution.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=268}} Christianity is criticised for having destroyed the rich and highly developed ancient Armenian culture, replacing the values of courage, martial spirit and honour with those of humility, obedience and modesty, thus causing the collapse of Armenian statehood and condemning the nation to centuries of subordination to foreign powers, migrations, persecutions and massacres.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=268}} According to the strongest accusations, Christianity is responsible for the \"first genocide of the Armenians\", which coincided with its forceful introduction in the fourth century.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=269}}\n\nAt the same time, the Armenian Apostolic Church is considered an institution peculiar to the Armenian nation, and the fruit of a synthesis of Christian and indigenous elements, in which the former represent just the surface. The hetanists find proof of this in the Church's prayers devoted to the Sun and light, in Church festivals overlapping indigenous Armenian festivals, and in the practice of ''matagh'', Christian animal sacrifice. Moreover, the hetanists believe that the Armenian alphabet, which Church historiography holds to have been invented by the monk Mesrop Mahtots, is actually an elaboration of ancient Armenian symbolism based on the motif of the ''[[swastika]]''.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=269}}\n\nHetanists generally do not have problems visiting Armenian churches and treating them as holy places, since many of them were built on the site of pre-Christian temples. Furthermore, some figures of the history of the Armenian Apostolic Church are revered as Hetanists in disguise: The ''[[Catholicos|catholicoi]]'' (high-ranking bishops) Vazgen I (in charge 1954\u20131994) and Garegin I (1995\u20131999). The former was a supporter of Nzhdeh and on his tombstone, instead of a cross, he has a letter of the Armenian alphabet which is considered a variant of the ''swastika'' and symbolic of seven Armenian gods. The latter is said to have visited Garni before his death and, despite being terminally ill, to have walked alone to the temple.{{sfn|Siekierski|Antonyan|2013|p=269}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n<references group=\"\" responsive=\"0\"></references>\n\n=== Sources ===\n\n* {{cite contribution|last1=Siekierski|first1=Konrad|last2=Antonyan|first2=Yulia|year=2013|contribution=A Neopagan Movement in Armenia: the Children of Ara|title=Modern Pagan and Native Faith Movements in Central and Eastern Europe|editor1=Kaarina Aitamurto|editor2=Scott Simpson|isbn=9781844656622|location=Durham|publisher=Acumen|pages=266\u2013282|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Antonyan|first=Yulia|year=2010|title='Re-creation' of a Religion: Neo-paganism in Armenia|url=https://www.academia.edu/191429|journal=Laboratorium|language=ru|location=Saint-Petersburg|pages=103\u2013128|ref=harv|number=1}}\n* {{cite contribution|last=Antonyan|language=hy|archivedate=16 April 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416201021/http://old.brusov.am/docs/cank-Identity_Articles_final.pdf|accessdate=16 April 2018|date=|ref=harv|pages=23\u201330|isbn=9789993079934|first=Yulia|location=Yerevan|publisher=Lingva|url=http://old.brusov.am/docs/cank-Identity_Articles_final.pdf|title=Identities and Changing World, Proceedings of International Conference|contribution=The Aryan Myth and the New Armenian Paganism|year=2008|author-mask={{long dash}}|url-status=dead}}\n\n; Armenian neoshamanism\n\n* {{cite contribution|last=Antonyan|first=Yulia|year=2008|contribution=Magical and Healing Practices in Contemporary Urban Environment (in Armenian Cities of Yerevan, Gyumri, and Vanadzor|title=Figuring the South Caucasus: Societies and Environment|publisher=Heinrich B\u00f6ll Foundation|location=Tbilisi|isbn=9789941900914|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Antonyan|first=Yulia|author-mask={{long dash}}|year=2006|title=On the Name and Origins of 'Chopchi' Healing Practices|journal=Bulletin of Armenian Studies|pages=61\u201366|ref=harv|number=1}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Antonyan|first=Yulia|author-mask={{long dash}}|year=2003|title=Pre-Christian Healers in a Christian Society|journal=Cultural Survival Quarterly|volume=27|ref=harv|number=2}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://arordiukht.do.am/ Order of the Children of Ari] \u2014 official website\n* [http://www.hayary.org/ Armenian Aryan Congregation] \u2014 official website\n{{Neopaganism}}\n\n[[Category:Modern Pagan traditions]]\n[[Category:Neopaganism in Europe]]\n[[Category:Neopaganism by country]]\n[[Category:Religion in Armenia]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hetanism}}\n", "name_user": "Bdijkstra", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixingdisallowed DISPLAYTITLE modifications", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Armenian_Native_Faith"}
{"title_page": "Bearded vulture", "text_new": "{{redirect|Ossifrage|the ship|SS Ossifrage}}\n{{short description|Species of bird}}\n{{speciesbox\n| fossil_range = {{fossil range|3.6|0|[[Pliocene]] \u2013 Recent}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Fossilworks Gypaetus barbatus|url=http://fossilworks.org/bridge.pl?a=taxonInfo&taxon_no=105599}}</ref>\n| name = Bearded vulture\n| status = NT\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22695174/0 |title=''Gypaetus barbatus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2013 |accessdate=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| image = Bartgeier Gypaetus barbatus front Richard Bartz.jpg\n| genus = Gypaetus\n| parent_authority = [[Gottlieb Conrad Christian Storr|Storr]], 1784\n| species = barbatus\n| authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])\n| range_map = GypaetusBarbatusIUCNver2018 2.png\n| range_map_caption =Distribution of ''Gypaetus barbatus'' {{leftlegend|#008000|Resident|outline=gray}} {{leftlegend|#007FFF|Non-breeding|outline=gray}} {{leftlegend|#FF8080|Probably extinct|outline=gray}}{{leftlegend|#FF0000|Extinct|outline=gray}} {{leftlegend|#AAFFAA|Possibly Extant (resident)|outline=gray}} {{leftlegend|#FFFF00|Extant & Reintroduced (resident)|outline=gray}} \n| synonyms = ''Vultur barbatus'' {{small|Linnaeus,&nbsp;1758}}\n}}\n\nThe '''bearded vulture''' (''Gypaetus barbatus''), also known as the '''lammergeier''' (or '''lammergeyer'''){{efn|The German spelling ''L\u00e4mmergeier'' is never used in English.}}<ref>[https://www.ahdictionary.com/word/search.html?q=lammergeier American Heritage Dictionary]</ref><ref>[https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/lammergeier Oxford Dictionaries Online]</ref> or '''ossifrage''', is a [[bird of prey]] and the only member of the genus ''Gypaetus''. Traditionally considered an [[Old World vulture]], it actually forms a minor lineage of [[Accipitridae]] together with the [[Egyptian vulture]] (''Neophron percnopterus''), its closest living relative. It is not much more closely related to the Old World vultures proper than to, for example, [[hawk]]s, and differs from the former by its feathered neck. Although dissimilar, the Egyptian and bearded vulture each have a [[lozenge]]-shaped tail\u2014unusual among birds of prey.\n\nThe bearded vulture is the only known vertebrate whose diet consists almost exclusively (70 to 90 percent) of bone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/about_our_earth/species/profiles/birds/bearded_vulture/|title=Bearded vulture|publisher=}}</ref>  It lives and breeds on crags in high mountains in southern [[Europe]], the [[Caucasus]],<ref name=Gavashelishvili5>{{cite journal |last1=Gavashelishvili| first1=A.|last2= McGrady|first2= M. J. |year=2006 |title=Breeding site selection by bearded vulture (''Gypaetus barbatus'') and Eurasian griffon (''Gyps fulvus'') in the Caucasus |journal=Animal Conservation |volume=9 |issue=2 |pages=159\u2013170 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2005.00017.x}}</ref><ref name=Gavashelishvili6>{{cite journal |last1=Gavashelishvili| first1=A.|last2= McGrady|first2= M. J.|year=2006 |title=Geographic information system-based modelling of vulture response to carcass appearance in the Caucasus |journal=Journal of Zoology |volume=269 |issue=3 |pages=365\u2013372 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-7998.2006.00062.x}}</ref><ref name=Gavashelishvili8>{{cite journal |last1=Gavashelishvili| first1=A.|last2= McGrady|first2= M. J. |year=2007 |title=Radio-satellite telemetry of a territorial Bearded Vulture ''Gypaetus barbatus'' in the Caucasus |journal=Vulture News |volume=56 |pages=4\u201313}}</ref> [[Africa]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.africanraptors.org/conservation-of-the-bearded-vulture-gypaetus-barbatus-meridionalis-by-sonja-kruger/ |title=Conservation of the Bearded Vulture ''Gypaetus barbatus meridionalis''|first= Sonja |last=Kr\u00fcger |publisher=Africanraptors.org |date=2010-04-19 |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> the [[India]]n subcontinent, and [[Tibet]], laying one or two [[Egg (biology)|eggs]] in mid-winter that hatch at the beginning of spring. Populations are residents.\n\nThe population of this species continues to decline. Until July 2014, it was classified by the [[IUCN Red List|IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]] as being of [[Least Concern]]; it has, however, since been reassessed as [[Near Threatened]].\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\nThe lammergeier is sparsely distributed across a vast, considerable range. It can be found in mountainous regions from [[Europe]] east to [[Siberia]] ([[Palearctic]]) and [[Africa]]. It is found in the [[Pyrenees]], the [[Alps]], the [[Caucasus]] region, the [[Zagros Mountains]], the [[Alborz]], the [[Koh-i-Baba]] in [[Bamyan]], [[Afghanistan]], the [[Altai Mountains]], the [[Himalayas]], Ladakh in northern India, western and central [[China]], [[Israel]] (Where although extinct as a breeder since 1981, single young birds have been reported in 2000, 2004 and 2016 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.birds.org.il/en/article-page.aspx?articleId=363|title=News from the field - Daily Updates|website=\u05e4\u05d5\u05e8\u05d8\u05dc \u05e6\u05e4\u05e8\u05d5\u05ea}}</ref>), and the [[Arabian Peninsula]]. In Africa, it is found in the [[Atlas Mountains]], the [[Ethiopian Highlands]] and down from [[Sudan]] to northeastern [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], central [[Kenya]] and northern [[Tanzania]]. An isolated population inhabits the [[Drakensberg]] of [[South Africa]].<ref name=RaptorsWorld>{{cite book | last = Ferguson-Lees | first = James | authorlink = James Ferguson-Lees | last2 = Christie | first2 = David A. | year = 2001| others = Illustrated by Kim Franklin, David Mead, and Philip Burton | title = Raptors of the World | publisher = Houghton Mifflin | isbn = 978-0-618-12762-7| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=hlIztc05HTQC&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1 | accessdate = 2011-05-29 |page=417}}</ref>\n\nThis species is almost entirely associated with mountains and [[Monadnock|inselbergs]] with plentiful cliffs, crags, precipices, canyons and gorges. They are often found near [[Transhumance in the Alps|alpine pastures]] and [[Alpine tundra|meadows]], [[Montane grasslands and shrublands|montane grassland]] and [[heath]], steep-sided, rocky [[wadi]]s, high [[steppe]] and are occasional around [[forest]]s. They seem to prefer desolate, lightly-populated areas where predators who provide many bones, such as [[gray wolf|wolves]] and [[golden eagle]]s, have healthy populations.\n\nIn [[Ethiopia]], they are now common at refuse tips on the outskirts of small villages and towns. Although they occasionally descend to {{convert|300|-|600|m|ft|abbr=on}}, bearded vultures are rare below an elevation of {{convert|1000|m|ft|abbr=on}} and normally reside above {{convert|2000|m|ft|abbr=on}} in some parts of their range. They are typically found around or above the [[tree line]] which are often near the tops of the mountains, at up to {{convert|2000|m|ft|abbr=on}} in Europe, {{convert|4500|m|ft|abbr=on}} in Africa and {{convert|5000|m|ft|abbr=on}} in central Asia. In southern Armenia they have been found to breed below {{convert|1000|m|ft|abbr=on}} if cliff availability permits.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bearded Vulture|year=2017|website=Armenian Bird Census Council|url=http://www.abcc-am.org/bearded-vulture.html}}</ref> They even have been observed living at altitudes of {{convert|7500|m|ft|abbr=on}} on [[Mount Everest]] and been observed flying at a height of {{convert|24000|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Gavashelishvili5\"/><ref name=\"Gavashelishvili6\"/><ref name=\"Gavashelishvili8\"/><ref name=RaptorsWorld/><ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Bruce\n  | first = Charles Granville\n  | authorlink = Charles Granville Bruce\n  | year = 1923\n  | title = The assault on Mount Everest 1922\n  | publisher = Longmans, Green and Co\n  | location = London\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/assaultonmountev00bruc}}</ref>\n\nDuring 1970s and 1980s the population of the bearded vulture in southern Africa declined however their distribution remained constant. The bearded vulture population occupies the highlands of Lesotho, Free State, Eastern Cape and Maloti-Drakensburg mountains in Kwa-Zulu Natal . Adult bearded vultures utilize areas with higher altitudes, with steep slopes and sharp points and within areas that are situated closer to their nesting sites . Adult bearded vultures are more likely to fly below 200m over Lesotho. Along the Drakensburg Escarpment from the area of Golden Gate Highlands Park south into the northern part of the Eastern Cape there was the greatest densities of bearded vultures.\n\nAbundance of bearded vultures is shown for eight regions within the species' range in southern Africa.<ref name=Ostrich>{{cite journal |last1=Brown |first1=C. J. |title=Distribution and status of the Bearded Vulture ''Gypaetus barbatus'' in southern Africa |journal=Ostrich |date=11 October 2010 |volume=63 |issue=1 |pages=1\u20139 |doi=10.1080/00306525.1992.9634172 }}</ref> The total population of bearded vultures in southern Africa is calculated as being 408 adult birds and 224 young birds of all age classes therefore giving an estimate of about 632 birds.<ref name= Ostrich/>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Bearded vulture.jpg|thumb|A lammergeier in Puga valley in east of Ladakh.]]\nThis bird is {{convert|94|-|125|cm|in|abbr=on}} long with a [[wingspan]] of {{convert|2.31|-|2.83|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> It weighs {{convert|4.5|-|7.8|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, with the nominate race averaging {{convert|6.21|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and ''G. b. meridionalis'' of Africa averaging {{convert|5.7|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> In Eurasia, vultures found around the Himalayas tend to be slightly larger than those from other mountain ranges.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Females are slightly larger than males.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/><ref>{{cite book|last=Beaman|first=Mark |last2= Madge|first2=Steve|title=The Handbook of Bird Identification for Europe and the Western Palearctic|publisher= Princeton University Press |year=1999|isbn= 978-0-691-02726-5}}</ref> It is essentially unmistakable with other vultures or indeed other birds in flight due to its long, narrow wings, with the [[Wing chord (biology)|wing chord]] measuring {{convert|71.5|-|91|cm|in|abbr=on}}, and long, wedge-shaped tail, which measures {{convert|42.7|-|52|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length. The tail is longer than the width of the wing.<ref>Lee, W-S; Koo,T-H; Park, J-Y (2005). A Field Guide to the Birds of Korea. p. 98. {{ISBN|978-8995141533}}.</ref> The tarsus is relatively small for the bird's size, at {{convert|8.8|-|10|cm|in|abbr=on}}. The proportions of the species have been compared to a [[falcon]], scaled to an enormous size.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/>\n\nUnlike most vultures, the bearded vulture does not have a bald head. This species is relatively small headed, although its neck is powerful and thick. It has a generally elongated, slender shape, sometimes appearing bulkier due to the often hunched back of these birds. The gait on the ground is waddling and the feet are large and powerful. The adult is mostly dark gray, rusty and whitish in color. It is grey-blue to grey-black above. The creamy-coloured forehead contrasts against a black band across the eyes and lores and bristles under the chin, which form a black beard that give the species its English name. Bearded vultures are variably orange or rust of plumage on their head, breast and leg feathers but this is actually cosmetic. This colouration may come from dust-bathing, rubbing mud on its body or from drinking in mineral-rich waters. The tail feathers and wings are gray. The juvenile bird is dark black-brown over most of the body, with a buff-brown breast and takes five years to reach full maturity. The bearded vulture is silent, apart from shrill whistles in their breeding displays and a falcon-like ''cheek-acheek'' call made around the nest.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/>\n\n<gallery mode=packed>\nFile:NovitatesZoologicae18 532 Gypaetus barbatus nestling.png|Nestlings are covered in dark [[down feather]]s\nFile:Gypaetus-barbatus-bearded-vulture-0b.jpg|The juvenile bird is mostly dark\nFile:Bartgeier 0505262.jpg|The adult has a buff-yellow body and head\nFile:Lammergeier or Bearded Vulture, Gypaetus barbatus. In flight.jpg|Adult in flight from below (note the tail shape)\nFile:Bartgeier_Gypaetus_barbatus_front2_Richard_Bartz.jpg|Adult spreading wings\n</gallery>\n\n=== Physiology ===\nThe acid concentration of the bearded vulture stomach has been estimated to be of pH about 1. Large bones will be digested in about 24 hours, aided by slow mixing/churning of the stomach content. The high fat content of bone marrow makes the net energy value of bone almost as good as that of muscle, even if bone is less completely digested. A skeleton left on a mountain will dehydrate and become protected from bacterial degradation, and the bearded vulture can return to consume the remainder of a carcass even months after the soft parts have been consumed by other animals, larvae and bacteria.<ref name=\"acid\">{{cite journal\n| year= 1994 |journal=J. Raptor Res.|volume= 28|issue=2|pages=73\u201378\n| url = http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/jrr/v028n02/p00073-p00078.pdf | title=Bone Digestion and Intestinal Morphology of the Bearded Vulture\n| accessdate = 2011-07-24\n| last1= Houston|first1=D.C. |last2= Copsey|first2=J.A.}}</ref>\n\n== Behaviour ==\n===Diet and feeding===\n[[File:Gipeto adulto.jpg|thumb|A flying bearded vulture in [[Gran Paradiso National Park]], [[Italy]]]]\n[[File:Gypaetus Barbatus.jpg|thumb|Bearded vulture on the rocks in [[Gran Paradiso National Park]].]]\nLike other [[vulture]]s, it is a [[scavenger]], feeding mostly on the remains of [[Carrion|dead animals]]. The bearded vulture diet comprises mammals (93%), birds (6%) and reptiles (1%), with medium-sized ungulates forming a large part of the diet.<ref name=\"Margalida et al 2009\"/>\nBearded vultures avoid remains of larger species (such as cows and horses) probably because of the variable cost/benefit ratios in handling efficiency, ingestion process and transportation of the remains.<ref name=\"Margalida et al 2009\"/>\nIt usually disdains the actual meat and lives on a diet that is typically 85\u201390% [[bone marrow]]. This is the only living bird species that specializes in feeding on marrow.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> The bearded vulture can swallow whole or bite through brittle bones up to the size of a lamb's femur<ref name=\"PBS-Bhutan\">\n{{cite web\n| title = Lammergeier Vulture\n| work= The Living Edens&nbsp;\u2014 Bhutan\n| publisher = PBS\n| url = https://www.pbs.org/edens/bhutan/a_lv.htm\n| accessdate = 2011-05-30\n}}\n</ref> and its powerful digestive system quickly dissolves even large pieces. The bearded vulture has learned to crack bones too large to be swallowed by carrying them in flight to a height of {{convert|50|-|150|m|ft|abbr=on}} above the ground and then dropping them onto rocks below, which smashes them into smaller pieces and exposes the nutritious marrow.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> They can fly with bones up to {{convert|10|cm|in|abbr=on}} in diameter and weighing over {{convert|4|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, or nearly equal to their own weight.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/>\n\nAfter dropping the large bones, the bearded vulture spirals or glides down to inspect them and may repeat the act if the bone is not sufficiently cracked.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> This learned skill requires extensive practice by immature birds and takes up to seven years to master.<ref name=\"BBC-BeardedVulture\">{{cite web| work = Wildlife Finder|title=Lammergeier (video, facts and news)| publisher = BBC| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/nature/species/Bearded_Vulture| accessdate = 2011-05-29}}</ref> Its old name of ''ossifrage'' (\"bone breaker\") relates to this habit. Less frequently, these birds have been observed trying to break bones (usually of a medium size) by hammering them with their bill directly into rocks while perched.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> During the breeding season they feed mainly on carrion. They prefer limbs of sheep and other small mammals and they carry the food to the nest, unlike other vultures which feed their young by regurgitation.<ref name=\"Margalida et al 2009\">{{cite journal |last1=Margalida |first1=Antoni |last2=Bertra |first2=Joan |last3=Heredia |first3=Rafael |title=Diet and food preferences of the endangered Bearded Vulture ''Gypaetus barbatus'': a basis for their conservation |journal=Ibis |date=23 March 2009 |volume=151 |issue=2 |pages=235\u2013243 |doi=10.1111/j.1474-919x.2008.00904.x }}</ref>\n\nLive prey is sometimes attacked by the bearded vulture, with perhaps greater regularity than any other vulture.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Among these, [[tortoise]]s seem to be especially favored depending on their local abundance. Tortoises preyed on may be nearly as heavy as the preying vulture. To kill tortoises, bearded vultures fly with them to some height and drop them to crack open the bulky reptiles' hard shells. Golden eagles have been observed to kill tortoises in the same way.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Other live animals, up to nearly their own size, have been observed to be predaciously seized and dropped in flight. Among these are [[rock hyrax]]es, [[hare]]s, [[marmot]]s and, in one case, a {{convert|62|cm|in|abbr=on}} long [[monitor lizard]].<ref name=RaptorsWorld/><ref name=\"PBS-Bhutan\" /> Larger animals have been known to be attacked by bearded vultures, including [[ibex]], [[Capra (genus)|''Capra'' goats]], [[Chamois]] and [[Steenbok]].<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> These animals have been killed by being surprised by the large birds and battered with wings until they fall off precipitous rocky edges to their deaths; although in some cases these may be accidental killings when both the vulture and the mammal surprise each other.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Many large animals killed by bearded vultures are unsteady young, or have appeared sickly or obviously injured.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Humans have been anecdotally reported to have been killed in the same way.  This is unconfirmed, however, and if it does happen, most biologists who have studied the birds generally agree it would be accidental on the part of the vulture.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Occasionally smaller ground-dwelling birds, such as [[partridge]]s and [[pigeon]]s, have been reported eaten, possibly either as fresh carrion (which is usually ignored by these birds) or killed with beating wings by the vulture.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> While foraging for bones or live prey while in flight, bearded vultures fly fairly low over the rocky ground, staying around {{convert|2|to|4|m|ft|abbr=on}} high.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Occasionally, breeding pairs may forage and hunt together.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> In the [[Ethiopian Highlands]], bearded vultures have adapted to living largely off human refuse.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/>\n\n===Breeding===\nThe bearded vulture occupies an enormous territory year-round. It may forage over two square kilometers each day. The breeding period is variable, being December through September in [[Eurasia]], November to June in the [[Indian subcontinent]], October to May in [[Ethiopia]], throughout the year in eastern Africa and May to January in southern Africa.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Although generally solitary, the bond between a breeding pair is often considerably close. Biparental monogamous care occurs in the bearded vulture.<ref name=\"Margalida et al 2000\">{{cite journal |last1=Margalida |first1=Antoni |last2=Bertran |first2=Joan |title=Breeding behaviour of the Bearded Vulture ''Gypaetus barbatus'': minimal sexual differences in parental activities |journal=Ibis |date=28 June 2008 |volume=142 |issue=2 |pages=225\u2013234 |doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.2000.tb04862.x }}</ref> In a few cases, [[polyandry]] has been recorded in the species.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> The territorial and breeding display between bearded vultures is often spectacular, involving the showing of talons, tumbling and spiralling while in solo flight. The large birds also regularly lock feet with each other and fall some distance through the sky with each other.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> In Europe the breeding pairs of bearded vultures are estimated to be 120.<ref name= Donazar>{{cite journal |last1=Donazar |first1=J. A. |last2=Hiraldo |first2=F. |last3=Bustamante |first3=J. |title=Factors Influencing Nest Site Selection, Breeding Density and Breeding Success in the Bearded Vulture (''Gypaetus barbatus'') |journal=Journal of Applied Ecology |date=1993 |volume=30 |issue=3 |pages=504\u2013514 |doi=10.2307/2404190 |jstor=2404190 |hdl=10261/47110 }}</ref> The mean productivity of the bearded vulture is 0.43\u00b10.28 fledgings/breeding pair/year and the breeding success averaged 0.56\u00b10.30 fledgings/pair with clutches/year.<ref name=\"Margalida et al 2003\">{{cite journal |last1=Margalida |first1=Antoni |last2=Garcia |first2=Diego |last3=Bertran |first3=Joan |last4=Heredia |first4=Rafael |title=Breeding biology and success of the Bearded Vulture ''Gypaetus barbatus'' in the eastern Pyrenees |journal=Ibis |date=27 March 2003 |volume=145 |issue=2 |pages=244\u2013252 |doi=10.1046/j.1474-919X.2003.00148.x }}</ref>\n\nThe nest is a massive pile of sticks, that goes from around {{convert|1|m|ft|abbr=on}} across and {{convert|69|cm|in|abbr=on}} deep when first constructed up to {{convert|2.5|m|ft|abbr=on}} across and {{convert|1|m|ft|abbr=on}} deep, with a covering of various animal matter from food, after repeated uses. The female usually lays a clutch of 1 to 2 eggs, though 3 have been recorded on rare occasions.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> which are incubated for 53 to 60 days. After hatching, the young spend 100 to 130 days in the nest before [[Fledge|fledging]]. The young may be dependent on the parents for up to 2 years, forcing the parents to nest in alternate years on a regular basis.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Typically, the bearded vulture nests in caves and on ledges and rock outcrops or caves on steep rock walls, so are very difficult for nest-predating mammals to access.<ref name=\"PBS-Bhutan\" /> Wild bearded vultures have a mean lifespan of 21.4 years,<ref name=\"CJBrown1997\">{{cite journal|last1=Brown|first1=C.J.|title=Population dynamics of the bearded vulture ''Gypaetus barbatus'' in southern Africa|journal=African Journal of Ecology|date=March 1997|volume=35|issue=1|pages=53\u201363|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2028.1997.048-89048.x}}</ref> but have been observed to live for up to at least 45 years in captivity.<ref name=\"RJAntor2007\">{{cite journal |last1=Antor |first1=Ram\u00f3n J. |last2=Margalida |first2=Antoni |last3=Frey |first3=Hans |last4=Heredia |first4=Rafael |last5=Lorente |first5=Luis |last6=Ses\u00e9 |first6=Jos\u00e9 Antonio |title=First Breeding Age in Captive and Wild Bearded Vultures |journal=Acta Ornithologica |date=July 2007 |volume=42 |issue=1 |pages=114\u2013118 |doi=10.3161/068.042.0106 }}</ref>\n<gallery>\nGypa\u00e8te barbu MHNT.jpg|''Gypaetus barbatus aureus'' egg \u2013 [[MHNT]]\nGypaetus barbatus hemachalanus MHNT.jpg|''Gypaetus barbatus hemachalanus'' egg \u2013 [[MHNT]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Reintroduction in the Alps==\nThe bearded vulture had a very poor reputation in early modern Europe, due in large part to tales of the birds stealing babies and livestock. The growing availability of firearms, combined with bounties offered for dead vultures, caused a sharp decline in the bearded vulture population around the Alps. By the beginning of the 20th century, they had completely disappeared from the Alpine regions.\n\nEfforts to reintroduce the bearded vulture began in earnest in the 1970s, in the French Alps. Zoologists Paul Geroudet and Gilbert Amigues attempted to release vultures that had been captured in Afghanistan, but this approach proved unsuccessful: it was too difficult to capture the vultures in the first place, and too many died in transport on their way to France. A second attempt was made in 1987, using a technique called \"hacking,\" by which young individuals (from 90\u2013100 days) from zoological parks would be taken from the nest and placed in a protected area in the Alps. As they were still unable to fly at that age, the chicks were hand-fed by humans until the birds learned to fly and were able to reach food without human assistance. This method has proven more successful, with over 200 birds released in the Alps from 1987 to 2015, and a bearded vulture population has reestablished itself in the Alps.<ref>http://gypaetebarbu.ch/project/reintroduction, 31.5.2018, Pro Gypa\u00e8te</ref>\n\n== Threats and conservation status ==\n[[File:Lammergeier with boy, Kabul, 1973.JPG|thumb|upright|Boy with live bearded vulture, [[Kabul]]]]\nThe bearded vulture is one of the most endangered European bird species as over the last century its abundance and breeding range have drastically declined.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bretagnolle |first1=Vincent |last2=Inchausti |first2=Pablo |last3=Seguin |first3=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois |last4=Thibault |first4=Jean-Claude |title=Evaluation of the extinction risk and of conservation alternatives for a very small insular population: the bearded vulture ''Gypaetus barbatus'' in Corsica |journal=Biological Conservation |date=November 2004 |volume=120 |issue=1 |pages=19\u201330 |doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2004.01.023 }}</ref> It naturally occurs at low densities, with anywhere from a dozen to 500 pairs now being found in each mountain range in Eurasia where the species breeds. The species is most common in [[Ethiopia]], where an estimated 1,400 to 2,200 are believed to breed.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Relatively large, healthy numbers seem to occur in some parts of the Himalayas as well. It was largely wiped out in Europe, and by the beginning of the 20th century the only substantial population was in the Spanish and French Pyrenees. Since then, it has been successfully reintroduced to the [[Swiss]] and [[Italy|Italian]] Alps, from where they have spread over into [[France]].<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> They have also declined somewhat in parts of Asia and Africa, though less severely than in Europe.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/>\n\nMany raptor species were shielded from anthropogenic influences in previously underdeveloped areas therefore they are greatly impacted as the human population rises and infrastructure increases in underdeveloped areas. The increase in human population and infrastructure results in the declines of the bearded vulture populations today. The increase of infrastructure includes the building of houses, roads and power lines and a major issue with infrastructure and bird species populations is the collision with power lines.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal|journal = PLOS ONE| year=2014| volume=9| issue=12| pages=e114920| title=Differential Range Use between Age Classes of Southern African Bearded Vultures ''Gypaetus barbatus''| author1=Kruger, Sonja| author2=Reid, Timothy| author3=Amar, Arjun|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0114920| pmid=25551614| pmc=4281122| bibcode=2014PLoSO...9k4920K}}</ref> The declines of the bearded vulture populations have been documented throughout their range resulting from a decrease in habitat space, fatal collisions with energy infrastructure, reduced food availability, poisons left out for carnivores and direct persecution in the form of Trophy Hunting.<ref name=\"howstuffworks\">{{cite web\n| title = Lammergeier\n| date = 2008-04-22\n| publisher = Discovery Communications\n| work = howstuffworks.com\n| url = http://animals.howstuffworks.com/birds/lammergeier-info.htm\n| accessdate = 2011-05-29| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110712230041/http://animals.howstuffworks.com/birds/lammergeier-info.htm| archivedate= 12 July 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThis species is currently listed as Near Threatened by the IUCN Red List last accessed on 1 October 2016, the population continues to decline as the distribution ranges of this species continues to decline due to human development.\n\n== Conservation action ==\n\nThere have been mitigation plans that have been established to reduce the population declines in bearded vulture populations. One of these plans includes the South African Biodiversity Management Plan that has been ratified by the government to stop the population decline in the short term. Actions that have been implemented include the mitigation of existing and proposed energy structures to prevent collision risks, the improved management of supplementary feeding sites as well to reduce the populations from being exposed to human persecution and poisoning accidents and to also have outreach programmes that are aimed as reducing poisoning incidents.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n== Etymology ==\nThis species was first described by [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]] in his ''[[Systema naturae]]'' in 1758 as ''Vultur barbatus''.<ref name=\"Linnaeus1758\">\n{{cite book\n| last = Linnaeus\n| first = Carolus\n| authorlink =Carl Linnaeus| year = 1758\n| title = Systema naturae per regna tria naturae, secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis. Tomus I. Editio decima, reformata\n| volume = v.1\n| page = 87\n| publisher = Holmiae. (Laurentii Salvii)\n| language = Latin\n|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/726992\n| quote = V. albidus, dorso fusco, jugulo barbato, rostro incarnato, capite linea nigra cincto.\n}}</ref> The present scientific name means \"bearded vulture-eagle\".\n\nThe name ''lammergeyer'' originates from [[German language|German]] ''{{lang|de|L\u00e4mmergeier}}'', which means \"lamb-vulture\". The name stems from the belief that it attacked [[Domestic sheep|lambs]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Everett|first=Mike|year=2008|title=Lammergeiers and lambs|journal=British Birds|volume= 101 |issue=4|page= 215}}</ref>\n\n== In culture ==\n<!-- Commented out: [[File:Iran Air logo.svg|thumb|Homa bird in the logo of [[Iran Air]]]] -->\nThe bearded vulture is considered a threatened species in [[Iran]]. Iranian mythology considers the rare bearded vulture ([[Persian language|Persian]]: \u0647\u0645\u0627, 'Homa') the symbol of luck and happiness. It was believed that if the shadow of a ''[[Huma bird|Homa]]'' fell on one, he would rise to sovereignty<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pollard |first1=J. R. T. |title=The Lammergeyer Comparative Descriptions in Aristotle and Pliny |journal=Greece and Rome |date=5 January 2009 |volume=16 |issue=46 |pages=23\u201328 |doi=10.1017/s0017383500009311}}</ref> and anyone shooting the bird would die in forty days. The habit of eating bones and apparently not killing living animals was noted by [[Saadi Shirazi|Sa'di]] in [[Gulistan (book)|Gulistan]] published in 1258 and Emperor Jahangir had the crop examined in 1625 to find that it was filled with bones.<ref>{{cite journal| title= Note on the Huma or Lammergeyer| url=https://archive.org/stream/mobot31753003193114#page/532/mode/1up | pages=532\u2013533| journal=Journal of the Asiatic Society of Bengal| year=1906| volume=2| issue=10| author=Phillott, D.C.|authorlink=Douglas Craven Phillott}}</ref>\n\nThe ancient [[Greeks]] used [[Ornithomancy|ornithomancer]]s to guide their political decisions: bearded vultures, or ossifragae were one of the few species of birds that could yield valid signs to these soothsayers.\n\nThe [[Greece|Greek]] playwright [[Aeschylus]] was said to have been killed in 456 or 455 BC by a [[tortoise]] dropped by an eagle who mistook his bald head for a stone \u2013 if this incident did occur, the bearded vulture is a likely candidate for the \"eagle\".\n\nIn the [[Bible]]/[[Torah]], the bearded vulture, as the ossifrage, is among the birds forbidden to be eaten ([[Leviticus]] 11:13).\n\nMore recently, in 1944, [[Shimon Peres]] (called Shimon Persky at the time) and [[David Ben-Gurion]] found a nest of bearded vultures in the [[Negev]] desert. The bird is called ''{{lang|he-Latn|peres}}'' in [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], and Shimon Persky liked it so much he adopted it as his [[surname]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Marche\n  | first = Stephen\n  | date = 2008-06-13\n  | title = Flight of Fancy\n  | journal = The New Republic\n  | url = http://www.tnr.com/article/politics/flight-fancy\n  | accessdate = 2011-05-31}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://slideblast.com/-in-memory-of-shimon-peres_59cd3bb31723dd5beeb47f52.html\n |title=In Memory of Israel's 9th President, Shimon Peres, 'The National Bird'\n |last=Leshem\n |first=Yossi\n |date=\n |website=\n |publisher=\n |access-date=2018-06-05\n |quote= }}</ref>\n\nRobot bearded vultures appear in some science fiction literature, including the first volume of the [[Viriconium]] series by M. John Harrison and [[Feersum Endjinn]] by [[Iain Banks|Iain M. Banks]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Gypaetus barbatus}}\n{{Wikispecies|Gypaetus barbatus}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101126140941/http://www.arkive.org/lammergeier/gypaetus-barbatus/video-08.html Video of lammergeier shattering bones into smaller pieces on which it then feeds] at ARKive\n* [http://sabap2.adu.org.za/docs/sabap1/119.pdf Species text] in The Atlas of Southern African Birds\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120621212539/http://www.vulture-territory.com/bearded.html Facts and Characteristics: Bearded Vulture] at Vulture Territory \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121029071234/http://www.iberianature.com/material/lammergeyer.html The Lammergeier in Spain]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20190103175505/http://www.cam3001.com/SEITEN/GypaetusFr.html Cine and photo work about the Bearded Vulture in the Alps]\n* [http://wwf.panda.org/about_our_earth/species/profiles/birds/bearded_vulture/ diet information]\n* [http://www.abcc-am.org/bearded-vulture.html Bearded Vulture in Armenia, Armenian Bird Census Council. 2017.]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/BBCOne/videos/bearded-vulture-the-snow-wolf-a-winters-tale/234415154152599/ Bone-eating vulture and a snow wolf]\n*{{cite journal |last1=Robert |first1=Isabelle |last2=Vigne |first2=Jean-Denis |title=The Bearded Vulture (''Gypaetus barbatus'') as an Accumulator of Archaeological Bones. Late Glacial Assemblages and Present-day Reference Data in Corsica (Western Mediterranean) |journal=Journal of Archaeological Science |date=July 2002 |volume=29 |issue=7 |pages=763\u2013777 |doi=10.1006/jasc.2001.0778 }}\n\n{{Vulture}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q126167}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:vulture, bearded}}\n[[Category:Old World vultures|bearded vulture]]\n[[Category:Birds of prey of Africa]]\n[[Category:Birds of Europe]]\n[[Category:Birds of Tibet]]\n[[Category:Birds of Western Asia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1758|bearded vulture]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Ossifrage|the ship|SS Ossifrage}}\n{{short description|Species of bird}}\n{{speciesbox\n| fossil_range = {{fossil range|3.6|0|[[Pliocene]] \u2013 Recent}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Fossilworks Gypaetus barbatus|url=http://fossilworks.org/bridge.pl?a=taxonInfo&taxon_no=105599}}</ref>\n| name = Bearded vulture\n| status = NT\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22695174/0 |title=''Gypaetus barbatus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2013 |accessdate=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| image = Bartgeier Gypaetus barbatus front Richard Bartz.jpg\n| genus = Gypaetus\n| parent_authority = [[Gottlieb Conrad Christian Storr|Storr]], 1784\n| species = barbatus\n| authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])\n| range_map = GypaetusBarbatusIUCNver2018 2.png\n| range_map_caption =Distribution of ''Gypaetus barbatus'' {{leftlegend|#008000|Resident|outline=gray}} {{leftlegend|#007FFF|Non-breeding|outline=gray}} {{leftlegend|#FF8080|Probably extinct|outline=gray}}{{leftlegend|#FF0000|Extinct|outline=gray}} {{leftlegend|#AAFFAA|Possibly Extant (resident)|outline=gray}} {{leftlegend|#FFFF00|Extant & Reintroduced (resident)|outline=gray}} \n| synonyms = ''Vultur barbatus'' {{small|Linnaeus,&nbsp;1758}}\n}}\n\nThe '''bearded vulture''' (''Gypaetus barbatus''), also known as the '''lammergeier''' (or '''lammergeyer'''){{efn|The German spelling ''L\u00e4mmergeier'' is never used in English.}}<ref>[https://www.ahdictionary.com/word/search.html?q=lammergeier American Heritage Dictionary]</ref><ref>[https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/lammergeier Oxford Dictionaries Online]</ref> or '''ossifrage''', is a [[bird of prey]] and the only member of the genus ''Gypaetus''. Traditionally considered an [[Old World vulture]], it actually forms a minor lineage of [[Accipitridae]] together with the [[Egyptian vulture]] (''Neophron percnopterus''), its closest living relative. It is not much more closely related to the Old World vultures proper than to, for example, [[hawk]]s, and differs from the former by its feathered neck. Although dissimilar, the Egyptian and bearded vulture each have a [[lozenge]]-shaped tail\u2014unusual among birds of prey.\n\nThe bearded vulture is the only known vertebrate whose diet consists almost exclusively (70 to 90 percent) of bone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwf.panda.org/about_our_earth/species/profiles/birds/bearded_vulture/|title=Bearded vulture|publisher=}}</ref>  It lives and breeds on crags in high mountains in southern [[Europe]], the [[Caucasus]],<ref name=Gavashelishvili5>{{cite journal |last1=Gavashelishvili| first1=A.|last2= McGrady|first2= M. J. |year=2006 |title=Breeding site selection by bearded vulture (''Gypaetus barbatus'') and Eurasian griffon (''Gyps fulvus'') in the Caucasus |journal=Animal Conservation |volume=9 |issue=2 |pages=159\u2013170 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2005.00017.x}}</ref><ref name=Gavashelishvili6>{{cite journal |last1=Gavashelishvili| first1=A.|last2= McGrady|first2= M. J.|year=2006 |title=Geographic information system-based modelling of vulture response to carcass appearance in the Caucasus |journal=Journal of Zoology |volume=269 |issue=3 |pages=365\u2013372 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-7998.2006.00062.x}}</ref><ref name=Gavashelishvili8>{{cite journal |last1=Gavashelishvili| first1=A.|last2= McGrady|first2= M. J. |year=2007 |title=Radio-satellite telemetry of a territorial Bearded Vulture ''Gypaetus barbatus'' in the Caucasus |journal=Vulture News |volume=56 |pages=4\u201313}}</ref> [[Africa]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.africanraptors.org/conservation-of-the-bearded-vulture-gypaetus-barbatus-meridionalis-by-sonja-kruger/ |title=Conservation of the Bearded Vulture ''Gypaetus barbatus meridionalis''|first= Sonja |last=Kr\u00fcger |publisher=Africanraptors.org |date=2010-04-19 |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> the [[India]]n subcontinent, and [[Tibet]], laying one or two [[Egg (biology)|eggs]] in mid-winter that hatch at the beginning of spring. Populations are residents.\n\nThe population of this species continues to decline. Until July 2014, it was classified by the [[IUCN Red List|IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]] as being of [[Least Concern]]; it has, however, since been reassessed as [[Near Threatened]].\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\nThe lammergeier is sparsely distributed across a vast, considerable range. It can be found in mountainous regions from [[Europe]] east to [[Siberia]] ([[Palearctic]]) and [[Africa]]. It is found in  in the [[Pyrenees]], the [[Alps]], the [[Caucasus]] region, the [[Zagros Mountains]], the [[Alborz]], the [[Koh-i-Baba]] in [[Bamyan]], [[Afghanistan]], the [[Altai Mountains]], the [[Himalayas]], Ladakh in northern India, western and central [[China]], [[Israel]] (Where although extinct as a breeder since 1981, single young birds have been reported in 2000, 2004 and 2016 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.birds.org.il/en/article-page.aspx?articleId=363|title=News from the field - Daily Updates|website=\u05e4\u05d5\u05e8\u05d8\u05dc \u05e6\u05e4\u05e8\u05d5\u05ea}}</ref>), and the [[Arabian Peninsula]]. In Africa, it is found in the [[Atlas Mountains]], the [[Ethiopian Highlands]] and down from [[Sudan]] to northeastern [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], central [[Kenya]] and northern [[Tanzania]]. An isolated population inhabits the [[Drakensberg]] of [[South Africa]].<ref name=RaptorsWorld>{{cite book | last = Ferguson-Lees | first = James | authorlink = James Ferguson-Lees | last2 = Christie | first2 = David A. | year = 2001| others = Illustrated by Kim Franklin, David Mead, and Philip Burton | title = Raptors of the World | publisher = Houghton Mifflin | isbn = 978-0-618-12762-7| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=hlIztc05HTQC&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1 | accessdate = 2011-05-29 |page=417}}</ref>\n\nThis species is almost entirely associated with mountains and [[Monadnock|inselbergs]] with plentiful cliffs, crags, precipices, canyons and gorges. They are often found near [[Transhumance in the Alps|alpine pastures]] and [[Alpine tundra|meadows]], [[Montane grasslands and shrublands|montane grassland]] and [[heath]], steep-sided, rocky [[wadi]]s, high [[steppe]] and are occasional around [[forest]]s. They seem to prefer desolate, lightly-populated areas where predators who provide many bones, such as [[gray wolf|wolves]] and [[golden eagle]]s, have healthy populations.\n\nIn [[Ethiopia]], they are now common at refuse tips on the outskirts of small villages and towns. Although they occasionally descend to {{convert|300|-|600|m|ft|abbr=on}}, bearded vultures are rare below an elevation of {{convert|1000|m|ft|abbr=on}} and normally reside above {{convert|2000|m|ft|abbr=on}} in some parts of their range. They are typically found around or above the [[tree line]] which are often near the tops of the mountains, at up to {{convert|2000|m|ft|abbr=on}} in Europe, {{convert|4500|m|ft|abbr=on}} in Africa and {{convert|5000|m|ft|abbr=on}} in central Asia. In southern Armenia they have been found to breed below {{convert|1000|m|ft|abbr=on}} if cliff availability permits.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bearded Vulture|year=2017|website=Armenian Bird Census Council|url=http://www.abcc-am.org/bearded-vulture.html}}</ref> They even have been observed living at altitudes of {{convert|7500|m|ft|abbr=on}} on [[Mount Everest]] and been observed flying at a height of {{convert|24000|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Gavashelishvili5\"/><ref name=\"Gavashelishvili6\"/><ref name=\"Gavashelishvili8\"/><ref name=RaptorsWorld/><ref>{{cite book\n  | last = Bruce\n  | first = Charles Granville\n  | authorlink = Charles Granville Bruce\n  | year = 1923\n  | title = The assault on Mount Everest 1922\n  | publisher = Longmans, Green and Co\n  | location = London\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/assaultonmountev00bruc}}</ref>\n\nDuring 1970s and 1980s the population of the bearded vulture in southern Africa declined however their distribution remained constant. The bearded vulture population occupies the highlands of Lesotho, Free State, Eastern Cape and Maloti-Drakensburg mountains in Kwa-Zulu Natal . Adult bearded vultures utilize areas with higher altitudes, with steep slopes and sharp points and within areas that are situated closer to their nesting sites . Adult bearded vultures are more likely to fly below 200m over Lesotho. Along the Drakensburg Escarpment from the area of Golden Gate Highlands Park south into the northern part of the Eastern Cape there was the greatest densities of bearded vultures.\n\nAbundance of bearded vultures is shown for eight regions within the species' range in southern Africa.<ref name=Ostrich>{{cite journal |last1=Brown |first1=C. J. |title=Distribution and status of the Bearded Vulture ''Gypaetus barbatus'' in southern Africa |journal=Ostrich |date=11 October 2010 |volume=63 |issue=1 |pages=1\u20139 |doi=10.1080/00306525.1992.9634172 }}</ref> The total population of bearded vultures in southern Africa is calculated as being 408 adult birds and 224 young birds of all age classes therefore giving an estimate of about 632 birds.<ref name= Ostrich/>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Bearded vulture.jpg|thumb|A lammergeier in Puga valley in east of Ladakh.]]\nThis bird is {{convert|94|-|125|cm|in|abbr=on}} long with a [[wingspan]] of {{convert|2.31|-|2.83|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> It weighs {{convert|4.5|-|7.8|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, with the nominate race averaging {{convert|6.21|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and ''G. b. meridionalis'' of Africa averaging {{convert|5.7|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> In Eurasia, vultures found around the Himalayas tend to be slightly larger than those from other mountain ranges.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Females are slightly larger than males.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/><ref>{{cite book|last=Beaman|first=Mark |last2= Madge|first2=Steve|title=The Handbook of Bird Identification for Europe and the Western Palearctic|publisher= Princeton University Press |year=1999|isbn= 978-0-691-02726-5}}</ref> It is essentially unmistakable with other vultures or indeed other birds in flight due to its long, narrow wings, with the [[Wing chord (biology)|wing chord]] measuring {{convert|71.5|-|91|cm|in|abbr=on}}, and long, wedge-shaped tail, which measures {{convert|42.7|-|52|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length. The tail is longer than the width of the wing.<ref>Lee, W-S; Koo,T-H; Park, J-Y (2005). A Field Guide to the Birds of Korea. p. 98. {{ISBN|978-8995141533}}.</ref> The tarsus is relatively small for the bird's size, at {{convert|8.8|-|10|cm|in|abbr=on}}. The proportions of the species have been compared to a [[falcon]], scaled to an enormous size.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/>\n\nUnlike most vultures, the bearded vulture does not have a bald head. This species is relatively small headed, although its neck is powerful and thick. It has a generally elongated, slender shape, sometimes appearing bulkier due to the often hunched back of these birds. The gait on the ground is waddling and the feet are large and powerful. The adult is mostly dark gray, rusty and whitish in color. It is grey-blue to grey-black above. The creamy-coloured forehead contrasts against a black band across the eyes and lores and bristles under the chin, which form a black beard that give the species its English name. Bearded vultures are variably orange or rust of plumage on their head, breast and leg feathers but this is actually cosmetic. This colouration may come from dust-bathing, rubbing mud on its body or from drinking in mineral-rich waters. The tail feathers and wings are gray. The juvenile bird is dark black-brown over most of the body, with a buff-brown breast and takes five years to reach full maturity. The bearded vulture is silent, apart from shrill whistles in their breeding displays and a falcon-like ''cheek-acheek'' call made around the nest.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/>\n\n<gallery mode=packed>\nFile:NovitatesZoologicae18 532 Gypaetus barbatus nestling.png|Nestlings are covered in dark [[down feather]]s\nFile:Gypaetus-barbatus-bearded-vulture-0b.jpg|The juvenile bird is mostly dark\nFile:Bartgeier 0505262.jpg|The adult has a buff-yellow body and head\nFile:Lammergeier or Bearded Vulture, Gypaetus barbatus. In flight.jpg|Adult in flight from below (note the tail shape)\nFile:Bartgeier_Gypaetus_barbatus_front2_Richard_Bartz.jpg|Adult spreading wings\n</gallery>\n\n=== Physiology ===\nThe acid concentration of the bearded vulture stomach has been estimated to be of pH about 1. Large bones will be digested in about 24 hours, aided by slow mixing/churning of the stomach content. The high fat content of bone marrow makes the net energy value of bone almost as good as that of muscle, even if bone is less completely digested. A skeleton left on a mountain will dehydrate and become protected from bacterial degradation, and the bearded vulture can return to consume the remainder of a carcass even months after the soft parts have been consumed by other animals, larvae and bacteria.<ref name=\"acid\">{{cite journal\n| year= 1994 |journal=J. Raptor Res.|volume= 28|issue=2|pages=73\u201378\n| url = http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/jrr/v028n02/p00073-p00078.pdf | title=Bone Digestion and Intestinal Morphology of the Bearded Vulture\n| accessdate = 2011-07-24\n| last1= Houston|first1=D.C. |last2= Copsey|first2=J.A.}}</ref>\n\n== Behaviour ==\n===Diet and feeding===\n[[File:Gipeto adulto.jpg|thumb|A flying bearded vulture in [[Gran Paradiso National Park]], [[Italy]]]]\n[[File:Gypaetus Barbatus.jpg|thumb|Bearded vulture on the rocks in [[Gran Paradiso National Park]].]]\nLike other [[vulture]]s, it is a [[scavenger]], feeding mostly on the remains of [[Carrion|dead animals]]. The bearded vulture diet comprises mammals (93%), birds (6%) and reptiles (1%), with medium sized ungulates forming a large part of the diet.<ref name=\"Margalida et al 2009\"/>\nBearded vultures avoid remains of larger species (such as cows and horses) probably because of the variable cost/benefit ratios in handling efficiency, ingestion process and transportation of the remains.<ref name=\"Margalida et al 2009\"/>\nIt usually disdains the actual meat and lives on a diet that is typically 85\u201390% [[bone marrow]]. This is the only living bird species that specializes in feeding on marrow.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> The bearded vulture can swallow whole or bite through brittle bones up to the size of a lamb's femur<ref name=\"PBS-Bhutan\">\n{{cite web\n| title = Lammergeier Vulture\n| work= The Living Edens&nbsp;\u2014 Bhutan\n| publisher = PBS\n| url = https://www.pbs.org/edens/bhutan/a_lv.htm\n| accessdate = 2011-05-30\n}}\n</ref> and its powerful digestive system quickly dissolves even large pieces. The bearded vulture has learned to crack bones too large to be swallowed by carrying them in flight to a height of {{convert|50|-|150|m|ft|abbr=on}} above the ground and then dropping them onto rocks below, which smashes them into smaller pieces and exposes the nutritious marrow.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> They can fly with bones up to {{convert|10|cm|in|abbr=on}} in diameter and weighing over {{convert|4|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, or nearly equal to their own weight.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/>\n\nAfter dropping the large bones, the bearded vulture spirals or glides down to inspect them and may repeat the act if the bone is not sufficiently cracked.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> This learned skill requires extensive practice by immature birds and takes up to seven years to master.<ref name=\"BBC-BeardedVulture\">{{cite web| work = Wildlife Finder|title=Lammergeier (video, facts and news)| publisher = BBC| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/nature/species/Bearded_Vulture| accessdate = 2011-05-29}}</ref> Its old name of ''ossifrage'' (\"bone breaker\") relates to this habit. Less frequently, these birds have been observed trying to break bones (usually of a medium size) by hammering them with their bill directly into rocks while perched.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> During the breeding season they feed mainly on carrion. They prefer limbs of sheep and other small mammals and they carry the food to the nest, unlike other vultures which feed their young by regurgitation.<ref name=\"Margalida et al 2009\">{{cite journal |last1=Margalida |first1=Antoni |last2=Bertra |first2=Joan |last3=Heredia |first3=Rafael |title=Diet and food preferences of the endangered Bearded Vulture ''Gypaetus barbatus'': a basis for their conservation |journal=Ibis |date=23 March 2009 |volume=151 |issue=2 |pages=235\u2013243 |doi=10.1111/j.1474-919x.2008.00904.x }}</ref>\n\nLive prey is sometimes attacked by the bearded vulture, with perhaps greater regularity than any other vulture.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Among these, [[tortoise]]s seem to be especially favored depending on their local abundance. Tortoises preyed on may be nearly as heavy as the preying vulture. To kill tortoises, bearded vultures fly with them to some height and drop them to crack open the bulky reptiles' hard shells. Golden eagles have been observed to kill tortoises in the same way.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Other live animals, up to nearly their own size, have been observed to be predaciously seized and dropped in flight. Among these are [[rock hyrax]]es, [[hare]]s, [[marmot]]s and, in one case, a {{convert|62|cm|in|abbr=on}} long [[monitor lizard]].<ref name=RaptorsWorld/><ref name=\"PBS-Bhutan\" /> Larger animals have been known to be attacked by bearded vultures, including [[ibex]], [[Capra (genus)|''Capra'' goats]], [[Chamois]] and [[Steenbok]].<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> These animals have been killed by being surprised by the large birds and battered with wings until they fall off precipitous rocky edges to their deaths; although in some cases these may be accidental killings when both the vulture and the mammal surprise each other.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Many large animals killed by bearded vultures are unsteady young, or have appeared sickly or obviously injured.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Humans have been anecdotally reported to have been killed in the same way.  This is unconfirmed, however, and if it does happen, most biologists who have studied the birds generally agree it would be accidental on the part of the vulture.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Occasionally smaller ground-dwelling birds, such as [[partridge]]s and [[pigeon]]s, have been reported eaten, possibly either as fresh carrion (which is usually ignored by these birds) or killed with beating wings by the vulture.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> While foraging for bones or live prey while in flight, bearded vultures fly fairly low over the rocky ground, staying around {{convert|2|to|4|m|ft|abbr=on}} high.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Occasionally, breeding pairs may forage and hunt together.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> In the [[Ethiopian Highlands]], bearded vultures have adapted to living largely off human refuse.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/>\n\n===Breeding===\nThe bearded vulture occupies an enormous territory year-round. It may forage over two square kilometers each day. The breeding period is variable, being December through September in [[Eurasia]], November to June in the [[Indian subcontinent]], October to May in [[Ethiopia]], throughout the year in eastern Africa and May to January in southern Africa.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Although generally solitary, the bond between a breeding pair is often considerably close. Biparental monogamous care occurs in the bearded vulture.<ref name=\"Margalida et al 2000\">{{cite journal |last1=Margalida |first1=Antoni |last2=Bertran |first2=Joan |title=Breeding behaviour of the Bearded Vulture ''Gypaetus barbatus'': minimal sexual differences in parental activities |journal=Ibis |date=28 June 2008 |volume=142 |issue=2 |pages=225\u2013234 |doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.2000.tb04862.x }}</ref> In a few cases, [[polyandry]] has been recorded in the species.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> The territorial and breeding display between bearded vultures is often spectacular, involving the showing of talons, tumbling and spiralling while in solo flight. The large birds also regularly lock feet with each other and fall some distance through the sky with each other.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> In Europe the breeding pairs of bearded vultures are estimated to be 120.<ref name= Donazar>{{cite journal |last1=Donazar |first1=J. A. |last2=Hiraldo |first2=F. |last3=Bustamante |first3=J. |title=Factors Influencing Nest Site Selection, Breeding Density and Breeding Success in the Bearded Vulture (''Gypaetus barbatus'') |journal=Journal of Applied Ecology |date=1993 |volume=30 |issue=3 |pages=504\u2013514 |doi=10.2307/2404190 |jstor=2404190 |hdl=10261/47110 }}</ref> The mean productivity of the bearded vulture is 0.43\u00b10.28 fledgings/breeding pair/year and the breeding success averaged 0.56\u00b10.30 fledgings/pair with clutches/year.<ref name=\"Margalida et al 2003\">{{cite journal |last1=Margalida |first1=Antoni |last2=Garcia |first2=Diego |last3=Bertran |first3=Joan |last4=Heredia |first4=Rafael |title=Breeding biology and success of the Bearded Vulture ''Gypaetus barbatus'' in the eastern Pyrenees |journal=Ibis |date=27 March 2003 |volume=145 |issue=2 |pages=244\u2013252 |doi=10.1046/j.1474-919X.2003.00148.x }}</ref>\n\nThe nest is a massive pile of sticks, that goes from around {{convert|1|m|ft|abbr=on}} across and {{convert|69|cm|in|abbr=on}} deep when first constructed up to {{convert|2.5|m|ft|abbr=on}} across and {{convert|1|m|ft|abbr=on}} deep, with a covering of various animal matter from food, after repeated uses. The female usually lays a clutch of 1 to 2 eggs, though 3 have been recorded on rare occasions.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> which are incubated for 53 to 60 days. After hatching, the young spend 100 to 130 days in the nest before [[Fledge|fledging]]. The young may be dependent on the parents for up to 2 years, forcing the parents to nest in alternate years on a regular basis.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Typically, the bearded vulture nests in caves and on ledges and rock outcrops or caves on steep rock walls, so are very difficult for nest-predating mammals to access.<ref name=\"PBS-Bhutan\" /> Wild bearded vultures have a mean lifespan of 21.4 years,<ref name=\"CJBrown1997\">{{cite journal|last1=Brown|first1=C.J.|title=Population dynamics of the bearded vulture ''Gypaetus barbatus'' in southern Africa|journal=African Journal of Ecology|date=March 1997|volume=35|issue=1|pages=53\u201363|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2028.1997.048-89048.x}}</ref> but have been observed to live for up to at least 45 years in captivity.<ref name=\"RJAntor2007\">{{cite journal |last1=Antor |first1=Ram\u00f3n J. |last2=Margalida |first2=Antoni |last3=Frey |first3=Hans |last4=Heredia |first4=Rafael |last5=Lorente |first5=Luis |last6=Ses\u00e9 |first6=Jos\u00e9 Antonio |title=First Breeding Age in Captive and Wild Bearded Vultures |journal=Acta Ornithologica |date=July 2007 |volume=42 |issue=1 |pages=114\u2013118 |doi=10.3161/068.042.0106 }}</ref>\n<gallery>\nGypa\u00e8te barbu MHNT.jpg|''Gypaetus barbatus aureus'' egg \u2013 [[MHNT]]\nGypaetus barbatus hemachalanus MHNT.jpg|''Gypaetus barbatus hemachalanus'' egg \u2013 [[MHNT]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Reintroduction in the Alps==\nThe bearded vulture had a very poor reputation in early modern Europe, due in large part to tales of the birds stealing babies and livestock. The growing availability of firearms, combined with bounties offered for dead vultures, caused a sharp decline in the bearded vulture population around the Alps. By the beginning of the 20th century, they had completely disappeared from the Alpine regions.\n\nEfforts to reintroduce the bearded vulture began in earnest in the 1970s, in the French Alps. Zoologists Paul Geroudet and Gilbert Amigues attempted to release vultures that had been captured in Afghanistan, but this approach proved unsuccessful: it was too difficult to capture the vultures in the first place, and too many died in transport on their way to France. A second attempt was made in 1987, using a technique called \"hacking,\" by which young individuals (from 90\u2013100 days) from zoological parks would be taken from the nest and placed in a protected area in the Alps. As they were still unable to fly at that age, the chicks were hand-fed by humans until the birds learned to fly and were able to reach food without human assistance. This method has proven more successful, with over 200 birds released in the Alps from 1987 to 2015, and a bearded vulture population has reestablished itself in the Alps.<ref>http://gypaetebarbu.ch/project/reintroduction, 31.5.2018, Pro Gypa\u00e8te</ref>\n\n== Threats and conservation status ==\n[[File:Lammergeier with boy, Kabul, 1973.JPG|thumb|upright|Boy with live bearded vulture, [[Kabul]]]]\nThe bearded vulture is one of the most endangered European bird species as over the last century its abundance and breeding range have drastically declined.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bretagnolle |first1=Vincent |last2=Inchausti |first2=Pablo |last3=Seguin |first3=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois |last4=Thibault |first4=Jean-Claude |title=Evaluation of the extinction risk and of conservation alternatives for a very small insular population: the bearded vulture ''Gypaetus barbatus'' in Corsica |journal=Biological Conservation |date=November 2004 |volume=120 |issue=1 |pages=19\u201330 |doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2004.01.023 }}</ref> It naturally occurs at low densities, with anywhere from a dozen to 500 pairs now being found in each mountain range in Eurasia where the species breeds. The species is most common in [[Ethiopia]], where an estimated 1,400 to 2,200 are believed to breed.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> Relatively large, healthy numbers seem to occur in some parts of the Himalayas as well. It was largely wiped out in Europe, and by the beginning of the 20th century the only substantial population was in the Spanish and French Pyrenees. Since then, it has been successfully reintroduced to the [[Swiss]] and [[Italy|Italian]] Alps, from where they have spread over into [[France]].<ref name=RaptorsWorld/> They have also declined somewhat in parts of Asia and Africa, though less severely than in Europe.<ref name=RaptorsWorld/>\n\nMany raptor species were shielded from anthropogenic influences in previously underdeveloped areas therefore they are greatly impacted as the human population rises and infrastructure increases in underdeveloped areas. The increase in human population and infrastructure results in the declines of the bearded vulture populations today. The increase of infrastructure includes the building of houses, roads and power lines and a major issue with infrastructure and bird species populations is the collision with power lines.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal|journal = PLOS ONE| year=2014| volume=9| issue=12| pages=e114920| title=Differential Range Use between Age Classes of Southern African Bearded Vultures ''Gypaetus barbatus''| author1=Kruger, Sonja| author2=Reid, Timothy| author3=Amar, Arjun|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0114920| pmid=25551614| pmc=4281122| bibcode=2014PLoSO...9k4920K}}</ref> The declines of the bearded vulture populations have been documented throughout their range resulting from a decrease in habitat space, fatal collisions with energy infrastructure, reduced food availability, poisons left out for carnivores and direct persecution in the form of Trophy Hunting.<ref name=\"howstuffworks\">{{cite web\n| title = Lammergeier\n| date = 2008-04-22\n| publisher = Discovery Communications\n| work = howstuffworks.com\n| url = http://animals.howstuffworks.com/birds/lammergeier-info.htm\n| accessdate = 2011-05-29| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110712230041/http://animals.howstuffworks.com/birds/lammergeier-info.htm| archivedate= 12 July 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThis species is currently listed as Near Threatened by the IUCN Red List last accessed on 1 October 2016, the population continues to decline as the distribution ranges of this species continues to decline due to human development.\n\n== Conservation action ==\n\nThere have been mitigation plans that have been established to reduce the population declines in bearded vulture populations. One of these plans includes the South African Biodiversity Management Plan that has been ratified by the government to stop the population decline in the short term. Actions that have been implemented include the mitigation of existing and proposed energy structures to prevent collision risks, the improved management of supplementary feeding sites as well to reduce the populations from being exposed to human persecution and poisoning accidents and to also have outreach programmes that are aimed as reducing poisoning incidents.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n== Etymology ==\nThis species was first described by [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]] in his ''[[Systema naturae]]'' in 1758 as ''Vultur barbatus''.<ref name=\"Linnaeus1758\">\n{{cite book\n| last = Linnaeus\n| first = Carolus\n| authorlink =Carl Linnaeus| year = 1758\n| title = Systema naturae per regna tria naturae, secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis. Tomus I. Editio decima, reformata\n| volume = v.1\n| page = 87\n| publisher = Holmiae. (Laurentii Salvii)\n| language = Latin\n|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/726992\n| quote = V. albidus, dorso fusco, jugulo barbato, rostro incarnato, capite linea nigra cincto.\n}}</ref> The present scientific name means \"bearded vulture-eagle\".\n\nThe name ''lammergeyer'' originates from [[German language|German]] ''{{lang|de|L\u00e4mmergeier}}'', which means \"lamb-vulture\". The name stems from the belief that it attacked [[Domestic sheep|lambs]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Everett|first=Mike|year=2008|title=Lammergeiers and lambs|journal=British Birds|volume= 101 |issue=4|page= 215}}</ref>\n\n== In culture ==\n<!-- Commented out: [[File:Iran Air logo.svg|thumb|Homa bird in the logo of [[Iran Air]]]] -->\nThe bearded vulture is considered a threatened species in [[Iran]]. Iranian mythology considers the rare bearded vulture ([[Persian language|Persian]]: \u0647\u0645\u0627, 'Homa') the symbol of luck and happiness. It was believed that if the shadow of a ''[[Huma bird|Homa]]'' fell on one, he would rise to sovereignty<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pollard |first1=J. R. T. |title=The Lammergeyer Comparative Descriptions in Aristotle and Pliny |journal=Greece and Rome |date=5 January 2009 |volume=16 |issue=46 |pages=23\u201328 |doi=10.1017/s0017383500009311}}</ref> and anyone shooting the bird would die in forty days. The habit of eating bones and apparently not killing living animals was noted by [[Saadi Shirazi|Sa'di]] in [[Gulistan (book)|Gulistan]] published in 1258 and Emperor Jahangir had the crop examined in 1625 to find that it was filled with bones.<ref>{{cite journal| title= Note on the Huma or Lammergeyer| url=https://archive.org/stream/mobot31753003193114#page/532/mode/1up | pages=532\u2013533| journal=Journal of the Asiatic Society of Bengal| year=1906| volume=2| issue=10| author=Phillott, D.C.|authorlink=Douglas Craven Phillott}}</ref>\n\nThe ancient [[Greeks]] used [[Ornithomancy|ornithomancer]]s to guide their political decisions: bearded vultures, or ossifragae were one of the few species of birds that could yield valid signs to these soothsayers.\n\nThe [[Greece|Greek]] playwright [[Aeschylus]] was said to have been killed in 456 or 455 BC by a [[tortoise]] dropped by an eagle who mistook his bald head for a stone \u2013 if this incident did occur, the bearded vulture is a likely candidate for the \"eagle\".\n\nIn the [[Bible]]/[[Torah]], the bearded vulture, as the ossifrage, is among the birds forbidden to be eaten ([[Leviticus]] 11:13).\n\nMore recently, in 1944, [[Shimon Peres]] (called Shimon Persky at the time) and [[David Ben-Gurion]] found a nest of bearded vultures in the [[Negev]] desert. The bird is called ''{{lang|he-Latn|peres}}'' in [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], and Shimon Persky liked it so much he adopted it as his [[surname]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Marche\n  | first = Stephen\n  | date = 2008-06-13\n  | title = Flight of Fancy\n  | journal = The New Republic\n  | url = http://www.tnr.com/article/politics/flight-fancy\n  | accessdate = 2011-05-31}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://slideblast.com/-in-memory-of-shimon-peres_59cd3bb31723dd5beeb47f52.html\n |title=In Memory of Israel's 9th President, Shimon Peres, 'The National Bird'\n |last=Leshem\n |first=Yossi\n |date=\n |website=\n |publisher=\n |access-date=2018-06-05\n |quote= }}</ref>\n\nRobot bearded vultures appear in some science fiction literature, including the first volume of the [[Viriconium]] series by M. John Harrison and [[Feersum Endjinn]] by [[Iain Banks|Iain M. Banks]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Gypaetus barbatus}}\n{{Wikispecies|Gypaetus barbatus}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101126140941/http://www.arkive.org/lammergeier/gypaetus-barbatus/video-08.html Video of lammergeier shattering bones into smaller pieces on which it then feeds] at ARKive\n* [http://sabap2.adu.org.za/docs/sabap1/119.pdf Species text] in The Atlas of Southern African Birds\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120621212539/http://www.vulture-territory.com/bearded.html Facts and Characteristics: Bearded Vulture] at Vulture Territory \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121029071234/http://www.iberianature.com/material/lammergeyer.html The Lammergeier in Spain]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20190103175505/http://www.cam3001.com/SEITEN/GypaetusFr.html Cine and photo work about the Bearded Vulture in the Alps]\n* [http://wwf.panda.org/about_our_earth/species/profiles/birds/bearded_vulture/ diet information]\n* [http://www.abcc-am.org/bearded-vulture.html Bearded Vulture in Armenia, Armenian Bird Census Council. 2017.]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/BBCOne/videos/bearded-vulture-the-snow-wolf-a-winters-tale/234415154152599/ Bone-eating vulture and a snow wolf]\n*{{cite journal |last1=Robert |first1=Isabelle |last2=Vigne |first2=Jean-Denis |title=The Bearded Vulture (''Gypaetus barbatus'') as an Accumulator of Archaeological Bones. Late Glacial Assemblages and Present-day Reference Data in Corsica (Western Mediterranean) |journal=Journal of Archaeological Science |date=July 2002 |volume=29 |issue=7 |pages=763\u2013777 |doi=10.1006/jasc.2001.0778 }}\n\n{{Vulture}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q126167}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:vulture, bearded}}\n[[Category:Old World vultures|bearded vulture]]\n[[Category:Birds of prey of Africa]]\n[[Category:Birds of Europe]]\n[[Category:Birds of Tibet]]\n[[Category:Birds of Western Asia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1758|bearded vulture]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing, replaced: in  in  \u2192  in,typo(s) fixed: medium sized \u2192 medium-sized", "url_page": "//en